<1ST_LINE>u p AM-WashingtonCaucuses     03-15 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Washington Caucuses,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Keeps Strong Lead over Jackson in Washington Democratic
Caucuses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis held a
strong lead over Jesse Jackson as Washington state party officials
released results Tuesday from last week's Democratic presidential
precinct caucuses.
   With about 68 percent of the precincts reporting the results of
last Tuesday's balloting, Dukakis had 45 percent, Jackson 35
percent, and 14 percent were uncommitted.
   All the other candidates were well off the pace, with Illinois
Sen. Paul Simon a weak fourth at 4 percent, Tennessee Sen. Albert
Gore Jr. 2 percent and Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri 1 percent.
   The Democratic Party made no effort to collect results statewide
on caucus night, gathering precinct returns slowly by mail instead.
   Republicans say it will be at least another week before county
chairmen submit the names of GOP delegates elected in last week's
precinct caucuses.
   The National Election Service reported last week that, with 71
percent of the Republican precincts reporting, former television
evangelist Pat Robertson led with 39 percent. Sen. Bob Dole of
Kansas finished second with 26 percent and Vice President George
Bush got 24 percent.
</TEXT>
