<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoxOffice     03-15 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Box Office,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Good Morning, Vietnam' Ties Box Office Record</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Good Morning, Vietnam'' was moviegoers'
favorite for the the ninth-straight weekend, tying it with
``Crocodile Dundee'' for the longest consecutive time at the top.
   Second in last weekend's box office survey was ``Vice Versa,''
featuring a Judge Reinhold transformation into a prepubescent kid,
followed by ``Masquerade'' in third and ``Off Limits'' fourth.
   All 10 top grossing films combined took in about $30 million,
with ``Good Morning, Vietnam'' ringing up a mere $4.36 million
during the pre-Easter vacation box office doldrums.
   ``It's another down week,'' said John Krier of Exhibitor
Relations Co., which surveys the studios' weekly performance at the
box office. ``It looks like we're marking time until Easter.''
   For the Easter break, the studios are releasing the animated
feature ``The Fox and the Hounds,'' Alan Alda's ``A New Life,''
Matthew Broderick's ``Biloxi Blues'' and Anthony Michael Hall's
``Johnny B. Goode.''
   In addition to ``Good Morning, Vietnam,'' the Disney Studios had
two other pictures in the top 10. ``Three Men and a Baby'' was
seventh 7 after 15 weeks in release and ``Shoot to Kill'' ninth.
   The lure of romance between Rob Lowe and Meg Tilly gave
``Masquerade'' a debut weekend gross of $3.5 million while the
Willem Dafoe-Gregory Hines cop thriller ``Off Limits'' earned $2.8
million.
   In fifth was Cher's critically-acclaimed ``Moonstruck,'' which
won her a Golden Globe trophy and an Oscar nomination, followed by
Harrison Ford's ``Frantic'' in sixth and ``Three Men and a Baby''
in seventh.
   ``Moving,'' starring Richard Pryor as a New York engineer forced
to relocate his family to Boise, Idaho, earned more than $2.4
million to place eighth, followed by ``Shoot to Kill.''
   In 10th place was ``Switching Channels,'' a broadcast version of
the venerable newsroom comedy ``The Front Page.'' It earned $1.9
million in its second week.
   Here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations Co., with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross, number of weeks in
release and estimated production costs.
   1. ``Good Morning, Vietnam,'' Disney-Touchstone, $4.36 million,
1,579 screens, $2,767 per screen, $91.5 million, 11 weeks, $21
million.
   2. ``Vice Versa,'' Columbia, $4.05 million, 1,225 screens,
$3,306 per screen, $4.05 million, one week, n-a.
   3. ``Masquerade,'' MGM-UA, $3.5 million, 1,030 screens, $3,398
per screen, $3.5 million, one week, n-a.
   4. ``Off Limits,'' 20th Century Fox, $2.79 million, 1,366
screens, $2,047 per screen, $2.79 million, one week, n-a.
   5. ``Moonstruck,'' MGM-UA, $2.66 million, 1,155 screens, $2,309
per screen, $49.37 million, 12 weeks, $17 million.
   6. ``Frantic,'' Warner Bros., $2.60 million, 1,054 screens,
$2,469 per screen, $13.2 million, two weeks, $20 million.
   7. ``Three Men And A Baby,'' Disney-Touchstone, $2.55 million,
1,348 screens, $1,893 per screen, $147.6 million, 15 weeks, $18
million.
   8. ``Moving,'' Warner Bros., $2.4 million, 1,404 screens, $1,732
per screen, $7.49 million, two weeks, n-a.
   9. ``Shoot to Kill,'' Disney-Touchstone, $2 million, 1,037
screens, $1,956 per screen, $24.2 million, four weeks, $18 million.
   10. ``Switching Channels,'' Tri-Star, $1.94 million, 971
screens, $2,002 per screen, $5.8 million, two weeks, n-a.
</TEXT>
