<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Networks-Primary     03-15 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Networks-Primary,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Networks Plan Election Specials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS and NBC said they will broadcast half-hour
news specials on Illinois primary election returns tonight at 11:30
p.m. EST.
   ABC planned no full-length election special but will devote the
first six minutes of its ``Nightline'' program at 11:30 p.m. to
election returns, ABC said.
   Cable News Network said it will provide periodic reports and a
half-hour program on election returns at 1 a.m. Wednesday.
   ABC, NBC and CBS also were broadcasting brief special reports on
voting results.
   NBC planned five-minute news briefs at 8:55 p.m. and 9:55 p.m.
and its half-hour special at 11:30 p.m., with ``NBC Nightly News''
anchorman Tom Brokaw as host, said spokeswoman Mary Lou O'Callaghan.
   CBS planned one prime-time news brief, with the time yet to be
set, and an 11:30 p.m. special program, with ``CBS Evening News''
anchorman Dan Rather as host, said Donna Dees, spokeswoman for the
network.
   CNN will air five- to seven-minute reports at every half hour
from 8 p.m. to 10:30 p.m. and will devote its ``Inside Politics''
program at 1 a.m. to election returns, said spokeswoman Kitsie
Bassett.
</TEXT>
