<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 0028EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Colombia-Elections     03-15 0777</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Colombia-Elections,0806</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rich Still Run Colombia, But Left Makes Tiny Inroads</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayoral elections in Colombia have left
a small crack in the political fortress of the upper class, the
power behind this Latin American country since it won independence
from Spain in 1819.
   The elections on Sunday marked the first time that mayors had
been elected in Colombia. Previously, they were appointed by
governors, who were appointed by the president.
   And the president always came from the Liberal or the
Conservative parties that are manipulated by the rich.
   But a leftist coalition, the Patriotic Union party, won at least
14 of l,008 mayoral posts in Sunday's election, which in some cases
brought people from the poorer classes closer to the seat of power
in local politics.
   The money and power of the traditional parties ruled out in most
cases, such as in Bogota where Andres Pastrana, the son of former
president Misael Pastrana, was elected mayor on the Conservative
ticket.
   The Liberal Party of President Virgilio Barco won 430 of the
mayoral races, and the Conservative party won 402 mayoral posts.
Coalition candidates won 24 of the mayoral elections.
   Other results may not be known for a week because of the
remoteness of many towns.
   The showing by the new Patriotic Union was small. But the
results were surprising given that the party was organized just
three years ago.
   The leftist coalition also had to survive a wave of
assassinations by right-wing death squads that killed 520 of the
members of the party, including its president, Jaime Pardo.
   The Patriotic Union also had to confront a colonial attitude of
patronage.
   Entire towns and areas traditionally adhere to one of the two
traditional parties. Until recently, people did not join political
parties. They were born into them.
   It is common knowledge that failure of a peasant to support the
party controlling an area means virtual economic suicide. A loan
application at the local bank for buying seed will be rejected. A
worker will be turned away when looking for a job at a big hacienda.
   Colombians still call the rich La Rosca, a kind of intertwined
pastry. The term refers to a loose intertwining of influential
people _ politicians, businessmen, landowners, doctors and lawyers
_ who control the lives of the poor.
   Nowhere are the poor more aware of La Rosca than in small towns,
where the wealthy own most of the rural land.
   A 1970 government study showed that 4.3 percent of the people in
Colombia owned 68 percent of the land. Ten percent of the farms
held 80 percent of total farmland. Those figures probably have not
changed much.
   The government's concession to hold mayoral elections is an
indication that Colombia may be heading toward true democracy.
   The country has a long history of violence, perpetuated largely
by a political elite that refused to reform partisan traditions.
   For example, elements of the Liberal party resisted social
changes in 1948. A charasmatic Liberal leader, Jorge Elicer Gaitan,
broke away from the party and ran as an independent. Gaitan was
assassinated shortly afterward.
   People saw their only hope of bettering their lives cut down,
and the frustration exploded into the worst disturbances ever seen
in Colombia.
   That period, known simply as The Violence, has had an impact
upon Colombian politics ever since.
   So when former president Belisario Betancur offered peace talks
to the country's leftist guerrillas in 1984, most people approved.
Perhaps they recognized that the need for social changes were again
putting pressure on the system.
   The guerrillas said in 1985 they wanted a government more
responsive to the poor people. For starters, they said they wanted
the election of mayors.
   Betancur agreed, and the congress approved a constitutional
amendement to allow the first election in 1988.
   The peace talks collapsed last year, but the government went
ahead with the elections.
   The army says there are about 5,000 leftist guerrillas in
Colombia. The rebels claim they have close to 20,000 combatants.
Whatever the number, their forces are growing each year.
   Ten years ago the army said there were only about 2,500
guerrillas.
   The growth of guerrilla forces and the possibility of another
upheaval probably will depend greatly on whether the wealthy will
concede to such programs as land reform, housing programs and
building more schools and hospitals in rural areas.
   The government's attitude toward social change continues to be
cautious. The election of mayors is a beginning, but not a solution.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Wells is bureau chief for The Associated
Press in Colombia.
</TEXT>
