<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SovietEmigre     03-15 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Emigre,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Svoiet Writer Finds New Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WOONSOCKET, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet dissident whose pleas for an
exit visa were ignored until he stepped up his reporting of human
rights abuses has found a new home in the West.
   Theodore Kizelov, 43, arrived in Rhode Island last Tuesday after
a journey that led from Sverdlovsk, a town in the Ural Mountains,
through Vienna and Rome to the United States.
   The Tolstoy Foundation, an international, non-profit
organization that helps resettle political refugees, found him an
apartment and gave him enough money to live on for a month, said
Maureen Dalpe of the Woonsocket chapter.
   Kizelov, who had never been outside the Soviet Union before his
expulsion, learned English by listening to British radio broadcasts
and should have little trouble finding a job, Ms. Dalpe said.
   ``I will start with any job available,'' said Kizelov, ``even
washing dishes in a restaurant.''
   Kizelov had been a dissident since the late 1970s, when he wrote
what he calls his first ``open letter'' opposing the government _ a
statement against the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan. He sent the
letter to the Moscow Monitor and Helsinki Group, which published it
outside the Soviet Union.
   ``I didn't begin to hide until 1983,'' Kizelov said, because in
general, it is safe to risk criticizing the Soviet government
without reprisals for three years or so.
   But the KGB patrols that began following him that year did not
deter him.
   To make himself a difficult target, Kizelov began moving from
city to city. He held odd jobs, and friends helped with money.
Meanwhile, he continued to gather information about Soviet human
rights violations, sending the information to groups interested in
publishing it.
   Last fall, Kizelov found himself working as a theater decorator
in Sverdlovsk, a town whose former political boss, Boris Yeltsin,
had been promoted to serve as the Communist Party's first secretary
of Moscow.
   Yeltsin was drummed out of office by party officials last
November after delivering a speech that reportedly rankled powerful
officials in the Communist Party, including General Secretary
Mikhail Gorbachev.
   Officials in Sverdlovsk, however, took a dim view of one of
their favorite sons being kicked out of office, and began
demonstrating in public. Kizelov wrote about it.
   He sent his 3,000-word report on the demonstrations and a cover
letter to Sergei Grigoryants, editor of a Moscow-based underground
magazine called Glasnost. The sporadically-published magazine takes
its cue from Gorbachev's policy of ``openness'' in public affairs.
   But Grigoryants never received the report. Kizelov assumes it
was intercepted by Soviet police. A short while after sending it,
he received an ``invitation'' to report to the emigration office to
talk about his desire to leave the Soviet Union.
   ``They say nothing until I was involved in the demonstrations,''
said Kizelov.
   While Americans seem to be cautiously optimistic about the
policy of glasnost, Kizelov calls it a ``mask.'' He says Soviet
society is intolerant of anything but the official line and there
is no such thing as freedom of speech.
   ``I don't like the socialist way of life in principle,'' said
Kizelov. ``In my opinion, it is the wrong way of development.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
