<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 0124EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan 2ndLd-Writethru a0688 03-15 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0688,0790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pressure Mounts on Pakistan To Sign Peace Pact</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT 2 grafs after 4th graf pvs, Both sides ... UPDATING
with latest Soviet comment. Picks up 5th graf pvs, Pakistan has ..
. editing 11th graf pvs, In Belgrade ... to conform.
^By MOHAMMAD AFTAB</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pressure mounted Monday on Pakistan to sign an
Afghan settlement aimed at securing the withdrawal of an estimated
115,000 Soviet troops and end nine years of fighting in Afghanistan.
   Sources close to the talks said the Pakistani chief
representative, acting Foreign Minister Zain Noorani, received a
message from the Kremlin calling upon him to sign the documents
without further delay.
   The chief Afghan negotiator, Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil,
scheduled a news conference for Tuesday, the day Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev named as a target date for the conclusion of
the nearly 6-year-old talks. Gorbachev said Moscow will bring home
its troops starting May 15 if the settlement is signed Tuesday.
   Both sides have said they do not consider March 15 a rigid
deadline. Sources close to the talks, who declined to be
identified, said that apart from pressing for the formation of an
interim government, Pakistan also felt that there are still some
loose ends to be sorted out in the agreements that make up the
peace package.
   The Soviet deputy foreign minister, Vadim Loginov, told a news
conference in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, on Monday that Moscow is still
``optimistic'' it can pull its troops out, but he acknowledged the
Geneva talks are encountering difficulties.
   ``Nobody has set a definite deadline,'' he said. ``All that has
been said is that if by the 15th (of March), the last of the four
agreements has been signed, then we will begin to withdraw our
forces.''
   Pakistan has been insisting that the formation of a transitional
government in Afghanistan be linked to the settlement.
   Both Kabul and Moscow have adamantly rejected that condition.
   Pakistan argues that only a broad-based government can guarantee
implementation of the peace accords and the safe return of five
million Afghan refugees in Pakistan and Iran.
   ``We are ready to sign the moment our concerns are removed,''
Noorani told reporters as his delegation left an afternoon meeting
with U.N. mediator Diego Cordovez.
   Before an earlier meeting in the morning, Noorani had said,
without elaborating, Pakistan would ``announce something today.''
But there was no such announcement as the talks were adjourned
until Tuesday.
   In Belgrade, where he was on a state visit, Gorbachev was asked
by a reporter if there was progress at the Geneva talks. With a
smile, he said, ``There is,'' and ``There will be,'' but did not
elaborate.
   Najib, president of Afghanistan's pro-Soviet government, accused
Pakistan Monday of using tricks to block the final agreement.
   ``It can be said candidly that that people who resort to ruses
and who don't want the document of the Geneva talks to be signed
are actually enemies of the refugees,'' Najib was quoted as saying
in an interview with the Afghan news agency Bakhtar excerpted by
Tass, the official Soviet news agency.
   Najib noted that Pakistan once said the only issue between the
two countries was an acceptable timetable for Soviet withdrawal. He
charged that Pakistan raised questions about an interim government
to delay the agreement.
   Najib said the rebels are interested in the millions of Afghan
refugees only as a ``reserve of military force to be used as cannon
fodder.''
   Noorani, meanwhile, was reported to be in constant touch with
his capital, Islamabad, where the cabinet held its third lengthy
meeting in two days, presumably to weigh its next step. The Swiss
Radio reported earlier that Prime Minister Mohammad Khan Junejo had
said a decision on whether Pakistan would sign the settlement would
be made Monday.
   In another development, a spokesman for the fragile seven-party
alliance of the anti-Soviet guerrillas, revealed that Moscow had
rejected again any direct negotiations with the insurgents.
   The spokesman, Gulbadin Hekmatyar, who also leads the largest
and most radical group in the alliance, said that no guerrilla
delegation would be sent to Geneva unless the Soviets drop their
opposition.
   Hekmatyar, the leader of the Hezb-i-islami group, is widely
believed to be the next chief of the seven-party alliance following
the resignation of Yunis Khalis for health reasons.
   Unconfirmed reports indicated the 69-year-old Khalis quit in
protest over plans to send a guerrilla delegation to the Geneva
talks.
   Hekmatyar said his appointment as leader of the alliance may be
announced Tuesday.
   ``But if there is a majority opposing my leadership, then I will
not be chosen,'' he added, speaking in Pakistan.
</TEXT>
