<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel Bjt   03-15 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, Bjt,0700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Imposes Curfew On 600,000 Palestinians In Gaza Strip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel imposed a nightly curfew on more than
600,000 Arabs in the entire Gaza Strip and reportedly sealed off
entrances to the occupied territory after about 300 Arab policemen
in Gaza said they would resign.
   The army on Monday also closed one of the West Bank's largest
fruit and vegetable markets as Israel tightened economic sanctions
in the occupied lands.
   Elsewhere in the West Bank, Israeli soldiers on Monday shot and
wounded 11 Palestinians, hospital officials said. A 3-year-old girl
was shot in the eye with a rubber bullet, and five Israelis were
injured by stones thrown by Arabs.
   Israel radio said the 300 Arab policemen in the Gaza Strip
announced Monday they would resign. They joined 450 officers in the
occupied lands who turned in their badges earlier following orders
of PLO-inspired underground leaflets.
   The curfew in Gaza, announced Monday, was a reaction to the
resignations, the radio said. The 10 p.m. to 3 a.m. curfew also was
designed to prevent ``the entrance of violent instigators ... and
of written instigation material,'' it said. The army said the
curfew was to prevent late night demonstrations.
   The curfew over the entire Gaza Strip was imposed for the first
time since Arab unrest started on Dec. 8. It forces the residents
to stay in their homes while entrances to Gaza are sealed off by
the army, the radio said.
   An army spokesman said the curfew would be imposed until further
notice.
   At the Erez checkpoint at the entrance to Gaza, AP photographer
Max Nash on Monday saw 15 to 20 Arab trucks and taxis prevented by
the army from entering.
   He said soldiers would let in army vehicles and cars belonging
to Jewish settlers who live in Gaza. Other Israelis and journalists
were not permitted to drive in. ``Where would we sleep? We want to
enter, all our families are inside,'' an Arab worker stopped at
Erez told Israel radio.
   The situation in Gaza's refugee camps was not immediately clear.
On Sunday night, the army cut electricity and telephone lines to
41,000 people in the Beach Camp, an Arab reporter said.
   Israeli authorities acknowledged that some policemen in the Gaza
Strip quit but gave no figures. About 850 Arab policemen work in
the occupied territories.
   The police control crime and direct traffic, but they are not
used to quell Arab rioting in the occupied lands.
   ``It is clear their resignations were not handed in freely but
because they fear for their lives,'' Gaza police commander Shimon
Levy said on Israel radio.
   Graffiti on the walls in Gaza City called for the resignation of
the Israeli-appointed mayor and city council, Israel Television
said.
   In response to the PLO-backed unrest, Israel stepped up economic
sanctions. Shipment of gasoline and other fuel to service stations
in the West Bank was banned as of Sunday, and a regional fruit and
vegetable market was closed on Monday in Jericho, 20 miles
northwest of Jerusalem.
   Arab merchants said 70 trucks carrying produce were turned away
Monday. In addition, the army ordered Jericho shop owners to close
during the morning hours when PLO leaflets said shops should be
open. Israel Television said the Arab merchants responded with a
total commercial strike.
   The economic test of wills continued on Monday in Gaza City,
where slogans painted in the red, green, white and black colors of
the outlawed Palestinian flag called for a two-day general strike
starting today.
   Protests were reported on Monday in Jenin and the nearby West
Bank village of Yamoun, where troops using live ammunition shot and
wounded 11 people, hospital officials said. According to United
Nations figures, at least 91 Palestinians have been killed since
anti-Israeli rioting began Dec. 8.
   Witnesses said Jewish settlers on Monday drove through the West
Bank town of Ramallah and nearby Al Amari refugee camp, honking
their horns. Witnesses said Palestinians then held a similar car
demonstration, during which soldiers shot 3-year-old Rasha Yussef
Said in the eye with a rubber bullet.
</TEXT>
