<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ATVSettlement     03-15 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-ATV Settlement,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New ATV Settlement Stresses Advertising, Safety Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advertising for all-terrain vehicles will
begin stressing safety under a new agreement that also calls on
makers of the off-road vehicles to set up new training programs and
limit ATV sales.
   The government on Monday disclosed the new settlement, which
could replace a preliminary agreement announced in December.
   The recreational vehicles have grown sharply in popularity in
recent years, with more than 2 million currently believed to be in
use.
   At the same time accidents have increased markedly, with more
than 900 fatalities reported in the last five years, as well as
300,000 injuries, according to information collected by the
Consumer Product Safety Commission.
   That led to a government safety investigation and the new
agreement by the commission, the Justice Department, and the five
manufacturers of the machines: Honda, Yamaha, Kawasaki, Suzuki and
Polaris Industries.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell will hold a hearing on the
settlement April 18 and could order it into effect immediately. It
would replace the preliminary agreement between the government and
the manufacturers announced on Dec. 30.
   Safety Commission Chairman Terrence M. Scanlon said through a
spokesman that the settlement is the biggest safety accomplishment
in the history of his agency.
   Commission general counsel James V. Lacy said the settlement
will continue the ban on sales of new three-wheeled ATVs and that
manufacturers have agreed to buy back any of the three-wheel
versions remaining in dealer inventories.
   The more stable four-wheel ATVs will still be sold, he said, but
marketing of the full-size versions with engines of 90 cubic
centimeters and over will be limited to riders aged 16 and over.
Smaller machines will be allowed to be sold for riders ages 12 to
16, he said.
   The commission vote was 2-1, with Scanlon and commissioner Carol
Dawson in favor and commissioner Anne Graham dissenting. Graham,
who also voted against the preliminary settlement in December, said
in a statement that the settlement should have allowed ATV owners
to obtain refunds.
   ``Without the refund, consumers are not obtaining the remedies
necessary given the nature and severity of the hazards presented by
ATVs,'' she said.
   The new 150-page settlement is much more detailed than the one
announced in December, which drew criticism from Congress and
consumer groups as not being extensive enough. Some consumer groups
have said all the vehicles should be recalled because of safety
problems.
   Lacy said the settlement calls for the manufacturers to spend
between $8.4 million and $8.6 million on advertising starting in
the fall.
   The ads will stress the inherent safety risks of the vehicles,
Lacy said, and will be placed in a variety of media. Included, he
said, would be advertising on such broadcasts as the World Series,
CBS Evening News and Monday Night Football.
   In addition the manufacturers have agreed to set up a national
headquarters to develop safety and training programs for riders,
and to provide hands-on training for all new purchasers and for all
consumers who bought the machines since Dec. 30, 1986.
   Buyers will be offered incentives such as $50 in cash, a $100
savings bond or merchandise certificates to induce them to take the
training programs, Lacy said.
   Other provisions of the agreement, he said, include:
   _New warning labels on the machines being sold, plus mailings
providing these labels for all current owners for whom the
manufacturers have addresses.
   _The hands-on training programs for new buyers will include
their immediate families also.
   _Development of new owners manuals with added safety information.
   _Establishment of a safety hotline for consumers to get
information and development of safety-related videos to be made
available at dealer showrooms.
   _Elimination of the safety verification form that had been
required as part of the earlier settlement.
   This form, in which a buyer acknowledges knowing of the hazards
of the machines, had been criticized by consumer groups, who said
it could be used to protect the manufacturers in case of lawsuits
stemming from accidents.
</TEXT>
