<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Economy     03-15 0710</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Economy,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Revolt Shifts Gears: A New Emphasis on Economy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The confrontation in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip has increasingly become an economic test of wills
between Israeli occupation authorities and Palestinians.
   Underground Palestinian leaders have persuaded many merchants
and ordinary citizens to stop paying taxes and have enforced
repeated strikes, keeping at home a large part of the 110,000
laborers who work in Israel.
   The measures are designed to make Israel bear more of the
economic burden for occupation, which Arab activists say will give
impetus to Israel's withdrawal. Israel has adopted increasingly
tough economic sanctions, some of which are designed to put the
squeeze on the Arab middle class.
   The army imposed an indefinite ban on trucks taking gasoline to
the West Bank's 50 service stations. The move crippled public and
private transport.
   Qabatiyeh, a West Bank village of several thousand people, was
banned from exporting its quarried rock to Jordan and visitors from
abroad will not be allowed to visit the village, Israeli officials
said.
   The move was punishment for the lynching of an alleged
collaborator who was hung from an electricty pole after he fired
into a crowd advancing on his home and fatally wounded a child.
   In Jericho, the army closed a regional produce market and
ordered shops to close during morning hours, when PLO leaflets said
the shops should be open.
   ``The military government is trying to tell the people here who
is boss. They want to hurt the people economically. I think they
intend to try to break the strike this way,'' said Saeb Erakat, a
political science professor at Al Najah University.
   Israeli authorities have selectively used other measures as
well, such as cutting off electricity to areas placed under curfew.
   Israeli officials say they hope such steps will encourage
moderates to put pressure on Palestinian militants, although there
is no sign that such measures are having the desired effect.
   ``Agitators on the Arab side want to disconnect the population
as much as possible from any connection with Israel,'' said a
senior official in the military administration of the occupied
territories.
   He said the tax rebellion had minimal impact in January and
February, leading to a 10 percent decline in revenues, or about
$200,000 a month.
   But he said collections were expected to be far lower in March
and that road repairs, garbage collection and other services in the
occupied territories could suffer if there was not enough income to
fund the $239 million budget of the army-run Civil Administration.
   To counter the tax boycott, authorities required Arabs to obtain
a certificate saying they paid their taxes before getting
import-export licenses, driver's permits and other documents.
   Israel also lowered the amount of money Palestinians could bring
from abroad without permission from $5,000 to $1,200.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said more
economic sanctions were being considered to quell the revolt, which
began Dec. 8. and has resulted in the death of more than 90 Arabs.
He declined to elaborate.
   But Arieh Shalev, former head of the army-run military
government in 1974-76, said it might be necessary to stop Arabs
from working in Israel or using the bridges to trade with Jordan.
   ``Violence has peaked, in my opinion, but it will continue and
it's doubtful whether it will stop without taking brutal (economic)
measures,'' Shalev said on Israel radio.
   Ephraim Kleiman, an economics professor at Hebrew University,
said Israel was better positioned to endure a showdown than the
Palestinians.
   ``The occupied territories are dependent for income on three
things: work in Israel, the export of agricultural goods and
quarried stone to Jordan, and financial support from Arab
countries,'' he said in an interview.
   He said Arab job boycotts would deal a ``serious blow'' to the
construction industry, textile factories, restaurants and garbage
collection. But overall, he said, the ``economic impact on Israel
is much smaller.''
   Arab economists disputed the contention. ``We are prepared to
suffer more than the Israelis,'' said Samir Hazboun, a Bir Zeit
University economist.
   He said the tax rebellion had added to Israel's cost of
continuing the occupation and that bad publicity abroad had
affected investment and tourism.
</TEXT>
