<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Minister-Attack     03-15 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Minister-Attack,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Railey Misses Deadline in Lawsuit, Attorney Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former minister Walker Railey has decided not to
contest a civil suit accusing him of choking his wife nearly to
death, Railey's attorney said Monday.
   Doug Mulder told the Dallas Morning News that Railey's decision
was based on estimates that it would cost nearly $100,000 in legal
fees to dispute the lawsuit filed Feb. 2 by Railey's mother-in-law,
Billie Jo Nicolai.
   ``He told me that he had decided his assets would be best used
in the support and maintenance of his children,'' said Mulder, who
represented Railey before a Dallas County grand jury investigating
the attack.
   Railey, 40, missed a Monday deadline for answering the suit,
which seeks unspecified damages, said Bill Arnold, an attorney for
Mrs. Nicolai.
   In absence of a response, a judge could rule against the former
senior minister of the First United Methodist Church of Dallas and
award damages.
   Peggy Railey, 39, has been in a coma since she was found
unconscious on the floor of her garage last April. She had been
choked.
   Railey was not charged, but both his attorney and Assistant
District Attorney Norm Kinne identified the former minister as the
prime suspect.
   Railey denied any involvement but refused to cooperate with
police, invoking his Fifth Amendment right against
self-incrimination 43 times when questioned by a grand jury.
   Mrs. Railey remains in a Tyler nursing home. Railey, who now
lives in San Francisco, has assigned her guardianship to her
parents, and that of his two children to family friends.
   ``The question now is when do I want to go to court and ask for
a default judgment,'' Arnold said Monday. ``It could be tomorrow or
it could be a couple of months. It depends on Peggy's best
interests.''
</TEXT>
