<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NukeProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0665 03-15 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuke Protest, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0665,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>200 Arrested in Continuing Action at Test Site</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 3rd graf pvs, `The majority...', to
UPDATE with later protest at booking site, picking up 4th graf pvs,
`Monday's arrests ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MERCURY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two hundred arrests were reported Monday as
anti-nuclear protesters tried to block buses carrying thousands of
workers to the nation's nuclear testing grounds.
   The protesters slowed traffic into the Nevada Test Site, 65
miles northwest of Las Vegas, but failed to halt work, said Energy
Department spokesman Chris West.
   The majority of those arrested were carried away by officers
after lying down on the main road leading into the sprawling desert
site.
   Later, many of those arrested had to be dragged by police off
buses in Tonopah, Nev., about 135 miles away, where they were taken
to be booked before being released.
   ``They weren't going to stand for being driven 135 miles away
and being let loose,'' said protest spokeswoman Trudy Mason.
   The Nye County Sheriff's Department said officers decided to
remove the protesters from three buses and from the Tonopah
convention center, which was serving as a booking facility, after
they refused for several hours to be released.
   ``They just sat down and went limp and we dragged them out of
there,'' said Capt. George Gumbmann. Mason claimed some of the
protesters were injured, but Gumbmann said he knew of no injuries.
   Monday's arrests followed a demonstration Saturday by up to
5,000 people, the largest in more than seven years of protests at
the site. Police arrested 1,240 people that day, mostly on
misdemeanor trespass citations.
   A spokesman for the American Peace Test, which is sponsoring the
demonstrations, said 50 protesters had infiltrated the
1,350-square-mile site, which is the size of Rhode Island.
   West said he was unaware of any such incidents, but said any
infiltrators would not be able to reach sensitive areas.
   American Peace Test estimated there were 200 protesters at the
site Monday, but West said the number was closer to 400.
   He said 300 personnel from the Nye County Sheriff's Office, the
Nevada Highway Patrol and Wackenhut Security remained on duty or on
standby.
   The protests are scheduled to continue through Sunday.
</TEXT>
