<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 0054EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Shamir-Peres     03-15 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shamir-Peres,0739</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Speaks For Half His Government in Washington</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The following is a look at the main points of
disagreement between Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and
Foreign Minister Shimon Peres on the Middle East peace process.
   
   LAND FOR PEACE
   Shamir's right-wing Likud Bloc opposes giving up any part of the
occupied West Bank or Gaza Strip in exchange for peace. Instead,
Shamir calls for the implementation of the 1978 U.S.-mediated Camp
David accords signed by Israel and Egypt.
   The agreement says Palestinians should be granted self-rule on
domestic matters while leaving security and foreign affairs to
Israel. After three years of autonomy, Israel and the Arabs would
negotiate a final status for the occupied lands. Shamir believes
handing occupied territories back to the Arabs would endanger
Israel's existence by leaving it smaller and more vulnerable.
   Peres' left-of-center Labor Party is ready to enter negotiations
with Jordan, from which Israel seized the West Bank, which would
involve returning parts of the occupied lands. Peres says Israel
would insist on retaining Arab east Jerusalem and holding on to
areas along the Jordan River as a ``security border.'' His guiding
principle is to hand back as much of the heavily populated
Palestinian areas as possible, above all the Gaza Strip, taken from
Egypt. The West Bank and the Gaza Strip were occupied during the
1967 Arab-Israeli war.
   Today 1.5 million Palestinians live in the occupied territories
along with 65,000 Jewish settlers. Peres is afraid that if Israel
keeps the territories, it will quickly lose its Jewish majority
because of the high Arab birth rate.
   
   THE INTERNATIONAL PEACE CONFERENCE
   The international peace conference idea calls for negotiations
between Israel and Arab representatives under the aegis of the five
permanent members of the U.N. Security Council _ the United States,
the Soviet Union, Britain, France and China.
   Shamir rejects the notion outright. He claims four of the five
powers side with the Arabs and will have the power to force Israel
to give up the occupied lands. He believes the United States will
side with them on this issue. He also fears the Palestine
Liberation Organization will be invited to join the talks.
   As a concession to international involvement, he has suggested
the United States and the Soviet Union invite Israel and Jordan to
talks, leaving them to negotiate on their own after a ceremonial
meeting of the four delegations.
   Peres believes Jordan will negotiate only within an
international forum and that Israel must accept this condition if
it wants to talk peace. He says the conference will be only an
``opening'' of direct talks between Israel and a joint
Jordanian-Palestinian delegation. He argues the conference will not
have the power to impose its will or interfere in direct
negotiations and says the PLO will not attend the talks.
   
   THE SHULTZ PLAN
   The peace initiative by Secretary of State George P. Shultz is
an attempt to bridge the gap among moderate Arabs, Peres and
Shamir. It calls for convening an international conference in
April, followed by direct talks between Israel and a joint
Jordanian-Palestinian delegation on Palestinian self-rule. In
December, even if autonomy negotiations were still going on, the
sides would begin talks on a permanent settlement.
   Shamir says the Shultz plan is ``cumbersome ... and does nothing
to guarantee the safety of Israel.'' His aides accuse the United
States of reneging on its commitment to the Camp David agreement.
Shamir is against negotiating a permanent settlement while talks on
the interim autonomy arrangements are still going on. He says the
idea of autonomy was to see whether Israelis and Palestinians could
live on a new footing before considering a permanent settlement.
   Peres accepts the Shultz plan, warning that it may be the last
chance in the forseeble future to make peace with the Arabs. He
says talks would be conducted while the Reagan government is in
office. He describes the Reagan administration as the freindliest
Israel has ever known.
   
   THE PLO
   Shamir and Peres both refuse to negotiate with the PLO. Peres
has left open the possibility of talking to the PLO if it renounces
violence and recognizes the Jewish state. Shamir will have nothing
to do with the organization.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
