<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Gore     03-15 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gore,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Kicks Off Michigan Campaign, Predicts Better-Than-Expected
Showing</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Lead prospects uncertain</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. stumped Michigan today in
hopes the state will demonstrate he can win in the North, while he
kept his fingers crossed for ``a stronger result than people now
expect'' from Illinois' Democratic presidential primary.
   Gore was traveling to Lansing today where he planned to appear
with state legislators backing his candidacy before returning to
Washington.
   Arriving in Detroit Monday night, Gore described himself as a
``friend of organized labor'' and invoked the name of the state's
Democratic governor, who hasn't endorsed a candidate.
   ``I'm offering the politics of the future, very much in the way
Gov. Jim Blanchard has,'' Gore said.
   As he campaigned across Illinois earlier Monday, the Tennessee
senator contended he was encouraged about his prospects in today's
Illinois voting, despite a dismal single-digit showing in
pre-election polls.
   He pointed to Illinois' ``two favorite sons'' of Jesse Jackson
and Paul Simon, and the short time span since his crucial victories
in the South last week launched him as a contender, as an
explanation for his anticipated finish behind them and Michael
Dukakis.
   ``The polls have been wrong quite frequently in this race
because the voters are thinking for themselves,'' Gore said.
``There's a large undecided vote and people are looking for an
alternative.
   ``We've had only a few days to get the message out in
Illinois,'' he said later. He added that he hoped ``we're going to
have a stronger result than people now expect.''
   Gore avoided setting expectations in Michigan, where Democrats
hold caucuses on March 26, and where Richard Gephardt has chosen to
make a last stand in hopes of salvaging his candidacy that was
nearly knocked out in the South.
   ``I never single him out and certainly don't now,'' Gore said of
Gephardt. ``... It's a three-person race now between myself and
Jackson and Dukakis. That's the reality, regardless of what's
happening in any one state.''
   Gore said that no matter what the Illinois outcome, he and
Jackson and Dukakis would fight for the nomination across the
series of industrial states leading up to California's final
primary.
   ``There are other contests on down the road in Ohio,
Connecticut, Pennsylvania and New York, and we're looking forward
to those contests _ and Michigan and Wisconsin _ all the way to
California,'' Gore said.
   ``We're going to compete everywhere and look for an opportunity
to punch through,'' he told reporters on his campaign plane.
   Gore depicted himself as the alternative to Dukakis and Jackson
``to bring the Democratic Party back in the mainstream.''
   At the University of Illinois, Gore appeared before the school's
super computer, a machine capable of millions of computations in an
instant, to call for increased federal money for computer research
and education. He accused the Reagan administration of starving
civilian computer research while putting money into military
applications.
   ``We are now on the verge of falling behind Japan, once again in
a field we pioneered,'' he said.
</TEXT>
