<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LouisianaGovernor     03-15 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Louisiana Governor,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roemer: `Clean Up Our Politics'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Buddy Roemer, who toppled political
legend Edwin Edwards, opened his four-year term by challenging
Louisiana's residents to help ``clean up our politics.''
   ``Hope is diminishing. Attitudes have been damaged. Image is
tarnished. Pride has been wounded. We are down but we are not
out,'' said Roemer, inaugurated Monday as Louisiana's 51st governor.
   Roemer did not cite the usual litany of Louisiana's problems,
including high national rankings in unemployment, teen pregnancies,
high school dropouts, an almost bankrupt government of a state with
a widespread image of political corruption.
   The former Democratic congressman takes over a state with an
accumulated budget deficit and cash shortfall of as much as $1.2
billion, much of it due to the depressed oil industry.
   Roemer's legislative liasion, Manny Fernandez, said the
governor's first order of business would be to order a special
legislative session to give him wide budget-cutting authority for
the rest of the fiscal year, which ends June 30.
   The governor grabbed a major political victory even before he
took office when the Legislature approved his choices for House
speaker and Senate president.
   Roemer had said removal of the incumbent officers was needed to
ensure that his legislative programs would receive a fair hearing.
   Standing on the Capitol steps, Roemer was surrounded by 5,000
people. He was sworn in by former U.S. Sen. Russell Long, the son
of another legendary governor, Huey Long.
   ``Louisiana's victory will not be limited to the few or the
strong. That's not victory. That's just more of the same. We'll
bring the whole family on this victory trip,'' Roemer said.
   ``On behalf of our family, we declare war on ignorance, on
racism, on joblessness, on business as usual, on environmental
pollution and on dishonest political leadership. ...
   ``Do we have the character to clean up our politics, to free our
political leadership from the stranglehold of the special
interests? I say we do.''
   Roemer was interrupted frequently by applause, including
spirited clapping from Edwards, who conceded a runoff after
trailing Roemer in his Oct. 24 primary bid for an unprecedented
fourth term.
   Edwards, who served as governor from 1972 to 1980 and returned
for a third term in 1984, was occupied for much of his last
administration defending himself successfully against federal
racketeering charges.
   ``I'm going hunting tomorrow,'' Edwards told reporters when
asked how he felt at the moment. ``It's his now.''
</TEXT>
