<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Darden 6thLd-Writethru a0438 03-15 0817</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Darden, 6th Ld - Writethru, a0438,0835</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>URGENT</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Legal Appeal Pressed, Protest Vigil Held</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 8-9 pvs bgng, `Meanwhile, the ...' to UPDATE with
Louisiana inmate put to death.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STARKE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Supreme Court early Tuesday refused
to halt the execution at dawn of convicted killer Willie Jasper
Darden, who survived an unprecedented six death warrants and became
an international cause celebre.
   Darden, who has maintained his innocence in the 1973 slaying of
a Lakeland businessman during a robbery, was scheduled to die in
the electric chair at 7 a.m. at Florida State Prison near this
North Florida town.
   The high court, in a 6-3 vote, denied a stay, as did a federal
appeals court in Atlanta, a federal judge in Tampa and Florida's
Supreme Court earlier in the day.
   ``I'm going to holler, I'm going to holler loud, and I'm not
going to stop hollering, and I'll be hollering, `Innocent,
innocent, innocent' if they put me in the chair,'' Darden said in
an interview taped earlier Monday and shown on ABC's ``Nightline.''
   ``If I had committed such a crime, I would have a guilty
conscience all these years. I could not have lived with it,'' he
said.
   His case has become focus of an international campaign against
capital punishment. Pope John Paul II and Soviet dissident Andrei
Sakharov had made appeals on his behalf.
   Darden's attorneys raised several claims on appeal, including
reports of new evidence and arguments that the 54-year-old Darden
had ineffective legal counsel.
   In Angola, La., meanwhile, Wayne R. Felde was put to death in
the electric chair early Tuesday for the 1978 slaying of a rookie
policeman. The the U.S. Supreme Court on Monday had refused in a
7-2 vote to halt the execution.
   Felde had claimed his wartime service in the Vietnam War had
made him insane, and pleaded with the jury to impose the death
penalty to keep him from killing again. He later withdrew the
request and fought his execution.
   Darden's appeals already had gone to the U.S. Supreme Court four
times. The last was rejected March 7 and Gov. Bob Martinez signed
Darden's seventh death warrant the next day.
   Martinez on Monday dismissed suggestions he was rushing the
execution.
   ``It's been 15 years,'' Martinez said. ``I think of the victim
at a moment like this and the family which was destroyed. A hideous
murder took place and that's what I keep in mind. Just because it's
15 years later, that doesn't reduce a crime that was committed at
the time.''
   Darden was condemned for the shooting of James Turman, who
interrupted a man robbing his wife, Helen, of $15. Mrs. Turman
later identified Darden as the assailant.
   ``I think it was all very fair and Darden was the one who did
it,'' Mrs. Turman told Lakeland radio station WONN. ``I was in the
store alone with him for a long time before Jim came in and was
shot. ... His face is still impressed in the back of my memory. I
can't get it out.''
   A neighbor, Philip Arnold, also identified Darden during the
trial. Arnold, then 16, entered the store after apparently hearing
the shooting and Mrs. Turman's cries and was shot three times.
   If executed, Darden will be the 18th man Florida has put to
death since May 1979. Those men died after three or fewer warrants.
   Death penalty opponents claim Darden was railroaded because he
is black, and that he is innocent of murder and has an alibi to
prove it. They claim there is evidence _ statements from a minister
and another person _ that Darden could not have committed the
murder.
   The signing of the warrant last week gave defense attorneys only
one week to prepare.
   ``A lot of people feel the primary reason for the seven-day
warrant was to limit Amnesty International's ability to have
sufficient time to mobilize a public opinion assault as they did
very effectively for the sixth warrant,'' said Larry Spalding,
chief of the Office of Capital Collateral Representative, a
state-funded office of defense attorneys for death row inmates.
   Several hundred phone calls and telegrams had been received at
the governor's office in Tallahassee, most in favor of clemency.
The Florida Conference on the Poor held a vigil in the Capitol
rotunda Monday to press for clemency.
   In Sweden, about a dozen people demonstrated Monday outside the
U.S. Embassy in Stockholm, urging Florida to commute Darden's death
sentence.
   The protest was sponsored by the Swedish chapter of Amnesty
International, which charged in a statement that ``death sentences
in the United States are handed down with a great deal of
discrimination and with a racial slant.''
   ``Since January, I have received close to 2,000 letters from
around the world,'' Darden said in an interview with The New York
Times published Sunday in which he maintained his innocence.
</TEXT>
