<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PeaceActivists     03-15 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peace Activists,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Peace Activists Say Americans Should Speak Up Against
Occupation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Israel Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prominent Israeli peace activists say American
Jews who refuse to criticize the occupation of the West Bank and
Gaza Strip are hurting Israel.
   By remaining silent, the activists said, many American Jews have
signaled endorsement of the policies of Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir, thereby increasing the credibility of his views.
   Shamir arrived here Monday for talks with U.S. officials. The
peace activists planned a prayer vigil outside the White House when
Shamir meets with President Reagan on Wednesday.
   But the activists said the Americans Jews opposed to Shamir
should make their views known. Those expressions could help curb
the ``terrifying phenomenon'' in which Israeli voters are moving to
the right, said Yael Dayan, daughter of the late Israeli Defense
Minister Moshe Dayan.
   ``On the whole, American Jews are not behind Shamir's policy,''
said Mordechai Bar-On, a founder of the Israeli group, Peace Now.
``They must speak out now.''
   Shamir, head of the Likud Party, is reluctant to cede to the
Palestinians land in the West Bank or Gaza, two areas seized by
Israel in the Six-Day War of 1967. His views are opposed by many
Labor Party officials in Jerusalem, who favor a more conciliatory
approach towards the Palestinians.
   Giora Furman, former deputy commander of the Israeli Air Force,
said it is unrealistic for Israel to hang on to the territories in
the face of the determined Palestinian uprising.
   The peace group wants Shamir to endorse the return of some land
to the Palestinians, which is part of Secretary of State George P.
Shultz's Middle East peace proposal.
   ``I am very upset with what is happening to the American Jewish
community,'' Ms. Dayan said, adding it was ``rubbish'' for American
Jews to hold their tongues when Israel does something morally wrong.
   Ms. Dayan said Americans should write members of Congress and
Israeli leaders. But using U.S. aid as a lever to force change
could be counterproductive because the money _ about $1.5 billion
annually _ is spent on worthy causes, she said.
   Morris Abram, chairman of the Conference of Presidents of Major
Jewish Organizations, said the peace activists should be directing
its criticism at the Arab leaders who refuse to meet with Israeli
officials.
   ``The group is misdirected as to where its criticism is being
put,'' he said.
</TEXT>
