<DOCNO> AP880315-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 0240EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Shultz-ArmsTreaty     03-15 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-Arms Treaty,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Disputes Helms Allegation Of Misrepresentations</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz says that
seven weeks of Senate testimony have produced nothing to bar the
speedy ratification of the new arms reduction treaty with the
Soviet Union.
   Testifying before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee on
Monday, Shultz angrily dismissed an allegation by Sen. Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., that the administration's public defense of the pact is
based on ``misrepresentation'' and is at odds with facts presented
in closed-door secret sessions.
   Shultz also said the Senate should firmly discard all proposed
amendments or reservations to the treaty, including one that would
tie its implementation to reversing Soviet superiority in
conventional arms in Europe.
   He ticked off objections that have been mounted to the terms of
the pact, which bans medium-range nuclear missiles, and asserted
that all those objections have been refuted.
   The secretary of state, whose testimony opened the committee's
examination of the treaty in January, commented as he made a return
appearance to offer a summing up.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., the Senate's deputy majority
leader and a respected vote counter, predicted that the pact will
be ratified by the full Senate by a margin far greater than the
required two-thirds majority.
   Cranston said the Senate will act well in advance of a planned
Moscow summit meeting this spring between President Reagan and
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``We believe the treaty stands on its merits,'' Shultz said.
``It is self-contained and should not be made a vehicle for
statements on other issues,'' including the Soviet military
occupation of Afghanistan.
   But he bristled after hearing Helms declare that there is ``a
wide gap between the administration's public representations about
the treaty and the information which we have received in closed
session.''
   ``Indeed,'' Helms said, ``after many hours of listening to
testimony both private and public, the administration's public
presentation of the treaty has been a tissue of confusion,
misstatements and _ and I use the word advisedly _ even
misrepresentations.''
   Shultz told Helms: ``In a sense I don't know what I'm doing
here. Are you sitting here accusing me of deliberately
misrepresenting? ... I can handle it fine when people say they
don't agree with me, but when they say I have misrepresented, I
have trouble with that.''
   Helms said he was not accusing Shultz of ``deliberately''
misrepresenting, but he added that ``the contradictions are
self-apparent.''
   Replying to questions, Shultz told Sen. Larry Pressler, R-S.D.,
that Senate passage of an amendment delaying implementation of the
treaty until the West achieved a balance with the Soviet Union in
conventional arms would kill the pact.
   The pact, formally termed the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces
or INF treaty, calls for the destruction of all nuclear missiles
with a range of between 300 miles and 3,400 miles.
   Shultz said he does not believe the treaty will cause West
Germany to demand the removal of all nuclear weapons from its soil
_ a step that some fear could open Europe to intimidation by the
Soviet Union, which is said to have superiority in conventional,
non-nuclear forces.
</TEXT>
