<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 0251EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Trade     03-15 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Erase Gephardt Trade Plan, Senators Urge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators are starting to push their House
counterparts in earnest to erase the trade plan that serves as the
centerpiece of Democrat Richard A. Gephardt's race for the
presidential nomination.
   ``We decided to stick with our own Super 301 plan and to oppose
the Gephardt amendment,'' Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, said Monday
after a meeting of Senate conferees on the trade issue.
   As part of the action, the Senate will ask the House to drop the
Gephardt plan from the final version of sweeping trade legislation
passed by both houses last year.
   The decision was made by Senate members of a House-Senate
conference committee seeking a compromise version of the rival
1,000-page trade bills. It came on a voice vote in a closed-door
session of the Senate conferees.
   The move represents step one in a compromise process involving
proposals that go back and forth between the House and Senate until
both chambers agree on one version.
   Gephardt spokesman Mark Johnson said the Senate's action
represented ``nothing new'' in the trade debate.
   ``It's merely an opening bargaining position,'' he said. ``We're
confident that whatever emerges from conference will be new,
forceful legislation to open foreign markets. And clearly the
Gephardt amendment paved the way.''
   Gephardt's plan calls for negotiations to reduce Japan's and
other nations' ``excess and unwarranted'' trade surpluses with the
United States.
   If those talks failed, the plan would prescribe presidential
action to cut the surpluses by 10 percent a year. Such action could
include tariffs or import quotas on Japanese goods brought into the
United States.
   The president could, however, take no action if there are
considerations of ``national economic security'' or if the other
country had a serious international debt problem.
   Gephardt's amendment has been the chief basis of his appeal to
blue-collar workers and others concerned over the impact on
American jobs of products imported from Japan and newly
industrialized nations in East Asia.
   The ``Super 301'' provision that the Senate is pushing would
require the president to act to eliminate all of the unfair foreign
trade practices listed on an inventory to be drawn up by the U.S.
Trade Representative. It is named for the section of the Trade Act
that deals with retaliatory steps against such unfair practices.
   Before sending their offer to the House, the senators planned to
return to the table today and fashion additional provisions
involving steps to combat ``dumping,'' or selling foreign-made
products in world markets at prices lower than those in home
markets.
   The senators also intend to work on provisions involving
``countervailing duties,'' or tariffs that are imposed to offset
the price advantage that some foreign-made products get from export
subsidies in their home countries.
   On Monday, the senators moved to expand from seven months to 12
months the time for the president to make a determination as to
whether a foreign trade practice should be considered unfair.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
