<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Biden     03-15 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biden,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Biden Doctors Discuss Treatment Plans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Joseph R. Biden's doctors are discussing
treatment to prevent more blood clots like the one just discovered
in one of the senator's lungs.
   Peter Esker, a spokesman at Walter Reed Army Medical Center,
said Monday that the clot in the lung was dissolving, but treatment
would likely be needed to prevent further clots.
   Doctors could use anti-coagulant drugs or a surgical procedure,
Esker said.
   Biden, 45, was admitted to the hospital Sunday. He underwent an
operation at Walter Reed on Feb. 12 to repair an aneurysm _ the
ballooning of an artery wall _ in an artery supplying blood to the
brain.
   Biden was recovering at home from that operation and waiting for
an operation on a second aneurysm when he had to re-enter the
hospital.
   ``Medical tests show that the senator did experience a pulmonary
embolism, or a blood clot, that lodged in one of his lungs,'' Esker
said.
   ``The clot, which could have resulted from decreased activity
following major surgery, did no damage. Medical tests are
continuing to determine the method of lessening the chances of
other clots developing,'' he said.
   Esker said the alternative to anti-coagulant drugs is to insert
a venous filter, a form of catheter, in a vein.
</TEXT>
