<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DeafPresident     03-15 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deaf President,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gallaudet President, Chairman Introduced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students at the nation's only liberal arts
college for the deaf greeted the week with jubilation, as they were
formally introduced to the first deaf president and first deaf
board chairman in Gallaudet University's history.
   Irving King Jordan Jr. and Philip W. Bravin received standing
ovations Monday from the same students who effectively shut down
the 124-year-old institution over appointment of a woman with
normal hearing to be president.
   ``People will look at us and study what we are doing,'' said
Jordan, a 44-year-old professor and dean of the college of arts and
sciences at Gallaudet. ``We will prove to them, not only can they
choose a deaf president and chairman, but that these two will
succeed.''
   The two officials were joined at a news conference by student
body president Greg Hlibok, one of the campus leaders in the week
of protest over the hiring of Elisabeth Ann Zinser as president.
   The students succeeded in pressuring Zinser to resign last
Friday, less than a week after her appointment and in winning the
subsequent resignation of board chairman Jane Bassett Spilman, who
can hear.
   ``We're back in business and back to business, but Gallaudet
will never again be what it used to be,'' said Hlibok, who spoke in
sign language and through an interpreter.
   Only a few students were on campus Monday, the first day of a
spring break, but many people filled the auditorium for the press
conference and wore their ``Deaf President Now'' buttons.
   Jordan had endorsed Zinser's presidency last week but then
retracted it.
   Jordan lost his hearing at age 20 in a motorcycle accident. He
speaks clearly, but also uses sign language when he talks.
   ``We are continually impressed with him and we will give him our
full support,'' said Jerry Covell, a leader of the protest.
   Jordan received his bachelor's degree in psychology at
Gallaudet, then obtained his master's and doctorate at the
University of Tennessee.
</TEXT>
