<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama-Church     03-15 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Church,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Leaders Offer To Mediate In Panama's Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic church leaders, who
have called on Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega to step down, offered to
mediate talks between the military strongman and opposition
political groups demanding his ouster.
   But church officials also said on Monday that it may be
difficult ``to build a silver bridge for (Noriega) to leave,'' now
that the United States has indicted Noriega on drug trafficking and
money laundering charges.
   Since then, the country has fallen into a deepening financial
crisis that occurred after the United States imposed several new
economic sanctions on Panama, including the withholding of $6.5
million in Panama Canal fees due this week. It earlier cut off all
economic and military aid to the country.
   The 118 local and foreign banks that do business in Panama
remained closed Monday by government order for the 20th straight
day.
   ``The church still hopes to act as a bridge. There is no
question that Noriega must go ... The problem is how he goes,'' the
Rev. Fernando Guardia, a top church spokesman and vicar of the
archdiocese, said Monday.
   Archbishop Marcos McGrath, a native of Philadelphia, has been
criticial of the government in the past, but always avoided direct
confrontation to protect his priests, nearly 75 percent of whom are
foreigners.
   Under Panamanian law, they must have their visas renewed every
three months by immigration authorities, which come under Noriega's
Defense Forces.
   Noriega, the Defense Forces chief and the nation's de facto
ruler, ousted President Eric Arturo Delvalle on Feb. 26 after
Delvalle tried to fire Noriega.
   ``We are under pressure,'' said Father Guardia, a Panamanian,
explaining that foreign priests who tried to speak out in the past
were often threatened and reminded that they can lose their visas.
``They have not expelled any of our priests, but they have us by
the neck.''
   The country's bishops, in a statements that mentioned no names,
have accused the military regime of being responsible for Panama's
crisis.
   The bishops urged ``strict observance of constitutional norms,
full and effective subordination of the military to civil
authority,'' the creation of conditions for free elections, ``the
restoration of civil liberties and human rights,'' and asked that
``news media be allowed to reopen.''
   The bishops also lashed out at the military for resorting ``to
false nationalism'' to whip up support for the Noriega government,
but called for a ``Panamanian solution to the crisis without
foreign intervention.''
   The bishops also offered on Monday to act as a ``liaison'' to
seek a solution to the crisis, but there was no answer from the
government. Official government media accused the Church of siding
with the oppostion.
   ``People were fed up with Noriega since last year,'' Father
Guardia said, ``but the indictment by the United States was
politically mishandled. The government party and other groups here
threw their support to Noriega and Noriega will hang in there
longer and eventually drag others with him.''
   ``They (the United States) closed all avenues,'' Father Guardia
added. ``It is very difficult for Noriega now to go somewhere with
the indictment hanging over his head. But he has to realize that he
msut go.
   About 80 percent of the people of Panama are Roman Catholic.
</TEXT>
