<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SubwaySenators 1stLd-Writethru a0452 03-15 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Subway Senators, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0452,0683</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: DELETES second section, `A magazine...', which repeats matter
from WASHINGTON WIRE of March 1. Picks up at prvs. third section,
`Rep. Bob Dornan'</NOTE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Snarled Subway Snares Slow Senators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate, struggling to make legislating a
more orderly affair, put itself on a new work schedule this year
and tightened up its procedures.
   The change produced unintended consequences.
   Under the new schedule the Senate works in Washington for three
straight weeks, then permits senators to return to their home
states for a full week to attend to their constituents.
   The purpose of the change was to disband the so-called
Tuesday-Thursday club, named for the age-old practice of many
senators who left Washington on Thursday evenings and did not
return until the following Tuesdays.
   Now when the Senate is meeting senators are expected to attend,
Monday through Friday, no exceptions.
   There have been other changes as well.
   Roll call votes, which often were prolonged for an hour or more
while the Senate waited for an absent member to arrive from the
airport or from a meeting across town, were limited to a strict 15
minutes each, no exceptions.
   And that caused the problem.
   The three Senate office buildings are linked to the Capitol by
an underground subway.
   For years that subway has routinely and efficiently served two
of those buildings _ the Russell and the Dirksen.
   But the tunnel which was extended to the new Hart Senate Office
Building is far longer, as is the trip to the Capitol.
   And the Hart Building contains the offices of 50 of the 100
senators.
   Last month, seven or eight senators hurried to the Hart subway
station with only minutes to spare to make a roll call.
   But the car was jammed with visitors.
   ``There were unusual circumstances,'' Sen. Howell Heflin,
D-Ala., told his colleagues.
   ``There were some blind people on the subway car and it took
some time to get them off.''
   The 15-minute clock ticked to an end and Heflin and his
colleagues missed the vote.
   They demanded a solution to their transportation problem and a
solution was provided.
   Tourists and other visitors were banned from the cars during
roll call votes.
   And a subway car will now depart the Hart subway station
precisely three minutes before the end of a 15-minute vote, giving
senators just enough time to reach the Senate chamber and cast
their votes.
   The Senate and its subway cars roll on.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Bob Dornan, R-Calif., was on the House floor earlier this
month, holding forth with some heat on the turn of events that had
seen Congress cut off all aid to the Contra rebels in Nicaragua.
   ``Mr. Speaker, if I have told you once I have told you a hundred
times that every time you cozy up to those communists down there in
Nicaragua they are going to stick a rusty knife right in your
back,'' he fumed, adding that he was off to California and would
return ``with more facts and figures'' from a RAND Corp. report on
communist activity south of the border.
   He said he would seek permission to publish all of it in the
Congressional Record.
   ``And I do not care if it costs thousands of dollars, and it
will,'' Dornan said in a shout.
   ``I want that whole report in the record, available to all the
schools and libraries across America and everybody who follows the
proceedings in this House through the written record and national
technical means _ that means electronic.''
   Dornan stopped.
   Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., took the floor.
   He had a question.
   ``I simply wanted to ask the gentleman from California if any of
us could help get him a sedative?'' Obey said.
   When the one-line comment appeared in the Congressional Record
it bore a five-word headline.
   The headline: ``A Sedative For A Member.''
</TEXT>
