<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 0419EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua-Cardinal     03-15 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Cardinal,0797</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Removal Of Cardinal Seen As Political Manuever</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo was
removed as mediator of the peace talks because he wanted the
Sandinistas to discuss political reforms as well as a cease-fire
with the Contras, sources said.
   President Daniel Ortega diplomatically eased Obando y Bravo from
his job as mediator on March 2, thanking him for his efforts but
saying the cardinal would not be needed for direct talks scheduled
for next week.
   The manuever effectively removed the Roman Catholic prelate from
pushing what were seen by the leftist Sandinista government as
pro-Contra proposals.
   Ortega has called for three days of face-to-face talks with the
Contras beginning Monday in the Nicaraguan post at Sapoa on the
border with Costa Rica.
   Ortega said his brother, Gen. Humberto Ortega, the nation's top
military leader, would head the Sandinista delegation. The Contras
countered by naming Adolfo Calero, their highest political leader,
to head their delegation.
   Sandinista sources and opposition figures, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said Ortega ousted Obando y Bravo because
he outlined a proposal that would force the government to discuss
internal politics with the rebels.
   The government has refused to discuss anything but a cease-fire.
   During the last round of talks on Feb. 18 in Guatemala, Obando y
Bravo called on the Sandinista government to grant total amnesty,
revise the military draft law, grant full press freedom and reopen
stalled talks with internal opposition parties. He also suggested a
30-day truce.
   The Contras quickly accepted the proposal. The Sandinistas
hesitated.
   Obando y Bravo, saying the two sides were at an impasse, broke
off the talks the following day.
   Ortega on Feb. 23 sent the cardinal an angry letter, decrying
the talks' ``abrupt suspension without consulation.'' The letter
was the first in a week of exchanges between the government and the
Catholic leader.
   The letters also sent signals that church-state relations had
once again deteriorated in Nicaragua.
   The strong Roman Catholic Church backed the 1979 revolution that
ousted dictator Anastasio Somoza and supported the Sandinistas. But
the church later became the staunchest government critic and
suffered repression.
   Since the signing of a regional peace plan in August by five
Central American presidents including Ortega, the situation seemed
to be improving.
   The government allowed two exiled priests to return, permitted
the Catholic Radio station to reopen and in November asked the
cardinal to be mediator.
   The cardinal's last letter to Ortega was sent March 2, hours
before Ortega removed him as mediator. In it, the prelate
reiterated the need for talks to ``put an end to the grueling war
that daily claims 50 or 60 young Nicaraguans'' and said he was open
to discussing a new outline for negotiations.
   A church source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
Sandinistas hoped to pressure Obando y Bravo into backing out of
his mediation role. When that failed, Ortega made his move and
visited Obando y Bravo that night.
   Ortega made it look like he was deferring to the cardinal's
wishes.
   ``The cardinal himself had suggested some time ago that a direct
meeting (with the Contras) and in our country would be very
important,'' Ortega said.
   For the past four years, Obando y Bravo has urged direct talks.
But the Sandinistas had repeatedly refused to sit down with the
Contras until they were forced to do so by the regional peace plan.
   The plan signed by Nicaragua, El Salvador, Costa Rica, Guatemala
and Honduras calls for cease-fires, democratization, amnesties and
an end to tactical or logistical support for insurgencies.
   The Sandinistas say peace talks should be held with the U.S.
government because it financed and trained the rebels. The Reagan
administration refuses.
   During the first few rounds of talks aimed at working out a
cease-fire, the cardinal acted as a go-between in indirect
negotiations.
   In January, Ortega proposed direct talks but with a mediator.
   After Obando y Bravo was asked to step down as mediator, the
Contras demanded he be involved in the meetings ``as witness,
moderator and guarantor of the talks.'' The president responded on
March 7 by calling on the cardinal to act as a witness, a role he
accepted and which satisfied the rebels.
   The first direct talks in Nicaragua were scheduled for last
week, March 9-11, but were canceled at the last minute by
Sandinistas after the Contras backed out and pressed for a
preliminary meeting.
   The Contras later dropped that demand.
   More than 40,000 people have been killed since November 1981,
when the Contras began fighting the Sandinista government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
