<HEAD>House Leader Says Delegates Will Broker at Democratic Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A brokered Democratic national convention
is possible, but it's too late for anyone but delegates to do the
horse trading, according to Rep. Tom Foley.
   Foley, D-Wash., the House majority leader who expects to be
convention parliamentarian when the Democrats meet in Atlanta in
July, said Monday the party's nominee likely won't be determined
beforehand.
   But if there is any brokering to be done at the Democratic
convention, it will be by the delegates, he said.
   ``I think there's a possibility that no candidate will go into
the convention with a sufficient number of delegates to be
nominated,'' he said. ``But I don't expect anybody else to be
nominated, other than those four or five that are now in the race.
   ``Brokering is largely going to be a decision of the delegates
themselves, not any sort of backroom `kingmaking' operation,'' said
Foley, who supports House colleague Dick Gephardt of Missouri.
