<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Study Says Jackson Gets Best TV Coverage, Robertson Gets Most
Negative</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study of network evening newscasts from Jan.
1 through Super Tuesday March 8 says Democrat Jesse Jackson got the
best television coverage and Republican Pat Robertson got the most
negative.
   The Center for Media and Public Affairs, a non-partisan study
group, said it studied 532 news items involving the election and
found:
   _Evaluations of every major candidate, based on clearly positive
or negative statements from all sources relating to character, job
performance, campaign performance or issue stands, became more
negative after the New Hampshire primary Feb. 16.
   _ Telecast comments involving Jackson were favorable 74 percent
of the time, compared with 90 percent this year before New
Hampshire. He also nearly tripled his share of the Democrats'
coverage, from 9 percent before New Hampshire to 26 percent in the
weeks leading up to March 8 Super Tuesday.
   _Robertson dropped from 70 percent positive evaluations before
New Hampshire to 33 percent after it. Comments about his prospects
also became more negative.
   The analysts also said there have been four stories on the
campaign horse race for every story on policy issues since the Feb.
8 Iowa caucuses and the issues most frequently mentioned are taxes
and trade.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaRouche Challenge of Simon Petitions Fails</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Board of Elections has rejected
challenges to Illinois Sen. Paul Simon's petitions for a spot on
New York's April 19 Democratic presidential primary ballot.
   The challenges had been filed by political extremist Lyndon
LaRouche and Monday's ruling meant Simon's name will appear on the
ballot.
   Board spokesman Steven LaFever said that after a lengthy
hearing, the board ruled that Simon had filed petitions containing
the valid signatures of 21,263 registered Democrats. His original
petitions had contained 22,076 signatures and only 10,000 are
needed to qualify for the ballot.
   The ruling in favor of Simon means that the New York ballot for
Democrats will include all the major Democratic candidates and
LaRouche.
   LaRouche is also seeking the Democratic nomination. His
petitions have not been challenged.
