<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HeroinArrest     03-15 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Heroin Arrest,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fugitive Drug Lord Nabbed In Case That Dwarfs French Connection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the country's most wanted narcotics
traffickers has been arrested and charged with importing 1,000
pounds of heroin into the United States from Asia over a three-year
period.
   Kon Yu-Leung, 44, who was arrested Sunday night outside a
Manhattan hotel, had been the Drug Enforcement Administration's No.
1 heroin target for about 2{ years, said U.S. Attorney Andrew
Maloney.
   Kon's drug ring was much larger than well-known heroin cases
operated by traditional organized crime groups, said Robert
Stutman, head of the DEA's New York office. The ``French
Connection'' case involved 70 pounds of heroin, the ``Pizza
Connection'' about 200, he said at a news conference with Maloney.
   Maloney said Kon was believed responsible for bringing into the
country twice the 1,000 pounds of heroin he was charged with
importing.
   ``Clearly, the levels of heroin we're dealing with here are
almost mind-boggling,'' said Stutman.
   The heroin from Kon's drug ring was smuggled into the country
between 1984 and 1987 through various means, including suitcases
and in shipments of vases, ice buckets, T-shirts and wall plaques,
Maloney said.
   Couriers then carried millions of dollars in drug proceeds back
to Hong Kong to be laundered, authorities said. Kon allegedly used
$20 million to buy commercial real estate in the New York area and
San Francisco.
   Stutman said Kon sold the heroin to distributors at an estimated
wholesale price of $100,000 per pound. Authorities estimate the
street value of one pound of heroin at $1 million.
   Law enforcement authorities confiscated 570 of the 1,000 pounds
alleged to have been imported by Kon's organization in several
seizures over the years, Stutman said.
   Kon first came to the DEA's attention in November 1984 when a
shipment of 250 pounds of heroin, believed to be destined for the
United States, was seized in the Hong Kong harbor from a fishing
trawler.
   Kon, the alleged mastermind, eluded arrest by moving between
Thailand, Taiwan, Japan and the Philippines, Maloney said.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Catherine Palmer said Kon had at least
six phony passports and traveled under numerous fictitious names.
   She said Kon, who was born in mainland China and later moved to
Hong Kong before becoming a fugitive, had numerous businesses in
Asia and the United States, including several fur companies and a
firm called the Kon China Trading Co. He also allegedly had a watch
manufacturing company in Paraguay.
   Maloney said federal authorities lured Kon to New York after a
federal grand jury indicted him. He declined to give any details
concerning the circumstances of Kon's arrest.
   Authorities also arrested John Routollo, a former New York
police officer, at his Montclair, N.J., home Sunday night.
Routollo, 50, was charged with picking up the heroin, usually at
the New York Hilton Hotel, for distribution in the United States.
   Maloney said that before Routollo left the force in 1981 he
supplied weapons to Kon's organization through his position in the
police department's office of pistols and licenses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
