<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Minister-Attack     03-15 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Minister-Attack,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Railey Won't Challenge Lawsuit, Attorney Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Methodist minister has decided not to
contest a lawsuit by his mother-in-law accusing him of a near-fatal
choking attack on his wife, saying legal fees would be too costly.
   ``He told me that he had decided his assets would be best used
in the support and maintenance of his children,'' said Doug Mulder,
a defense attorney who represented Walker Railey before a Dallas
County grand jury investigating the attack.
   Mulder said the former minister decided not to contest the
lawsuit because of estimates it would cost nearly $100,000 in legal
fees. Mulder called the lawsuit a ``publicity stunt,'' and said his
client could win if he spent the money.
   The suit was filed by Billie Jo Nicolai, seeking an undetermined
amount of damages in the April attack on her daughter, Peggy
Railey. Mrs. Railey, 39, never regained consciousness and remains
in a coma in a Tyler nursing home.
   Mrs. Nicolai's attorney, Bill Arnold, said Monday he will seek a
default judgment but will ask for a jury trial to determine damages.
   ``The question now is, when do I want to go to court?' It could
be tomorrow or it could be a couple of months. It depends on
Peggy's best interests. I'm not going to run my schedule according
to Walker's schedule,'' Arnold said.
   Railey's father-in-law said he was disappointed there was no
response to the lawsuit.
   ``We thought he might come through and answer some of our
questions. It sure would help, but it didn't turn out that way,''
he said in a Monday night telephone interview from his rural Smith
County home. ``It really is disappointing. I guess we're just going
to have to keep waiting.''
   Without a response, a judge could rule against the former senior
minister of the First United Methodist Church of Dallas and award
damages in his absence.
   Railey, 40, was not charged, but both his attorney and Dallas
County Assistant District Attorney Norm Kinne identified him the
prime suspect.
   Railey refused to cooperate with police, denying his involvement
and then invoking his Fifth Amendment right against
self-incrimination 43 times when questioned by a grand jury.
   A psychologist, Lucy Papillon, reportedly told the grand jury
that she and Railey were romantically involved and had discussed
marriage before the attack.
   Railey is living in San Francisco, where he rented an apartment
with Ms. Papillon, Arnold said.
   Railey assigned his wife's guardianship to her mother, and that
of his two children, ages 5 and 2, to family friends in Dallas.
</TEXT>
