<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Claims More Missile Attacks On Tehran</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said it fired four more long-range
missiles into Tehran today, and Iran said civilians were killed
when Iraqi missiles crashed into residential areas of the city.
   Iran claimed its jet fighters ``heavily pounded'' Iraqi troop
concentrations in southern Iraq today, inflicting substantial
casualties and losses. Iraq did not comment on the report.
   In another development, the Soviet Union acknowledged at the
United Nations in New York on Monday that it had failed to win
support for a Security Council resolution calling for an end to the
deadly missile duel.
   The Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, said four missiles
were fired into Tehran today. It reported eight such missile
strikes on Monday.
   Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored in Nicosia,
said ``a number'' of civilians were killed in missile attacks on
residential areas of the city overnight. It did not say how many
rockets hit Tehran.
   On Monday, Iran said missiles killed 26 civilians and wounded 50
in Tehran. Iraq also reported civilian casualties in Baghdad but
gave no figures.
   Iraq says it has fired 13 missiles into Tehran since the duel
with Iran resumed with a single rocket fired into the Iranian
capital Sunday night after a two-day truce. Iran has fired two into
Baghdad since Sunday.
   Declaring an all-out offensive on Iranian cities, Iraq said it
launched air raids on ``military and economic targets'' in six
western border towns Monday.
   IRNA also said Revolutionary Guards commandos pushed into
northeast Iraq to within 12 miles of the provincial capital of
Sulaimaniyeh early Monday, seizing a dozen villages and killing or
wounding 1,000 Iraqis.
   Iran also said its anti-aircraft gunners shot down an Iraqi
fighter-bomber in the northeastern battles, while Iraq claimed its
helicoptergunships downed an Iranian helicopter.
   An uneasy two-day truce that ended Sunday had brought a brief
respite following a 12-day exchange of missiles, artillery fire and
air raids by both sides that killed or wounded hundreds of
civilians.
   Iraq said it fired 71 missiles into Tehran, the holy city of Qom
and the central city of Isfahan, capital of ancient Persia, between
Feb. 29 and March 11. Iran said it shot 27 missiles into Tehran and
two into the northeastern city of Mosul in that period.
   At the United Nations, Soviet Ambassador Alexander Belonogov
acknowledged on Monday that the Soviet bid for a new resolution on
the ``war of the cities'' had failed after the council met behind
closed doors.
   ``Our personal preference would be a resolution of the Security
Council,'' but the important thing is ``not the form but the
essence'' of the council's action, he told reporters after a
closed-door council meeting.
   The United States saw the proposal as a maneuver to deflect
attention from the American push for a worldwide arms embargo
against Iran to punish it for refusing to honor the council's July
20 cease-fire resolution and peace plan.
   Instead of a new resolution, the council is expected to issue a
statement later this week calling for an end to the missile
attacks. A presidential statement is the mildest form of council
action.
   Iran and Iraq have been at war since 1980.
</TEXT>
