<1ST_LINE>u i PM-IRAFuneral     03-15 0733</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-IRA Funeral,0756</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearses Of IRA Guerrillas Attacked By Protestants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hearses carrying the bodies of
three Irish Republican Army guerrillas home to Roman Catholic west
Belfast ran a gantlet of jeering, rock-throwing Protestants early
today.
   Thousands of IRA sympathizers waved black flags of mourning
along the 100-mile Dublin-Belfast highway, mourning the three
guerrillas who were shot by British troops while allegedly
preparing a car-bomb attack in Gibraltar.
   The March 6 killing of the unarmed guerrillas in the British
colony sparked riots in Belfast for much of the following week.
   In another development, an IRA gunman and a Catholic civilian
were reportedly shot and killed in Belfast on Monday night and
early today.
   The nine-hour procession for the slain IRA guerrillas was marked
by a confrontation at the border over Irish flags on the coffins
and accusations by the IRA's political wing, Sinn Fein, that police
tried to break up the cortege and twice crashed a vehicle into one
of the hearses.
   Crowds of Protestants waving British flags threw rocks and other
objects at the procession on at least six occasions as it traveled
by road the 40 miles from the border town of Carrickaron in the
Irish Republic to Belfast.
   Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams said police deliberately slowed the
cortege where Protestants had gathered ``to allow them to throw
stones and jeer.'' Police denied the accusation, saying their
concern was to ensure security.
   A few hours before the cortege arrived in Belfast, police said
British soldiers shot a gunman who fired on an army patrol near the
home of one of the dead guerrillas. The man, identified by police
as Kevin McCracken, 33, died shortly afterward in the hospital.
   A police statement said McCracken was jailed in 1978 for
membership in the outlawed Irish Republican Army, illegal
possession of guns and criminal damage and was released on parole
in 1985.
   An unidentified Catholic was shot today at point-blank range
from a motorcycle as he arrived for work at a south Belfast store,
police said. No group claimed responsibility.
   In Dublin, police said they were investigating a suspected
letter bomb blast overnight at the city's central mail sorting
office which blew a hole in the wooden floor and slightly injured
two postal workers.
   News reports that the package was addressed to the British
Embassy in Dublin were dismissed as speculation by detectives.
   The IRA said its members fired a volley over a makeshift shrine
in Belfast as a farewell salute to Mairead Farrell, 31; Sean
Savage, 24; and Daniel McCann, 30, who died in Gibraltar.
   The traditional paramilitary salute, which is banned in Northern
Ireland as an illegal display of firearms, was fired Monday
afternoon as the bodies landed in Dublin, the IRA said in a
statement issued through Sinn Fein.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary, Northern Ireland's police force,
promised in newspaper advertisements not to interfere with the
funerals if the IRA did not mount a gunfire salute over the coffins.
   The funerals are expected to take place on Wednesday in west
Belfast, with burial in the Catholic Milltown Cemetery alongside
many other IRA guerrillas killed in nearly 20 years of political
and sectarian strife in the province.
   The coffins arrived in Dublin on a plane chartered by Sinn Fein
to a reception by about 1,000 supporters. The slow procession to
the border, with thousands lining the route, was uneventful.
   At the border, two senior Royal Ulster Constabulary officers
demanded the removal of the Irish tricolors draped on each coffin.
   The tricolor, Ireland's national flag, is regarded by Northern
Ireland Protestants as a symbol of the IRA's fight to drive Britain
out of Northern Ireland and unite the mainly Protestant province
with the overwhelmingly Catholic republic.
   After a 30-minute confrontation, a compromise was reached
whereby the flags were folded, replaced on the coffins and covered
with wreaths.
   At Newry, fives miles inside Northern Ireland, the hearses were
paraded around the largely Catholic town for two hours in front of
cheering IRA supporters.
   On the outskirts of Newry, crowds from a Protestant municipal
housing project jeered, waved British flags and hurled bricks,
bottles and stones at the cortege. Windows in some of the cars were
broken by the missiles.
   Similar scenes repeated themselves along the road to Belfast.
   The coffins containing the bodies of the three guerrillas were
taken into the homes of their families in West Belfast.
</TEXT>
