<2ND_LINE>PM-Carlucci-Soviet, 1st ld-Writethru, a0487,0686</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Has Doubts About New Soviet Defense Posture</HEAD>
<HEAD>PRECEDE SHANNON</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs, Carlucci reaches Bern. Picks up 5th graf
pvs ``Carlucci was...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci wants
his Soviet counterpart to cut production of tanks, artillery and
heavy missiles to prove he is seriously pursuing a new defensive
military doctrine.
   Carlucci, speaking to reporters today en route to a meeting in
Bern with Soviet counterpart Dmitri Yazov, said that despite the
extensive publicity surrounding the emerging Kremlin doctrine of
``reasonable sufficiency,'' he has seen ``absolutely no practical
change.''
   ``If anything, their military continues to grow. They continue
to modernize,'' Carlucci told reporters aboard his Air Force jet.
   The plane refueled in Ireland and then completed the flight to
Switzerland.
   Carlucci was to attend a dinner with Yazov tonight, and sit down
Wednesday and Thursday for the first ever business session between
U.S. and Soviet defense secretaries.
   Yazov and other Soviet officials have said they are moving
toward a new doctrine with a defensive posture. But they have never
acknowledged that their past doctrine embodied an offensive
posture, and various Soviet commentators have offered different
views on the meaning of ``reasonable sufficiency.''
   ``That's a question, by the way, I intend to ask him,'' said
Carlucci. ``I'm still not sure what it is.''
   If Yazov wants to demonstrate that the Kremlin is moving from an
offensive to a defensive doctrine, the Soviets should slack off in
tank and artillery production and ``maybe'' desist from the SS-18
intercontinental ballistic missile that carries 10 nuclear
warheads, said Carlucci.
   ``One of the most important indicators, I would think, would be
tanks. But tanks continue to pour out,'' he said. ``So there is no
indication at the other end of the pipeline that there has been any
change.''
   The U.S. side also wants to discuss so-called ``dangerous
incidents'' such as a collision involving U.S. and Soviet warships
off the Soviet Black Sea coast last month, and the fatal shooting
by a Soviet soldier of U.S. Maj. Arthur D. Nicholson on March 24,
1985, in East Germany.
   ``One idea I have is for them to apologize for Maj. Nicholson,
which they still haven't done,'' said Carlucci.
   The Reagan administration wants the Soviets to agree on broad
guidelines to curtail such incidents.
   The Soviets last month rammed two U.S. warships as they passed
through Soviet territorial waters in an exercise designed to assert
the ``right of innocent passage'' from international waters on one
side of the Crimean peninsula to the other.
   On a personal level, Carlucci said he was ``looking forward'' to
meeting Yazov.
   The meeting, the first of its kind and perhaps the first in a
series of high-level military consultations, ``is kind of an
interesting idea,'' he said.
   ``He was....mildly critical of `glasnost' as applied to the
military, which seems to be a bit at variance with the standard
line,'' Carlucci said.
   Yazov, although generally supportive of the reform policies of
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, has said the policy of
glasnost, or greater openness, must be restricted in the armed
forces.
   Carlucci, dwelling on the meaning of the emerging Soviet
military doctrine, said that ``sufficiency is a word that has been
around for a long time'' since the detente era of the 1970s.
   ``Sufficiency can mean anything you define it to be, as best I
can tell,'' he said. ``The (Soviet) military is saying that
sufficiency is sufficient to meet the threat ... and , `Oh, by the
way, you have to have sufficient offense so that if the other
fellow attacks you, you can attack him all the way to the ocean.'
   ``That doesn't sound to me like anything new. At the same time,
Gorbachev is saying that there is something new.
   ``Some (Soviet) academics are saying, `Well, maybe this means we
can rethink our military establishment and do the same thing with
less.' So obviously there is some kind of debate going on.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
