<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Record Cold Overtakes Parts Of The South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Unseasonably cold air sent thermometers plunging across the
South, producing record lows in some areas and bringing freezing
temperatures early today as far south as Midland, Texas,
Shreveport, La., and Atlanta.
   Meanwhile, snow showers sprinkled the Northeast, and reached
from the upper Mississippi Valley across the Great Lakes region to
the Appalachians. Snow also was scattered from southern New England
into New Jersey. The heaviest snow continued to fall along the
shores of the Great Lakes.
   More than 14 inches of snow fell in the Conneaut area of
northeast Ohio, with 8 to 10 inches reported in Ashtabula, Ohio,
and 4 to 6 inches in Geneva, Ohio.
   More than 2 feet of snow has buried portions of the Snow Belt in
northern Wisconsin and upper Michigan since Saturday.
   Another storm system over the northern Rockies was spreading
snow from Idaho and western Montana across western Wyoming and
northern Utah. The central and southern mountains of Idaho were
expected to receive about 5 inches of snow by late this afternoon.
   Winter storm warnings were in effect today over the mountains of
Montana and northwest Wyoming, with up to a foot of snow possible.
   Snow was forecast to increase southward into the central Rockies
by tonight. Winter storm watches were been posted for tonight and
Wednesday across northern and western Wyoming and the northern
mountains of Utah.
   A record low of 22 degrees was set in Asheville, N.C., beating
the old mark for the date of 24 degrees, set in 1979. Greer, S.C.,
reached 23, one degree below the record set on March 14, 1968; and
Meridian, Miss., hit 26, beating the 27-degree mark for the same
date in 1970.
   For today, snow was forecast from New England to the Ohio Valley
and Great Lakes region, and across the northern Rockies, with
scattered snow showers over the northern half of the Plateau region
and the central Rockies. Sunny skies were predicted over the
Plains, the Pacific Coast and the southern third of the nation.
Winds were expected to be strong and gusty over the northern
Rockies and the southern Plateau.
   Most of the nation will have highs in the 30s, 40s or 50s. Highs
will be in the 20s in the northern Rockies and from North Dakota
across the Great lakes region and the Ohio Valley. Temperatures
will reach the 60s and 70s from California across the desert
Southwest, from southern and central New Mexico across southern
Texas, and over the Florida peninsula.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from zero at
Lemmon, S.D., to 63 at Key West Naval Air Station, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 30 fair; Boston 34 snow; Buffalo 17 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 36 fair; Cincinnati 22 snow; Cleveland 22 snow;
Detroit 19 partly cloudy; Miami 54 windy; New York 32 snow;
Philadelphia 32 cloudy; Pittsburgh 21 snow; Portland, Maine 29
cloudy; Washington 28 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 4 fair; Chicago 20 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 35
fair; Denver 27 cloudy; Des Moines 18 fair; Indianapolis 22 snow;
Kansas City 14 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 20 snow; Nashville 23
fair; New Orleans 44 fair; St. Louis 22 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 35 fair; Anchorage 27 snow; Las Vegas 50
fair; Los Angeles 55 fair; Phoenix 55 fair; Salt Lake City 40
partly cloudy; San Diego 55 fair; San Francisco 50 fair; Seattle 39
fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 28 snow; Toronto 14 fair.
</TEXT>
