<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Mondale,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mondale Says Chinese Leaders Committed to Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Vice President Walter Mondale today said
Chinese leaders are committed to their open-door policy and an
ambitious plan to allow coastal areas to develop ahead of the rest
of the country.
   Mondale also told a news conference that the Chinese eagerly
seek more foreign investment in order to expand exports. He said
they are prepared to open up domestic markets and remove other
obstacles that have discouraged foreign businessmen from investing
in China.
   The Minnesota Democrat, who arrived in Beijing last week for
business connected to his Minneapolis-based law firm, met Acting
Premier Li Peng, Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang and other
Chinese leaders during his stay. He was to leave for Tokyo later
today.
   On Monday he said he discerned no signs of differences between
Zhao and Li on the pace and scope of economic reforms and China's
open-door policies.
   Zhao, the protege of senior leader Deng Xiaoping, is believed to
be more aggressive in pushing for market-oriented reforms, while Li
prefers a slower, more cautious approach.
   ``My impression was that Li Peng was just as committed'' to
reform, Mondale said. ``He didn't show any qualifications.''
   He said Chinese leaders appeared united behind Zhao's plan to
put priority on developing and opening up coastal regions.
</TEXT>
