<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Spycatcher     03-15 0128</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Spycatcher,0131</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Government Loses Appeal Of Spycatcher Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British government today lost
its fight for damages from a newspaper for publishing sections of
the book Spycatcher.
   The court dismissed Britain's appeal, which sought damages and
an account of profits from the book written by Peter Wright, a
former assistant director of the British security service MI5 who
now lives in Australia.
   The British government says the book revealed security secrets.
   The president of the Court of Appeal, Sir Robin Cooke, said the
claim was defeated by two defenses from The Dominion, a
Wellington-based newspaper.
   The first was that there was enough prior publication to destroy
confidentiality. The second was that the New Zealand public
interest justified publication in The Dominion.
</TEXT>
