<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Safeway-Boycott     03-15 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Safeway-Boycott,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Market Chain Settles Anti-Israel Boycott Charges Out of Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Safeway Stores Inc. agreed to pay $995,000 in
penalties to the U.S. Commerce Department to settle charges that
the company cooperated with a long-standing Arab boycott against
Israel.
   ``It (the settlement) is equitable, and it indicated we take
enforcement of the anti-boycott laws very seriously and will
continue to vigorously enforce them,'' said Paul Freedenberg,
undersecretary of commerce for export administration.
   The settlement announced Monday was the largest of its kind, the
Los Angeles Times reported in today's editions.
   For more than 30 years, Arab countries have boycotted Israeli
goods and companies that do business with Israel. A U.S. law passed
in 1977 forbids Americans to comply with the boycott.
   The department filed charges against three stores licensed by
Oakland-based Safeway, two in Saudi Arabia and one in Kuwait.
   Commerce officials alleged the three stores refused to do
business with companies on an anti-Israeli blacklist and store
managers instructed suppliers and customers to avoid such business
relations.
   Safeway officials said the penalty, less than one-quarter of
what the department originally sought, absolved the company of
wrongdoing.
   ``The settlement terms clearly vindicate the position that
Safeway's conduct in its dealings with licensees in the Middle East
did not merit the harsh penalties originally sought,'' said Peter
A. Magowan, chairman and chief executive officer.
   ``We agree with the purpose and the spirit of the anti-boycott
laws,'' he said.
   Three years ago Citicorp was fined $323,000, the previous
largest anti-boycott penalty.
</TEXT>
