<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0515 ,0795</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Israel Bans Palestinian Travel Between Occupied Territories</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with one dead, five wounded in West Bank
clashes, ban on travel by Palestinians. NO PICKUP.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAX NASH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EREZ CHECKPOINT, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli authorities
today banned Palestinians from traveling between the occupied
territories, and hundreds of people rioted after a nightly curfew
on the 650,000 Arabs in the Gaza Strip.
   Hospital officials said troops shot dead one Arab and wounded
five today during clashes on the West Bank. No injuries were
reported in the rioting in the Gaza Strip.
   In Jerusalem, police spokesman Rafi Levy said seven of 90 Arab
polie officers had quit. They were the first such resignations in
the disputed Israeli capital.
   Their action came after 500 Arab police in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip heeded a call by underground Palestinian activists to
turn in their badges.
   On the West Bank, a general strike called for by the Palestine
Liberation Organization got under way with transportation halted
and Arab-owned stores closed.
   The travel ban between the Gaza Strip and the West Bank
represented an effort by the Israeli army to stem the growing
campaign against Israeli occupation inspired by PLO.
   An official of the military's Civil Administration said the
measure applied to traffic in both directions. He said exemptions
would be issued for hardship cases.
   ``They are allowed to work in Israel, but they can't continue
into Judea and Samaria or vice versa. They would be turned back at
a checkpoint,'' said the official, using the biblical terms for the
West Bank.
   ``The policy is not to separate (the Palestinians), but to make
it more difficult for agitators to move and to help stop
distribution of anti-Israeli pamphlets that cause incitement,''
said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The ban was the most comprehensive travel restriction imposed
since Israel seized the areas in the 1967 Middle East War. Under
Israeli law, Palestinians are allowed into Israel to work but must
have police authorization to spend the night.
   The Israeli military also said it would to take punitive actions
against foreign and local journalists it believed had filed false
reports about incidents in the occupied territories. Army officers
declined to elaborate, saying a statement would be released later.
   Officials at Jerusalem's Mukassad Hospital said a 22-year-old
Palestinian from the West Bank village of Ain Yabrud was dead on
arrival with a bullet wound to the jaw. The Arab-owned Palestine
Press Service identified the dead man as Arafat Hweih and said he
was shot during a demonstration in Deir Jarir, 9 miles northeast of
Ramallah.
   Troops also shot and wounded four Palestinians in Qalqilya, 16
miles west of Nablus on the West Bank, officials at Qalqilya
Hospital said. The Press Service put the wounded at six and said
two were women shot in the head.
   The army said it imposed a curfew on Qalqilya.
   In Ramallah, thick black smoke from burning tires rose above
several neighborhoods. At least three handcuffed Palestinians were
detained by troops and sitting on the ground in the Ramallah police
station.
   In the Gaza Strip, the army imposed a 10 p.m. to 3 a.m. curfew
over the entire coastal territory following the resignation of 300
Arab policemen.
   Soldiers at the Erez checkpoint, the main entrance leading into
the Gaza Strip, turned back Arab residents during the curfew, which
was imposed without advance notice. Journalists saw 15 to 20 cars
turned back in the first hour.
   After the curfew was lifted for the day, soldiers fired tear gas
at hundreds of Arabs who threw stones at an army administrative
office in the Jabaliya refugee camp in the Gaza Strip. No injuries
were reported.
   Army officers said the nightly curfew, which forces Arabs to
stay in their homes, would keep Arab agitators from entering the
Gaza Strip and provoking demonstrations.
   Israel radio today said 300 Arab police in Gaza City had also
resigned. They joined 450 officers in the occupied lands who turned
in their badges earlier following orders of PLO-inspired
underground leaflets. The radio said that 40 officers who had
handed in their resignations in the West Bank city of Hebron
continued working after local Arab leaders asked them to stay on.
   About 850 Arab policemen work in the occupied territories.
   In response to months of PLO-backed unrest in the occupied
lands, Israel stepped up economic sanctions. Shipment of gasoline
and other fuel to service stations in the West Bank was banned as
of Sunday.
   According to United Nations figures, at least 91 Palestinians
have been killed since anti-Israeli rioting began Dec. 8.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
