<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Inquest     03-15 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Inquest,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ice Chunk Probably Killed Prince Charles' Friend, Pathologist Said</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British army officer killed in an avalanche that
nearly engulfed his friend, Prince Charles, most likely died from a
chunk of ice that crashed down a Swiss mountainside, an inquest was
told today.
   Maj. Hugh Lindsay, a 34-year-old career army officer, died of a
single blow to the head and probably was standing when he was
struk, Dr. Esha Sarvesvaran, a pathologist, testified.
   The pathologist told Hammersmith Coroner's Court that the blow
fractured Lindsay's skull and caused severe bleeding. He said the
object that struck Lindsay probably was a lump of ice.
   Lindsay, Charles and others were skiing in Switzerland on
Thursday off of a main trail at Klosters when the avalanche broke
loose. Charles and other members of the party skiied clear but
Lindsay was caught in the avalanche. Another friend, Patti
Palmer-Tomkinson, suffered broken legs and lung injuries.
   Coroner John Burton, who presided over the inquest, said he
wanted to dispel speculation that Lindsay suffocated in the snow.
   Lindsay is to be cremated after a funeral Thursday at the Royal
Military College at Sandhurst.
   Burton adjourned the inquest until an unspecified date while a
Swiss examining magistrate completes his inquiries.
   ``If it proves necessary to seek further evidence, then that
would be taken from those who can give the most helpful evidence,''
Burton said, reading from a statement. ``That is the only
consideration when one decides which witnesses one might call.''
   He said nothing about whether Prince Charles, the 39-year-old
heir to the British throne, might be summoned to testify.
</TEXT>
