<HEAD>More Than 50 Feared Drowned In Bus Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A passenger bus rolled into the Kumar
River and sank as it was attempting to board a ferry, and more than
50 people were feared drowned, news reports said today.
   Newspapers said about 60 passengers were believed to be on the
bus, which was en route from the southern town of Barisal to Dhaka.
They quoted witnesses as saying only seven people jumped or swam to
safety after the accident Monday night.
   The Janata, a Bengali-language daily, said the bus' brakes
apparently failed. It said the driver and two assistants were among
the missing.
   A senior police official at Madaripur said in a telephone
interview today that five bodies had been recovered. ``Some more
bodies might have been trapped inside the bus,'' he added.
   The police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
rescue work was hampered by a lack of equipment. He said that the
Dhaka fire department had been asked to rush cranes and other
equipment to the scene.
