<2ND_LINE>PM-Poison Coffee,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Junior High Students Expelled For Coffee Poisoning Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FOREST LAKE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three students accused of putting a
foreign substance into a school official's coffee in an attempt to
poison him have been expelled for the rest of the school year,
school officials say.
   The school board took the action Monday after two of the
students, girls in the seventh and ninth grades at Forest Lake
Southwest Junior High School, waived their right to hearings.
   The other student, a ninth-grade girl, had insisted on a closed
hearing, which was held March 10 before a state hearing examiner.
The examiner recommended that she be expelled, and the board
accepted the recommendation.
   All three girls have been accused in Washington County Juvenile
Court of conspiracy to commit murder.
   They're accused of putting a foreign substance into vice
principal Robert Espelien's coffee cup on Feb. 25. Espelien said he
became suspicious when he saw a ``brownish-tan substance'' floating
at the top of the cup and had it sent to a medical lab for analysis.
   The substance put in the coffee has not been revealed.
   Forest Lake District Superintendent Gerald Brynildson said the
students are entitled to return to school next fall unless the
expulsion is extended. Until then, the district is required to
provide tutors.
