<DOCNO> AP880315-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 0917EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Meese-Pipeline     03-15 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Meese-Pipeline,0724</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swiss Oilman Says Meese Friend Tried To Get Around State
Department</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Swiss oilman involved in a failed Iraqi oil
pipeline plan says a friend of Attorney General Edwin Meese III
tried to bypass the U.S. State Department by attempting to get
Meese's help on the project.
   Bruce Rappaport also said Monday he had been ready to give
Israel a third of his profits from the $1 billion project in return
for an Israeli promise not to bomb the pipeline to Jordan, which
would have passed near the Israeli border.
   Speaking in Hebrew on Israel television, Rappaport denied
allegations he offered a bribe to Foreign Minister Shimon Peres,
then prime minister, in return for a promise not to attack the
pipeline.
   The pipeline project was prompted by Iraq's war with Iran. Iraq
backed out of the project because it was not satisfied with
security arrangements.
   On Sept. 19, 1985 Peres wrote a letter to Meese saying Israel
would not bomb the pipeline, and Meese's friend, E. Robert Wallach,
took charge of organizing meetings with officials in Washington,
Rappaport said.
   ``He (Wallach) apparently approached and told me: `Look, if Mr.
Peres confirms the (assurances) to Mr. Meese, then we will arrange
such a meeting, and it will go up to the president' and so on,''
Rappaport said.
   ``What I understand now is that the intention then was to bypass
the U.S. State Department,'' Rappaport said.
   He was not clear in the interview exactly what the meetings in
Washington were about.
   ``Wallach understood that if we want to receive support for such
a guarantee which Israel has no possibility or need to give ... and
we had an alternative agreement with large insurance companies,
with a group of bankers, with individuals, so if this had to pass
through the Senate, the Congress or the State Department it would
not come into being,'' he said.
   He said President Saddam Hussein of Iraq feared for his life if
Israel bombed the pipeline and in meetings Hussein demanded a $400
million guarantee no bombing would occur.
   Rappaport said he received the guarantee from the Overseas
Private Investment Corp., a U.S. government-run export company,
while Israel was asked to provide ``a moral guarantee.''
   At that stage, Rappaport said, he was introduced to Wallach, who
organized a meeting with then-National Security Council head Robert
McFarlane.
   ``He (McFarlane) was very excited to get all possible assistance
for ... Israel,'' he said.
   A memo by Wallach says that on Oct. 16, 1985, Meese, Peres and
Wallach had a ``three-way discussion'' of the project at the
Israeli Embassy in Washington. On Sunday, James Rocap, one of
Meese's lawyers, said Wallach's account ``totally exaggerates'' the
discussion.
   Rappaport said he was first told of the pipeline project in
September 1984. He said he met in Israel with Peres, who confirmed
the Jewish state had no intention to bomb the pipeline.
   He said he also met with representatives of the San-Francisco
based Bechtel Group Inc., which was to build the pipeline.
   Rappaport said he had been prepared to give Israel $60 million
to $70 million a year, or a third of his profits from the project,
over a 10-year period.
   Wallach wrote a memo to Meese saying that of $65 million to $70
million a year over 10 years which Rappaport was going to funnel to
Israel, some would go to Peres' Labor Party, although that would be
``denied everywhere.''
   As a result, U.S. independent counsel James McKay is
investigating in Washington whether Meese, Wallach, Rappaport and
others conspired to pay an illegal bribe to a foreign official _
that is, Peres and his party.
   McKay is trying to determine if Meese was simply passing a
problem on to the appropriate official _ as Meese's lawyers say _
when he referred Wallach to McFarlane in May 1985, or if he was
aiding a conspiracy to get funds for the guarantee despite
opposition from the State Department and Overseas Private
Investment Corp.
   Whatever he heard from Meese, Wallach and Rappaport, McFarlane
endorsed the idea and assigned an aide to work on it while keeping
progress of the proposal secret from the State Department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
