<DOCNO> AP880315-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 0919EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Year-RoundSchool     03-15 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Year-Round School,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proposal Dropped by Superintendent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public school Superintendent Leonard Britton
abruptly withdrew a districtwide plan for year-round schools by
July 1989, conceding there wasn't enough support from the school
board.
   ``Frankly, it is very late to place the entire school district
on a new calendar in July 1989,'' Britton said Monday, just before
the seven-member board was to vote on the proposal.
   The board earlier had agreed to the July 1989 date, but tabled
it last October after a fiery public outcry. The district adopted a
policy two years ago phasing in year-round schooling for all
students by the 1991-92 school year.
   Those in favor of the proposal said it would ease overcrowding
by putting some students in classes during the usually idle summer
months. They also said it would provide educational advantages such
as better retention of information.
   Currently about one-quarter of Los Angeles Unified School
District students, those in the most crowded schools, are on
year-round schedules. Proponents say the selective policy is
unfair, especially to the minorities who account for most of the
student population.
   Critics say year-round schools disrupt family vacations and
students' summer jobs, make child care more difficult and force
some students to spend summer days in hot, antiquated rooms.
   Britten said the district will still aim for a year-round
schedule, but he admitted a majority of the current seven-member
school board may never agree.
</TEXT>
