<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 0927EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0494 03-15 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0494,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks Reach Soviet-Set Target Date, Still Awaiting Breakthrough</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Cordovez's and Soviets'
comments. PICKS up 6th graf, `Those elements ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Afghanistan peace talks reached a Soviet-set
target date today but the U.N. mediator, citing difficult issues
still to be resolved, said negotiations will continue.
   ``We are discussing very serious, difficult issues but we
continue to negotiate and look for solutions,'' said U.N. mediator
Diego Cordovez.
   Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev has said that if an agreement
was reached by March 15, Moscow's estimated 115,000 troops would
start leaving Afghanistan by mid-May.
   Neither side in the negotiations, which resumed today, has said
the deadline was a rigid one or that the Soviets would consider
going back on their pledge to withdraw their troops if the deadline
passed without an agreement.
   But in Moscow today, the Soviets said failure to meet the
deadline will delay the start of a Soviet troop withdrawal.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said there was
only a ``slim'' chance the accords could be signed by the end of
the day. He blamed the situation on Pakistan's insistence that a
coalition government be formed in Kabul before the agreement was
reached.
   He accused Pakistan of ``procrastination'' in the negotiations
in an attempt to arrange a post-war government to its liking.
   Pakistan has said it wants a transitional government in Kabul
before the Soviets begin their withdrawal to oversee the Soviet
pullout and ensure the safe return of more than 5 million refugees
from Pakistan and Iran.
   Moscow and Kabul say Afghanistan should decide the makeup of its
future government after the settlement is signed.
   The current round of talks, now three weeks old, has completed
all main elements of the settlement aimed at ending nine years of
fighting.
   Those elements include the timetable and basic logistics of the
pullout of the estimated 115,000 Soviet troops, an issue that has
eluded a solution for several years.
   Sources close to the talks, who declined to be identified, said
on Monday the Pakistanis also have reservations about some minor
points in the complex agreement package.
   The sources said Pakistan received a new Kremlin message during
the weekend, urging it to sign the settlement without delay.
   Unconfirmed reports quoted Pakistan's Prime Minister Mohammad
Khan Junejo as saying that a decision on whether it would sign
would be announced Monday. But there was no official word by
nightfall. Pakistan's Cabinet has held three meetings since Sunday,
apparently to weigh its next step.
   Meanwhile, the fragile seven-party Alliance of Moslem guerrillas
failed to decide whether it would drop its demand to dominate a
future Afghan government.
   A guerrilla leader said on Monday in Pakistan that Moscow again
rejected direct talks with the Moslem rebels on the Afghan issue.
The resistance is represented by Pakistan in the Geneva talks but
its position has not always been identical with Pakistan's.
   The guerrillas have started to form a government of their own
which Pakistan considers too hard-line.
   The Soviet Union began sending troops to Afghanistan in December
1979 at the request of the pro-Moscow government. The Soviet troops
and the Kabul government's regular army of about 50,000 men are
pitted against 200,000 Moslem rebels, supported by the United
States, China and Pakistan.
</TEXT>
