<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BridgeFall     03-15 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bridge Fall,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protester Survives Unplanned Plunge From GG Bridge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A protester who wanted to dramatize his
cause by spending a week in a garbage can dangling from the Golden
Gate Bridge fell 220 feet into the icy water and was nearly washed
out to sea.
   Paul Alarab, 29, of Kensington, Calif., suffered collapsed lungs
and three broken ribs but was listed in satisfactory condition at
Letterman Army Medical Center following Monday's rescue.
   He was plucked from a rock by the Coast Guard nine hours after
the fall.
   ``He's lucky,'' said his brother, Chris Alarab. ``Now he has a
second chance to give his message.''
   Paul Alarab said he wanted to draw attention to the plight of
the old and infirm by living for a week in a plastic garbage can
suspended from the bridge.
   He complained that the elderly must stand in long lines in
supermarkets and banks and are neglected by young people, the
California Highway Patrol said.
   Alarab had equipped the 33-gallon garbage can with clothing, two
jugs of water, a life vest and some political pamphlets, the CHP
said.
   Alarab said he lowered the can, attached to the bridge railing
by 60 feet of nylon rope, Sunday night and was shinnying down when
he fell.
   The CHP was called to the scene but found only the swaying
plastic barrel. Fearing it was a bomb, authorities closed the
bridge for 40 minutes.
   Monday morning a fishing boat reported a man clinging to a rock
near Point Diablo, on the ocean side of the bridge's north end.
   Highway patrol officials said they will seek a trespassing
charge against Alarab when he is discharged from the hospital. His
brother said Alarab has been unemployed for six months.
</TEXT>
