<DOCNO> AP880315-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 0939EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam-Premier     03-15 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-Premier,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premier Pham Hung Buried In Hanoi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam today buried Premier Pham Hung
after eulogizing him as a dedicated revolutionary who defied
torture and harsh battlefields in a 60-year struggle for the
communist cause.
   Guerrillas fighting Vietnam's nine-year occupation of Cambodia
called Hung ``a notorious murderer'' who brought widespread
suffering to Vietnam and Cambodia.
   Hung, who played a key role in defeating the U.S.-backed South
Vietnam government and rose to the No. 2 position in the Communist
Party hierarchy, was buried in Hanoi after dying of a heart attack
last Thursday. He was 75.
   Vietnamese radio reports said Communist party chief Nguyen Van
Linh and other top party officials carried Hung's casket from the
Ba Dinh conference hall to a gun carriage for the trip to Mai Dich
cemetery, the final resting place of Vietnam's revolutionary
leaders.
   Tens of thousands of mourners lined the six-mile route of the
carriage, flanked by two rows of armed military honor guards, said
the reports monitored in Bangkok.
   The radio of the Khmer Rouge, the main anti-Vietnamese guerrilla
group, said Hung died ``as one who brought endless misery and
suffering on Vietnam and on the Vietnamese and Cambodian peoples.''
   The broadcast, a text of which was seen in Bangkok today, said
Vietnam's leaders should rethink the line adopted by Hung and
Communist Party chief Le Duan, who died in July 1986.
   Hung died while Vietnamese forces were ``almost choking to death
from their attempt to swallow Cambodia,'' the broadcast on Sunday
said. Vietnam's economy has ``hit rock bottom,'' and the country is
internationally isolated, it said.
   Vo Van Kiet, a vice premier and head of state economic planning,
has been chosen acting premier to replace Hung.
   Linh and Kiet are regarded by Western analysts as the country's
leading proponents of Western-style reforms which the party has
deemed crucial to overcome the nation's economic crisis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880315-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 0947EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-DardenExecution 8thLd-Writethru a0552 03-15 1002</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Darden Execution, 8th Ld-Writethru, a0552,1028</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Darden Executed; Maintained Innocence To The End</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th grafs, ``Darden's case, to CORRECT by deleting
mention of pope; DELETES 16th graf, ``It's obvious, for same
reason; SUBS 26th graf, ``Martinez rejected xxx, with two grafs, to
show that pope has expressed concern about Florida death cases, but
Darden's not among them</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STARKE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted murderer Willie Jasper Darden, who
maintained his innocence through 14 years on death row and became
the focus of an international debate on capital punishment, was
executed today in Florida's electric chair.
   Darden, 54, was convicted of fatally shooting Lakeland
businessman James C. Turman while robbing his wife of $15 in
September 1973.
   ``I was not guilty for the charge for which I was arrested and
this morning I tell you I am not guilty of the charge for which I
am about to be executed,'' Darden said in a final statement to 30
witnesses in the death chamber.
   ``I go this morning with a clear conscience. I bear no guilt.
I'm at peace with myself, with the world, with each of you. God
bless you.''
   Darden winked and nodded at one of his attorneys just before the
hood was put over his head, and was declared dead at 7:12 a.m.
after 2,000 volts of electricity flowed through his body for two
minutes. Two puffs of smoke rose from his right leg where one of
the electrodes was attached.
   Darden's case attracted worldwide attention, including pleas for
clemency Nobel peace prize winner Andrei Sakharov and other human
rights activists. They said Darden was railroaded because he was
black and the victim was white.
   Earlier today, Wayne Robert Felde was executed in Louisiana's
electric chair for the 1978 murder of a policeman.
   It was the first time two inmates were executed the same day in
the United States since Aug. 28, when three murderers were put to
death, in Florida, Alabama and Utah.
   Darden spent 14 years on death row, one month less than Howard
V. Douglas, who has been on death row in Florida since December
1973.
   Darden refused his last meal this morning, said prison spokesman
Bob Macmaster. By 6 a.m., Darden had showered, and his head and
lower right leg were shaved to facilitate the flow of electricity,
the spokesman said.
   On Monday, the U.S. Supreme Court, the 11th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals, a federal judge and the state Supreme Court rejected
Darden's appeals.
   His last hope was a reprieve from Gov. Bob Martinez, who signed
Darden's seventh black-bordered death warrant last week and said
Monday he had no plans to issue a stay.
   ``I think of the victim at a moment like this and the family
which was destroyed,'' Martinez said. ``A hideous murder took place
and that's what I keep in mind. Just because it's 15 years later,
that doesn't reduce a crime that was committed at the time.''
   ``The governor's hands are now stained with the blood of a man
from whom justice was withheld,'' Amnesty International said in a
statement from John G. Healey, executive director of Amnesty
International USA in New York.
   Early today, about 40 people gathered in a cow pasture across
from the Florida State Prison to protest the execution.
   The opponents maintained silence after 7 a.m. while the
execution took place, then began singing ``We Shall Overcome.''
   ``I think it's long overdue. He did it to himself. I'm just
thinking right now I want some peace of mind ... it's been a long
time and I'm glad it's finally over,'' said Turman's widow, Helen
Turman Baum, minutes after the execution. Mrs. Baum has remarried
since the shooting.
   Darden went into Turman's furniture store on September 8, 1973,
and had just robbed Turman's wife of $15 when Turman came on the
scene.
   Court records say that after shooting Turman between the eyes,
Darden unbuckled his belt and unzipped his pants and ordered his
wife to get on the floor, remove her false teeth and perform oral
sex on him while Turman lay dying just a few feet away.
   A neighbor, Philip Arnold, also identified Darden during the
trial. Arnold, then 16, entered the store after apparently hearing
the shooting and the woman's cries. He was shot three times but
survived.
   Darden became the 18th person executed in the state and the 96th
executed in the nation since the Supreme Court restored capital
punishment in 1976.
   Death penalty opponents, led by Amnesty International, have said
Darden had an alibi to prove his innocence. They claim there is
evidence _ statements from a minister and a woman _ that Darden
could not have committed the murder.
   In Sweden, about a dozen people demonstrated Monday outside the
U.S. Embassy in Stockholm, urging Florida to commute Darden's death
sentence.
   Martinez rejected appeals on Darden's behalf by Sakharov,
Democratic presidential candidate Jesse Jackson, actress Margot
Kidder and others.
   Jon Peck, a spokesman for Martinez, said Pope John Paul II,
through Florida-based Roman Catholic leaders, has expressed
concerns in the past about Florida death cases, but never Darden's
specifically.
   Ray McDaniel, who prosecuted Darden for the Turman killing said
Friday, ``There is no question he is guilty.''
   Then-Gov. Bob Graham signed Darden's first death warrant in 1979
on the same day as a warrant for John Spenkelink, the first man
electrocuted in Florida after the state resumed the death penalty.
   Darden was born in Snow Hill, N.C., the second of four children.
He graduated from high school in Greene County, N.C. His conviction
record dated to 1964 and included breaking and entering and
attempted rape.
   Douglas, at 51 the man who has spent the longest time on death
row, was convicted of the July 1973 shooting death of his former
lover's husband in Polk County.
   His first death warrant resulted in the U.S. Supreme Court
sending the case back in 1984. He was resentenced to death and the
case is now pending on appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
