<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 1001EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Strike     03-15 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Strike,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Killed, 90 Hurt In Anti-Gandhi Clashes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least four people were killed and
more than 90 injured today during an opposition-sponsored strike to
demand the resignation of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi.
   The strike closed offices and businesses in six of India's
states but failed to achieve widespread support in the other 17
states.
   At least three people were killed and several others were hurt
in street clashes in Bihar state, United News of India said.
Violence also was reported in neighboring West Bengal state, where
at least 75 people were reported injured.
   In Kerala state, the news agency reported a youth was killed and
seven other people injured when a flour mill operator opened fire
at opposition party supporters attacking his mill near the coastal
city of Ernakulam.
   United News also said 14 police were injured near the Pakistan
border in Rajasthan state when they were pelted with stones while
trying to remove roadblocks.
   The strike disrupted normal life in Bombay, India's business
center, and in Calcutta, the country's largest city. But it drew
little response in the capital at New Delhi, where most businesses
remained open.
   United News of India said police arrested at least 3,000 people
from various cities for attempting to block traffic and close shops.
   But the opposition coalition that called the strike said at
least 150,000 people were arrested. In a statement in New Delhi,
the eight parties maintained the strike was complete in all major
towns and industrial areas.
   The strike was called by most major opposition parties to
protest sectarian violence, rising prices and alleged corruption in
government. The parties, which include two communist groups, demand
that Parliament be dissolved and new elections held.
   In Parliament, proceedings were disrupted for more than an hour
when opposition members raised anti-government slogans in the upper
house. Earlier, the entire opposition boycotted the first hour of
business in both houses in support of the strike.
   On Monday, at least 25,000 people were arrested in the southern
state of Tamil Nadu and 500 others in Orissa in the east in what
police said was a move to pre-empt violence during today's strike.
   Opposition members in Parliament today criticized the government
for Monday's arrests, United News of India said.
   Gandhi's Congress Party holds more than 400 of the 542 seats in
the popularly elected lower house of Parliament. The rest are
divided among opposition parties which have failed to act jointly
despite common demands that Gandhi resign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
