<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FedoIndictment 1stLd-Writethru a0562 03-15 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fedo Indictment, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0562,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Duluth Mayor Named In 23-Count Indictment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf to CORRECT, Duluth at western tip of Lake
Superior</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DULUTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grand jury has indicted Mayor John Fedo
on 23 charges including theft, falsifying expense records and
attempting to obstruct the state auditor.
   The indictment, made public Monday after the mayor's arraignment
in State District Court, included 22 felony charges.
   Fedo, 37, said the charges were a political ploy arranged by
people who don't like him. The indictment, he said, ``is not going
to have an effect on City Hall.''
   If convicted, Fedo, 37, faces a maximum penalty of 10 years in
prison on the theft charge and up to five years in prison on most
of the other charges. Fedo was freed on his own recognizance and
scheduled to appear in court May 3, when a judge will determine
whether enough evidence exists to proceed to trial.
   His lawyer, Douglas Sauter, said he will move for dismissal of
the charges. Fedo was ``tried once in the election and found not
guilty,'' he said.
   Fedo, a member of Minnesota's Democratic-Farmer-Labor Party, won
his first four-year term as mayor in 1979 and has been re-elected
twice.
   The theft charge concerns $13,500 given to Fedo by three
businessmen to lobby for state funds for a convention center in the
city.
   During the 1987 election campaign, Fedo said he passed the funds
to an unnamed Twin Cities businessman in 1985 in exchange for
information about other cities' convention center proposals.
   But prosecutors say the mayor played a limited role in lobbying
for a convention center he later claimed to have won almost
single-handedly.
   Duluth, a city of 85,000 on the western tip of Lake Superior,
was never in competition for the $200 million convention center for
which Bloomington and Minneapolis vied, the charges say. The State
Legislature awarded Duluth a total of $17.2 million for its own,
relatively small center.
</TEXT>
