<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Koch     03-15 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Koch,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New York Mayor: TV Cameras Should Be Banned From Occupied
Territories</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch of New York wrote in an
Israeli newspaper today that television cameras should be barred
from the occupied territories.
   In a signed column published in the Jerusalem Post, Koch said
that in view of what is happening elsewhere in the world, Israel
would be justified in taking steps to bar TV crews from the West
Bank and the Gaza Strip.
   ``Many other nations throughout the world are experiencing
troubles similar to those now taking place in Israel. Should Israel
be the only nation to allow full television coverage of these
troubles?
   ``This creates a false impression in the minds of television
viewers that such events are happening only in Israel,'' wrote
Koch, a longtime supporter of Israel.
   More than 90 Palestinians have been killed by Israeli gunfire
and beatings in riots that started Dec. 8 in the territories
occupied by Israel in the 1967 Middle East War. The territories are
home to 1.5 million Palestinians.
   Koch said he thought Israel should use whatever force necessary
to put down the Palestinian uprising in the occupied lands.
   The mayor also criticized U.S. editorial writers and columnists
for their ``relentless drumbeat of criticism against Israel.''
   He added that he had attacked U.S. involvement in the Vietnam
War but now had ``second thoughts'' about the wisdom of deserting
South Vietnamese allies.
   ``It's easy for columnists, and for all of us, to play God with
the lives of other people, endanger them and leave them ultimately
to be destroyed,'' he wrote.
</TEXT>
