<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-TrainStalls     03-15 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Train Stalls,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Train Stalls World's Longest Tunnel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Passengers spent longer than they bargained for
today in the world's longest undersea tunnel, which opened to
trains two days earlier.
   A power outage left them stranded for more than three hours 460
feet underground in the 37-mile-long Seikan Tunnel.
   The tunnel links Japan's largest island, Honshu, with Hokkaido,
the northernmost main island. It cuts two hours off a trip formerly
made by ferry.
   It took 24 years to build at an estimated cost of $8.5 billion.
   Most of the 166 passengers were asleep when the outage halted
their 11-coach express train, bound for Tokyo from Sapporo, about
12 miles from the tunnel's south exit. A locomotive pulled the
train from the tunnel, and it resumed its journey from the next
station, at Aomori, 3 hours and 50 minutes behind schedule, a
Hokkaido Rail Japan Co. spokesman said.
   The cause of the power outage was under investigation, said the
Hokkaido representative, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Six trains have been stopped by faulty fire detectors since the
tunnel opened.
</TEXT>
