<DOCNO> AP880315-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 1059EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Writer'sStrike     03-15 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writer's Strike,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Producers Seek Exemptions, Striking Scriptwriters Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 50 independent
production companies, including Johnny Carson's talk show, are
seeking exemptions from striking scriptwriters, union officials say.
   That would allow some companies to work during the Writers Guild
of America strike against the 200-member Alliance of Motion Picture
and Television Producers. No talks were scheduled in the 10-day-old
strike by 9,000 Guild members.
   Brian Walton, West Coast executive director of the guild, said
its board would consider appeals for an interim agreement with
several companies. Cheryl Rhoden, a spokeswoman for the writers,
said decisions on exemptions would probably be announced Wednesday
or Thursday.
   Walton declined to identify those seeking interim agreements,
but ``The Tonight Show'' announced through its publicists that it
was among them.
   A spokesman for the producers belittled the union's assertion
about the number of independents seeking waivers.
   ``The overwhelming number of independents are actually a writer
that employs himself for tax purposes. He produces nothing,'' said
Alliance spokesman Herb Steinberg. ``With the exception of Carson,
I don't know of any other independent producer looking to make a
deal who is also member of the alliance.''
   Among shows already rejected for a waiver or interim contract
was the Academy Awards, scheduled for broadcast on April 11.
   Lobell-Bergman Productions disclosed Monday that the strike has
affected development of five of eight movies on its slate and
stopped work on a network comedy series. Previously postponed was a
revival of ``The Smothers Brothers Comedy Hour'' and ``The
Dictator,'' a new series starring Christopher Lloyd.
   The guild is seeking an increase in creative control, an
increase in residuals from foreign market distribution, and
rejection of a producers' contention that residuals for hour-long
syndicated television shows should be adjusted.
</TEXT>
