<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDS-DrugMaker     03-15 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Drug Maker,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troubled Maker Of AIDS Drugs Promises Better Quality But Faces New
Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration has
released a new report sharply criticizing quality control
procedures at LyphoMed Inc., which makes drugs to fight symptoms of
AIDS and other diseases.
   An FDA official said Monday a re-inspection of LyphoMed's main
manufacturing plant found the same sort of problems that led the
agency to take disciplinary action against the suburban Chicago
company last fall.
   LyphoMed said Monday it intends to respond to the latest
inspection report later this week.
   ``We are committed to ensuring that our quality meets and
exceeds the FDA standards,'' said John N. Kapoor, LyphoMed's
chairman and chief executive officer.
   LyphoMed gained national prominence for its sales of
pentamidine, a drug used to fight a form of pneumonia that
frequently kills people with AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency
syndrome.
   In November, the federal agency warned LyphoMed it could be
taken to court if ``serious violations'' of FDA regulations were
not corrected, and it suspended approval of the company's
applications to market new drugs.
   The latest FDA report listed 44 violations of ``good
manufacturing practices'' found during a three-month inspection.
   Violations cited included shipping products that had failed some
sterility tests, changing the manufacturing process for several
drugs without knowing the effect of the changes, distributing drugs
without proper FDA approval, and other quality control problems.
   George Bailey, a compliance officer at the FDA's Chicago
district, said the problems were the same type of violations as
cited last fall, Bailey said.
   ``The severity and degree of the violations is yet to be
determined,'' he said.
   LyphoMed said in a statement that it had appointed a new
director of quality control and a new director of regulatory
affairs since November.
   The discovery of new or continuing violations doesn't
necessarily mean the FDA will continue its suspension of work
processing LyphoMed's applications to market new drugs, Bailey said.
   ``It depends on how significant the deviations would be and what
they have done to correct them,'' he said.
   A former LyphoMed employee, Richard Johnson, filed a lawsuit
earlier this month claiming the company had fired him because he
refused to release drugs that had failed quality tests. LyphoMed
has said he was fired for ``performance reasons.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
