<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Hungary-Protests     03-15 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hungary-Protests,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>10,000 March In Protest Through Budapest Streets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 10,000 protesters marched through
the streets of this Communist capital today calling for democracy
and freedom of the press.
   Dozens of police patrols passed by, but authorities made no
attempt to hinder the unofficial protest, which came on the
anniversary of Hungary's aborted 1848 revolution against Austria.
   Protesters carried signs that read ``We Want Democracy'' and
``We Want Freedom of the Press'' and chanted anti-government
slogans.
   Groups of demonstrators whistled and applauded when police
vehicles passed by, but authorities refused to act on what appeared
to be attempts to provoke them.
   The protesters blocked traffic and attracted large groups of
passers-by, some of whom joined the throng as it meandered through
central Budapest.
   Dissident sources said four prominent activists were detained in
advance of the unofficial protest. The sources earlier report three
activists had been taken into custody.
   Communist party authorities, meanwhile, held an official rally
to mark the anniversary on the steps of Budapest's national museum,
where the 1848 revolution broke out.
   Communist party officials laid wreaths and made speeches calling
for greater national unity and economic progress.
   Hungarian dissidents have marked the anniversay by staging
unofficial rallies on March 15 since 1973, and have met with
varying reactions from authorities.
   Last year, police allowed thousands of people to march through
downtown Budapest, calling for democracy as part of one of the
biggest unofficial protests here in years.
   But in 1986, police clashed with protesters on March 15, and
broke up that year's unofficial demonstration.
   Hungary has won a reputation as a relatively liberal Soviet bloc
country, although far less dissent is tolerated than in Western
countries.
   One dissident source identified three of the activists detained
this morning as writer Miklos Haraszti, Tamas Mlynar and Gabor
Demszky, Hungary's biggest underground publisher.
   The source, who asked not to be named, said two other activists
_ Ottilia Solt and writer Gyoergy Gado _ may also have been taken
into custody. He said friends were unable to reach them early today.
   Sources speculated the activists were detained to warn
dissidents away from the unofficial protest, and predicted they
would be relased later today.
   Police have raided the homes of at least eight dissidents during
the past two weeks, including Gado, Solt and Demszky, sources told
The Associated Press.
   During the police search, hundreds of copies of unofficial
journals, political documents and books were confiscated, Haraszti
said.
</TEXT>
