<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--1951Killing     03-15 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--1951 Killing,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Carnival Worker Pleads Innocent to 1951 Murder Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEDIA, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former carnival worker has pleaded innocent
to charges of murdering an eight-year-old girl in 1951.
   Assistant Public Defender Michael Malloy entered the plea Monday
in Delaware County Common Pleas Court on behalf of his client,
William Henry Redmond.
   Redmond, 66, suffering from a heart condition and emphysema, sat
in a wheelchair and said nothing during the arraignment.
   A pretrial hearing is scheduled for April 11.
   At a preliminary hearing in February, State Police Trooper
Malcolm Murphy said Redmond had confessed to smothering Jane Marie
Althoff. Her body was found in a carnival truck in Trainer, a small
town about 15 miles southeast of Philadelphia, on April 25, 1951.
   Redmond, who was living in Grand Island, Neb., at the time of
his arrest, is charged with first- and second-degree murder,
voluntary and involuntary manslaughter, kidnapping and assault with
intent to ravish.
   Redmond is being held without bail in Delaware County Prison.
</TEXT>
