<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iran-Iraq 2ndLd-Writethru   03-15 0677</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0540,0693</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Claims More Missile Attacks On Tehran</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with eight grafs to UPDATE with new missile attack,
correct name of tanker to Gas Prince, sted Gas Queen; picks up 8th
graf pvs: The Iraqi...; SUBS penultimate graf, bgng ``The
46,723-ton...,'' to correct tanker name; picks up last graf: The
convoy...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said it fired six missiles into
Tehran today and its air force bombed other Iranian cities. Iran
said it pounded southern Iraqi towns with shells, short-range
rockets and warplane raids.
   Iran said civilians were killed in Iraqi missile attacks and
Iraq said Iranian shelling killed nine civilians in the city of
Basra.
   In New York, the Soviet Union acknowledged it failed to win
support for a U.N. Security Council resolution calling for an end
to the deadly missile duel in the 7{-year-old war.
   The U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tanker Gas Prince was sailing up the
Persian Gulf in the 17th convoy conducted by the U.S. Navy this
year.
   The Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, said six missiles
were fired into the Iranian capital today. It reported eight such
missiles strikes Monday.
   Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored in Nicosia,
said ``a number'' of civilians were killed in missile attacks on
residential areas of Tehran overnight. It did not say how many
rockets hit the city.
   On Monday, Iran said missiles killed 26 civilians and wounded 50
in Tehran. Iraq also reported civilian casualties in Baghdad but
gave no figures.
   Iraq says it has fired 15 missiles into Tehran since the duel
resumed with a single rocket fired into the Iranian capital Sunday
night after a two-day truce. Iran has fired two into Baghdad.
   The Iraqi agency said warplanes pounded the western Iranian
cities of Dezful, Kermanshah and Hamadan today in ``destructive''
raids. IRNA said sores of civilians were killed.
   Iran said its artillery shelled Basra province, whose capital is
Iraq's second-largest city, and fired 11 short-range rockets into
the region. The Iraqi agency quoted its correspondent in Basra as
saying nine civilians were killed and 10 wounded.
   Tehran radio said Iranian warplanes bombed Al-Amarah, about
halfway between Basra and Baghdad, and the northeastern town of
Sulaymaniyah.
   IRNA said Monday that Revolutionary Guards commandos pushed to
within 12 miles of Sulaymaniyah. It said the Iranians seized a
dozen peaks and several villages, killing or wounding 1,000 Iraqis.
   Iraq said the latest round of missile attacks was a reprisal for
Iran's shelling of Iraqi border towns Sunday night in which at
least 21 civilians were killed and 80 wounded.
   Baghdad earlier charged Iran broke a Friday cease-fire by
launching ground attacks and bombarding Iraqi towns.
   An uneasy two-day truce brought a brief respite after 12 days in
which both sides fired dozens of missiles and artillery fire and
launched air raids that killed or wounded hundreds of civilians.
   At the United Nations, Soviet Ambassador Alexander Belonogov
acknowledged Monday that the Soviet bid for a new resolution on the
``war of the cities'' had failed after the Security Council met
behind closed doors.
   ``Our personal preference would be a resolution of the Security
Council,'' he said, but the important thing is ``not the form but
the essence'' of the council's action.
   The United States saw the proposal as a maneuver designed to
deflect attention from the American push for a worldwide arms
embargo against Iran to punish it for refusing to honor the
council's July 20 cease-fire resolution and peace plan.
   Instead of a new resolution, the council is expected to issue a
statement later this week calling for an end to the missile attacks.
   The 46,723-ton Gas Prince, a liquefied-gas carrier was sighted
off Dubai at midday. It was escorted by the missile frigate
Simpson, witnesses reported.
   The convoy was the 39th since July, when the U.S. Navy began
escorting 11 Kuwaiti tankers, re-registered under the American
flag, to protect them from Iranian attack. There have been no
direct attacks on any of the vessels since the escort operations
began.
</TEXT>
