<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 1130EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BusDrivers     03-15 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Drivers,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Department Agrees to Compromise on 17-year-old Drivers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DUBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Labor Department has agreed to
allow South Carolina and North Carolina limited use of 17-year-old
school bus drivers through the end of the school year.
   The governors of the two states today announced the agreement
overriding a February order that had required a halt to the young
drivers by April 1.
   ``During our discussions with (Labor) Secretary (Ann)
McLaughlin, I think it became apparent that our school children
would be a lot safer riding with 17-year-olds with seven or eight
months of bus driving experience than it would be to have them
riding with drivers who have little or no experience driving a
school bus,'' North Carolina Gov. Jim Martin said.
   Without the extension there wouldn't be enough trained drivers
to transport students, the governors contended.
   Under the agreement, all districts in both states may use
drivers who will turn 18 before June 15. And certain districts that
have had difficulty hiring older drivers may through the end of the
school year use 17-year-old drivers who will not turn 18 by June 15.
   All 17-year-old drivers must have been hired and trained before
the school year began and must have clean driving records, the
agreement said.
   North Carolina has about 2,100 17-year-old drivers; South
Carolina has about 1,200.
   Tucker Eskew, a spokesman for South Carolina Gov. Carroll
Campbell, estimated several hundred 17-year-old drivers in that
state would turn 18 by June 15.
   Seventeen-year-olds have been permitted to drive school buses in
the two states under an exemption to the Fair Labor Standards Act.
   That was repealed after Labor Department investigations found
North Carolina had violated the act 80 times in January and
February, and South Carolina had recorded 200 violations in that
time.
   The investigation was triggered when a 4-year-old boy in West
Columbia, S.C., was struck and killed by a 17-year-old driver with
a bad driving record.
   Martin said in a statement today that he would seek a $24
million from the legislature in June to increase the school bus
drivers pay so the state can attract more adult drivers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
