<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 1131EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese-Pipeline     03-15 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Pipeline,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-NSC Staff Member Testifies Before Grand Jury</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former National Security Council staff member
Roger Robinson appeared before a federal grand jury today in the
criminal investigation of Attorney General Edwin Meese III and a
proposed $1 billion Iraqi oil pipeline.
   Robinson worked closely with longtime Meese friend E. Robert
Wallach in the summer of 1985, when supporters of the pipeline were
seeking U.S. support for the project.
   Robinson is the second NSC aide in two weeks to testify in the
probe of Meese being conducted by independent counsel James McKay.
Former NSC aide David Wigg testified earlier.
   In addition, two former aides in Meese's office, John Richardson
and John Harrison, testified last week before the grand jury to
which McKay's office is presenting evidence. Richardson was Meese's
chief of staff before leaving the Justice Department several months
ago. Harrison worked on Meese's staff in mid-1985.
   The probe of Meese revolves around whether he may have violated
the 1977 Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, which prohibits bribes by
U.S. companies or their agents to foreign officials.
   Wallach wrote a memo to Meese in September 1985 saying that a
portion of up to $700 million from the pipeline would be paid to
the Israeli Labor Party. Meese says he doesn't recall reading the
portion of the memo relating to planned Labor Party payments.
   Wallach had been hired by Swiss oilman Bruce Rappaport to assist
in the project and Wallach went to Meese on the matter in May 1985.
Meese referred him to then-National Security Adviser Robert
McFarlane, who directed that Robinson assist the project.
   Iraq was seeking an insurance package for the pipeline in the
event it was bombed by Israel. Then-Israeli Prime Minister Shimon
Peres gave assurances that Israel would not attack the line, but
Iraq wanted a financial package to back up that promise.
   The NSC aides assisted on a number of proposed packages,
initially trying to promote a $400 million bank-backed package
acceptable to the Overseas Private Investment Corp. The government
agency insures foreign investments by U.S. firms such as Bechtel
Group Inc., which was going to build the project.
   Robinson left the NSC and his place on the project was taken by
Wigg, who worked with Wallach on alternative proposals. Those
included pledging U.S. aid to Israel as a guarantee for the
pipeline and seeking to put Pentagon budget money for Israel in an
overseas escrow account as insurance. None of the insurance
proposals was adopted and the pipeline wasn't built.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
