<DOCNO> AP880315-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 1136EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Cabinet-VA     03-15 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cabinet-VA,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Finds Little Evidence That Cabinet Status Would Improve VA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An independent study group said today it could
find little evidence that elevating the Veterans Administration to
a Cabinet-level department would help the agency do its job better.
   The group and the General Accounting Office, the investigative
arm of Congress, said changes in the way the VA is managed should
be made whether or not the agency is granted cabinet status.
   In a report to the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee, a
panel of the National Academy of Public Administration said it was
not making a recommendation for or against a Cabinet-level VA.
   William Fischer, chairman of the academy's seven-member study
group, said the panel did not take a vote on elevating the VA to
Cabinet status, but he said, ``We did agree on the report.''
   ``We are not here to discuss the priority of meeting the needs
... of veterans,'' Fischer told the committee. ``We are discussing
... structure.''
   The panel, which did the study in seven weeks, found ``little
evidence that the prospects of fulfilling the vital mission of
providing for the present and future needs of veterans would be
materially improved by elevating the VA to a Cabinet department.''
   The panel also said it does not believe the elevation to
Cabinet-status ``would significantly improve either access to the
president, the adequacy of necessary resources, or the
organization, management and delivery of high-quality services and
benefits.
   ``The panel does recognize the potential political value of
raising the public visibility of the needs of veterans and the
programs designed to meet these needs by making VA a department in
the president's Cabinet,'' the report said. ``However, given the
broad political support which already exists for the VA and its
programs, the gain would be at the margin.''
   Legislation to elevate the VA has been endorsed by President
Reagan and was approved by the House on Nov. 17. There has been
strong support in the Senate for passage.
   Governmental Affairs Committee chairman, Sen. John Glenn,
D-Ohio, said at today's hearing: ``If the elevation of the VA to
Cabinet-level status is accompanied by significant measures to
improve the management and operation of the agency, as well as to
ensure the fair treatment of all veterans seeking access to agency
services and benefits, then the case for elevation becomes much
stronger.''
   Glenn said improvements within the VA legislation ``should be
the goal of this committee over the next few weeks.''
   The National Academy for Public Administration, chartered by
Congress, provides independent advice on the organization and
operation of government at all levels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
