<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BuriedCars     03-15 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Buried Cars,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deputies Seek `Hard Worker' Who Allegedly Buried Stolen Cars And
Wastes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HESPERIA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who spent months industriously
burying stolen cars, trucks and other equipment in the back yard of
his rural home was being sought today, officials said.
   The man, identified as Korey Cragg, jumped out a back window of
his home when he was questioned by a deputy, sheriff's Detective
Allan L. Foreman said. Cragg was being sought for an alleged role
in a car-stripping operation.
   By Monday afternoon officials had unearthed more than a dozen
cars and trucks plus various equipment and car parts, officials
said. They also discovered numerous buried 55-gallon drums
containing motor oil, gasoline and transmission fluid.
   For months, residents living in the desert 65 miles northeast of
Los Angeles had watched as Cragg buried the vehicles with a
backhoe, Foreman said.
   ``A neighbor told us he was hauling out a trailer load of
engines every other day,'' Foreman said. ``He was a busy, busy boy.
It appears he was working 24 hours a day. ... He could go through
two or three cars a day.''
   Sylvestre Carrillo, who lives in a home just east of the house,
said he thought his neighbor was ``just a hard worker.''
   ``He'd be at it day and night,'' Carrillo said. ``He was a
pretty good mechanic, or so we thought.''
   Someone finally called the sheriff after seeing Cragg bury an
almost-new car over the weekend, and a deputy confronted Cragg on
Sunday.
   After answering a couple of questions, Cragg excused himself to
go to the bathroom. Instead, he climbed out a back bedroom window
and fled, Foreman said.
   Police found a stolen red Corvette in the garage and secured a
search warrant, Foreman said.
   Three people inside the house at the time were booked for
investigation of grand theft auto, a jail deputy in Victorville, 10
miles north of here, said. They were identified as Cragg's wife,
Kathy, 27, of Hesperia, and Brian Powell, 26 and Sheryl VanSanford,
28, both of Los Angeles County.
   Bail was set at $200,000 each and the three were scheduled for
arraignment Wednesday in Victorville Municipal Court, the deputy
said.
   On Monday, county detectives-turned-archaeologists returned to
excavate the cache of stolen property.
   The car-stripping operation apparently started about five months
ago, and Foreman said officialos had not idea how many vehicles
they might eventually find. He said investigators expect to find
even more buried cars in the surrounding desert.
   ``That's just a guess at this time,'' said Foreman. ``Neighbors
say he would haul the backhoe out into the desert to bury stuff.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
