<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Greece-Vatican     03-15 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Greece-Vatican,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greece to Open its First Embassy at Vatican</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greece will open its first embassy at the
Vatican in a move that comes in the wake of improving relations
between the Greek Orthodox and Roman Catholic churches, a senior
foreign ministry official said Tuesday.
   The diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the move
had no direct connection to easing of 900-year-old religious
tensions and Pope John Paul II's meeting with Orthodox Patriarch
Dimitrios I in December.
   He said the decision to open the embassy was made before the two
met.
   Greece established diplomatic relations with the Vatican 10
years ago. Its ambassador in Paris has been accredited there.
   The Greek Orthodox Church is one of the autonomous Eastern
Orthodox churches organized mainly along national lines. It
recognizes the leadership of the patriarch of Constantinople,
modern-day Istanbul, Turkey, rather than that of the pope.
   The Greek diplomat said the decision to send an ambassador was
approved by the Greek parliament last month. He did not say when an
ambassador will be picked.
</TEXT>
