<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JordanCommandos 3rdLd-Writethru a0610 03-15 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jordan Commandos, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0610,0604</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman, Daughter Safely Back In Texas After Commando Rescue</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS two grafs at end, no official Jordanian comment,
Jordanian citizen reported detained</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman and her daughter have returned to Texas
after retired U.S. commandos hired for $200,000 grabbed the girl in
Jordan where she had been taken by her father in a custody dispute,
newspapers reported today.
   Meanwhile, the United States expressed regret to Jordan over the
incident, and an American Embassy officer in Amman was recalled to
Washington for questioning about his knowledge of the affair, State
Department spokesman Charles Redman said Monday in Washington.
   The Philadelphia Inquirer reported on Saturday that the woman
and the commandos entered Jordan and seized Lauren Bayan, 7, from a
school bus Jan. 28 in Jerash, north of Amman.
   The woman had been identified at Kathy Mahoon, but Holly
Planells, head of American Children Held Hostage, said her name is
Cathy Phelps Mahone, The Dallas Morning News and the Dallas Times
Herald reported today.
   The woman claims her ex-husband, Jordanian-born Mohammed Ali
Bayan, kidnapped the child and took her to Jordan although she was
granted custody of the child following a divorce.
   Dallas County court records confirm that a judge granted Ms.
Mahone custody of her daughter, but police say they have no record
of the reported kidnapping in September.
   ``She (Ms. Mahone) called me from Texas and said they're alive
and well and very happy,'' Ms. Planells, of White Plains, N.Y.,
told the Morning News on Monday.
   ``She's really getting assimilated back to American life,'' Ms.
Plannels said, referring to the girl. ``It was a traumatic
experience to be away from her mother like that. Jordan is a
strange place.''
   Ms. Plannels declined to say where Ms. Mahone is, saying the
woman fears her husband ``will try this again.''
   Ms. Mahone, unable to get her daughter back through legal
channnels, hired former Army commandos to take the girl away from
her father, who claimed legal custody of the child under Jordanian
law, the Inquirer reported Saturday.
   Corporate Training Unlimited, a company in Fayetteville, N.C.,
that specializes in ``hostage rescue training,'' plotted and
carried out the seizure, the newspaper said.
   The Times Herald quoted Ms. Planells as saying the operation
cost Ms. Mahone $200,000. Ms. Mahone has mentioned the possibility
of a movie deal about the raid, Ms. Planells said.
   Company president Donald Feeney denied the story, but other
well-placed sources described the company's role, the Inquirer said.
   Bayan reported his daughter had been abducted by three Americans
and he published newspaper advertisements seeking information.
   Sameer Salem, a Jordanian friend of Bayan's, told The Associated
Press that Bayan had returned to Jordan in fall 1987 after selling
a Dallas restaurant called The Country Skillet.
   The recalled American Embassy official, who was not named, had
some knowledge prior to the incident that the group had arrived in
Jordan, Redman said. But the officer had been misled as to its
intentions.
   ``We have expressed regret to the government of Jordan for any
role that an embassy officer might have played in this violation of
Jordanian law,'' Redman said.
   There was no official comment from Jordanian authorities.
However, one Jordanian official, who did not want his name used,
said a Jordanian citizen was involved in getting the girl out of
Jordan.
   He said the man was an employee of an agency which does security
work for the U.S. Embassy and that he had been detained for
questioning. He did not give the man's name.
</TEXT>
