<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GermanyProtest     03-15 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany Protest,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>300 March in East Germany to Demand More Freedom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEIPZIG, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 300 protesters defied police
orders and marched in a human chain to demand greater freedom from
the communist government, witnesses said Tuesday.
   Police did not intervene except to order by loudspeaker that the
demonstrators disperse, the witnesses said, speaking on condition
of anonymity. The demonstration came Monday on the second day of
the Leipzig Trade Fair, which draws visitors from 100 nations.
   The protesters came out of a ``peace prayer'' in the Nicholas
Church in downtown Leipzig, marched about 500 yards to another
church where they sang songs, and then walked back to where they
began, said the witnesses. The protesters voluntarily left after
about 40 minutes.
   They were among more than 1,000 people who attended the prayer
service at the Lutheran church, according to the witnesses.
   Church officials speaking at the hour-long prayer service were
applauded when they demanded greater freedom for East Germans and
an end to legal actions against those who want to leave the
country, the witnesses said.
   An unidentified church official was quoted as telling the
congregation that the country needs laws in line with international
conventions.
   Officials of East Germany's Lutheran Church have become
increasingly outspoken in favor of improved human rights conditions
in the country.
   The witnesses also said government officials banned a Monday
night rally where activists had planned to publicize the plight of
East Germans who are denied the right to leave the country.
</TEXT>
