<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Nigeria-Population     03-15 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Nigeria-Population,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nigeria to Press on With Disputed Population Control Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Nigerian official said Tuesday the
government will press ahead with its population control project
over the objections of Christian leaders who argue it favors
Moslems.
   The plan to curtail the growth rate in black Africa's most
populous nation, with about 95 million people, created considerable
controversy when it was announced last month. Christian leaders
said it favored the country's Moslem majority because Christian men
may only have one wife while Moslem men can marry up to four women.
   Several prominent women have demanded that the government also
institute a plan to limit Nigerian men to one wife.
   The government's population control plan attempts to limit women
to four children through education campaigns.
   Air Marshal Ibrahim Alfa of the Armed Forces Ruling Council said
the government intended to advance the plan anyway. ``This is a
policy that will take some time to take hold, and we are quite
aware of the problems it would face,'' he said.
</TEXT>
