<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 1251EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Cabinet-LevelVA     03-15 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cabinet-Level VA,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Studies Say Changes Needed at VA, With or Without Cabinet-Level
Status</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Significant changes in the way the Veterans
Administration is being managed should be made whether or not it is
elevated to Cabinet status, a Senate committee was told Tuesday.
   A panel of the National Academy of Public Administration, an
independent study group, and the General Accounting Office, the
investigative arm of Congress, did not make recommendations on
whether the VA should become part of the president's cabinet.
   But in its reports to the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee,
the seven-member academy panel said it found ``little evidence'' in
its study that Cabinet-level status would materially improve the
VA's mission of providing for the present and future needs of
veterans.
   ``The panel does not believe that such an elevation would
significantly improve either access to the president, the adequacy
of necessary resources, or the organization, management and
delivery of high-quality services and benefits,'' the report said.
   The panel said it ``does recognize the potential political value
of raising the public visibility of the needs of veterans and the
programs designed to meet these needs by making VA a department in
the president's Cabinet. However, given the broad political support
which already exists for the VA and its programs, the gain would be
at the margin.''
   The GAO said signficant changes are needed in the way the VA is
being managed, and that they should be made whether or not the
agency is granted Cabinet status.
   ``To appropriately manage any large, decentralized organization,
top management must have reliable information on each unit's output
and the resources used to achieve the output,'' the office said.
``GAO reports have documented situations in which top managers were
unaware of inefficient or poor quality services because they lacked
complete, reliable and accurate data and the incentives to use
those data to improve service delivery.''
   The GAO recommended that the VA's deputy administrator, or the
undersecretary if the VA is made a cabinet department, be given the
responsibility for the agency's day-to-day management.
   The academy panel said it had seen reports of internal
weaknesses in the VA. However, it concluded that a Cabinet
department is not required to make necessary improvements,
``although the creation of more presidential appointments could
improve the quality of veterans programs by attracting better
managers.''
   A Cabinet-level VA could possibly achieve more uniformity of
broad, cross-cutting national policy goals, the panel conceded.
However, it said, ``there are other mechanisms now in place or
available which have been, and could be, used to accomplish these
purposes whether or not the VA is elevated to be a Cabinet
department although Cabinet status might make the current
mechanisms work more effectively.''
   President Reagan has endorsed legislation to raise the VA to
Cabinet status. The House passed a similar bill last Nov. 17. There
also has been strong support in the Senate for passage of the
legislation.
   The VA is an independent agency created in 1930. It provides
health, disability, pension and death benefits to veterans, as well
as loans and educational programs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
