<2ND_LINE>AM-Demjanjuk,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judges Admit New Evidence in War Atrocities Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judges in John Demjanjuk's war crimes trial
granted a defense request Tuesday to admit new evidence from 15
Holocaust survivors who failed to identify the retired Ohio
autoworker as a Nazi guard.
   Defense attorney Yoram Sheftel said the new evidence casts doubt
on testimony from five Treblinka death camp survivors who
identified Demjanjuk from a 1942 photograph as ``Ivan the
Terrible.'' Prisoners used that nickname for the guard who operated
gas chambers that killed 850,000 Jews in Nazi-occupied Poland.
   ``There are 15 statements of Treblinka survivors who did not
identify Demjanjuk as Ivan versus five who did,'' Sheftel told
Israel radio. ``This evidence is extremely substantial and
extremely important.''
   The three-judge panel interrupted its deliberations Tuesday to
consider the new evidence during a special session in Jerusalem
District Court. Demjanjuk's year-long trial ended Feb. 18.
   The judges set a court session for Monday to allow prosecutors
and defense attorneys to address the new evidence in summary
arguments, assistant prosecutor Eliyahu Avram said.
   The Ukrainian-born Demjanjuk, 67, retired as a Cleveland-area
autoworker and says he is the victim of mistaken identity.
   Sheftel said the latest evidence also includes statements
revealing there were at least six Nazi guards who resembled
Demjanjuk at Treblinka.
   Sheftel said he received the new evidence last week. A federal
judge in Washington ordered the Justice Department to release the
documents after Demjanjuk's family sued for them under the Freedom
of Information act.
</TEXT>
