<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CapitolSecurity     03-15 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Capitol Security,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Capitol Police Seized 1,162 Weapons Last Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Capitol Police, who have arrested visitors
carrying an Uzi machine gun, a pistol disguised as a beeper and
soda bottles containing explosives, are worried about a 147 percent
surge in weapons seizures at the Capitol last year.
   The police confiscated 1,162 weapons from visitors entering the
Capitol or six adjacent House and Senate office buildings in 1987,
up from 470 weapons seizures the previous year, according to House
Sergeant at Arms Jack Russ.
   Russ is citing these figures to lobby for an $18.5 million plan
to tighten security on the House side of the Capitol, including
bombproof glass around the visitors' gallery overlooking the House
chamber.
   Russ said in an interview that most of the weapons last year
were seized from visitors who were unaware of gun control
restrictions at the Capitol and had no criminal intent. These
included constituents carrying out-of-state gun permits that are
invalid on the Capitol grounds.
   Of the 1,162 arrests on illegal weapons charges last year, he
said, only 63 were prosecuted, compared with 50 arrests prosecuted
in 1986.
   The House security plan being pushed by Russ calls for spending
$4.2 million to install shatterproof glass shields around the House
visitors' gallery and modify seats on the chamber floor to protect
against bomb blasts.
   He also is requesting a $4.7 million emergency telephone system
to alert every House office immediately to a terrorist attack,
$413,352 worth of additional bomb detectors in House office
buildings, a $3.5 million electronic card system for access to
House garages, and a $5.7 million alarm system connecting
home-district offices with local police.
   Strict anti-terrorist proposals, such as placing a wrought iron
security fence around the Capitol grounds and glass enclosures
around the House and Senate galleries, have been widely criticized
in the past.
   Many legislators argue that the Capitol, as a symbol of open
democracy, should be easily accessible to the public. But Russ says
this is unrealistic because of growing security threats.
   ``I think everybody _ me included _ would like the easy-going
atmosphere of a Mayberry RFD police force, with a friendly cop
directing traffic,'' Russ said. ``But in this day and time, you
also need a high-tech, well-trained police department. You've got
to have both.''
   Russ outlined his plan last week at a House Appropriations
subcommittee hearing on the proposed $1.96 billion budget for
congressional operations next year, and plans to seek spending
authority from a separate House committee.
   Still awaiting action by the House and Senate leadership is a
more sweeping security plan that calls for fencing in the Capitol
Plaza, a parking ban on the East Front plaza and gatehouses to
screen visitors before they enter the Capitol grounds.
   Although only authorized vehicles are permitted to enter the
Capitol grounds, pedestrians may enter unhindered and are not
screened for illegal weapons until enter the Capitol building
itself, or adjacent office buildings.
   The comprehensive security plan for the entire Capitol area has
been approved by the Capitol Police Board, consisting of the House
and Senate sergeants at arms, the Capitol Police chief and the
architect of the Capitol.
   A $13 million appropriation to implement the plan remains
largely unspent, awaiting a final go-ahead from congressional
leaders. Russ said he hopes the leaders will meet before the end of
April to review the broader plan.
   Meanwhile, police are using hydraulically operated, steel street
barricades to halt unauthorized vehicles at the two main traffic
entrances to the Capitol grounds. In addition, large concrete
flower and shrubbery pots stand along driveways and sidewalks to
thwart any attempted truck bombings of the Capitol.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
