<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Ozone 2ndLd-Writethru a0475 03-15 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ozone, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0475,680</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 6th graf pvs, ``At this, to CORRECT typo in Rowland's
name and spelling of ``Irvine.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The protective ozone layer over the United
States appears to have shrunk about 2.3 percent since 1969,
scientists said today in the most thorough study yet of ozone
depletion.
   Experts have estimated that a 1 percent depletion could mean a 5
percent to 6 percent increase in skin cancers.
   But today's report from the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration, the work of more than 100 experts over 17 months,
put the annual ozone depletion over the mid-latitudes of the
northern hemisphere at a much higher rate.
   Those latitudes, 30 degrees to 64 degrees, take in all of the
United States except southern Texas, Louisiana and Florida and
extend halfway up Canada's Yukon Territory.
   The scientists laid the responsibility for the ozone depletion
squarely on chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs), chemicals used to power
some aerosol sprays.
   ``At this point there is no other culprit to blame,'' said
Sherwood Rowland of the University of California at Irvine. ``We
have taken out all the natural phenomena that are believed to
affect ozone.''
   The report also said that the annual springtime depletion of
ozone over Antarctica appears to be diluting ozone yearround over
the Southern Hemisphere to about 60 degrees southern latitude, a
point midway between the tip of the Antarctic Peninsula and Cape
Horn at the southern tip of South America.
   Rowland, who headed one NASA study groups, said the scientists
had re-examined years of ground-based and satellite observations of
the atmosphere to remove the normal biennial fluctuations of many
atmospheric characteristics and also the effects of the 11-year
solar cycle.
   The ground-based observations were limited to mid-latitudes in
the Northern Hemisphere because there are few stations elsewhere in
the world. But never before have scientists re-analyzed the monthly
data at differing latitudes to try to remove the solar and biennial
fluctuations.
   Ozone in the atmosphere 15 miles to 25 miles up filters out the
sun's ultraviolet rays, making life on earth possible. The same
ultraviolet breaks up the CFC compounds, liberating chlorine, which
in turn destroys ozone.
   Ozone is a pollutant on the ground, but CFCs don't break up
there _ not enough ultraviolet gets through.
   CFCs were banned as aerosol propellants in the United States in
1978, and worldwide emissions declined. There was one report in
1983 from the National Academy of Sciences that said future ozone
decline would be only 2 percent to 4 percent.
   But CFC use started growing again, in part because one compound
turned out to be ideal for cleaning computer chips and other
electronic parts. Other major uses are for refrigeration fluids and
as blowing agents in making plastic foams.
   Then an annual ozone ``hole'' over the Antarctic was discovered,
and records going back to 1958 showed that it hadn't happened
before the late 1970s.
   Discovery of the ozone hole _ an annual Antarctic springtime
plunge in ozone concentrations, last year by a record 50 percent _
spurred treaty negotiators last fall in Montreal.
   The Environmental Protection Agency has estimated that a 1
percent thinning of the Earth's ozone shield means a 5 percent to 6
percent increase in skin cancer. If CFC use continued increasing at
2.5 percent per year, EPA said, 20 percent of the ozone barrier
could be gone in the next century.
   Today's report came one day after the Senate, on a vote of 83-0,
became the first major chemical-producing nation to ratify a
31-country treaty cutting emissions that damage the Earth's
protective ozone layer.
   The treaty commits the signers to a 50 percent cut from 1986
levels in production of compounds called chlorofluorocarbons, CFCs,
by 1998.
   The treaty will be officially ratified when the president signs
it. Though the United States will be the first major producer of
CFC compounds to ratify, it is not the first ratifier _ that is
Mexico.
   Under the treaty, EPA says, the decline would slow to the point
where it would be swamped by the normal year-to-year fluctuations.
   The Soviet Union has several CFC plants under construction, and
won concessions permitting it to exceed the treaty limits for a
time _ which led to a Soviet treaty signature in December. Similar
provisions were made for developing countries. If those exceptions
are used, the Environmental Defense Fund has estimated, the actual
1998 rollback in emissions could be 35 percent instead of 50
percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
