<HEAD>In Deathbed Interview, Porn Star Denied Witnessing Murder</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to delete reference to `deathbed,' INSERTS one graf
after 3rd pvs with time of interview not stated</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an interview with his biographer, porno
actor John C. Holmes said he did not know who was responsible for a
multiple murder in which he was a suspect, a newspaper reported
today.
   Holmes said that during the hours before four people were
bludgeoned to death and a fifth was maimed at a house in Laurel
Canyon on July 1, 1981, he was held at gunpoint at another house.
   The Los Angeles Times, relying on two unidentified sources
familiar with the manuscript of Holmes' as-yet-unpublished
biography, reported that after his captors let him go, he went to
the house where the killings occurred and discovered the bodies.
   The biography is based on extensive interviews with the actor,
but it was not clear when those interviews were conducted. One of
the sources said: ``John ... did not know up to the time of his
death who did the murders. He was not there when it happened.''
   Holmes died early Sunday at the Veterans Administration Medical
Center in Sepulveda at the age of 43. He died of pneumonia brought
on by AIDS, his second wife, Laurie, said Monday.
   Holmes, a leading sex film actor of the 1970s and early '80s,
was tried and acquitted in the murders in 1982. At the time of the
killings, Holmes was a cocaine addict.
   Within the last six weeks, homicide detectives again questioned
Holmes about his role in the killings, but he either refused or was
unable to answer, the Times reported.
   Attorneys James M. Eisenman and William D Kibanow confirmed
Monday that a biography of Holmes has been offered to several
publishers, but they declined to discuss its contents. The lawyers
represent Mrs. Holmes, 24, and her husband's estate. The
biographer's name was not revealed.
   Holmes had been hospitalized with acquired immune deficiency
syndrome since November.
   Authorities have theorized that the Laurel Canyon killings were
committed to avenge an armed robbery of nightclub owner Adel
Nasrallah, also known as Eddie Nash.
   Former Deputy District Attorney Ronald S. Coen, who prosecuted
the case, said Holmes was a middleman between Nash and a theft ring.
   Coen said Holmes set up the armed robbery of Nasrallah and later
was forced to lead the killers to the Laurel Canyon house where
members of the ring were staying.
</TEXT>
