<HEAD>Two State Prison Guards Charged In Alleged Murder-For-Hire Plot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two married Department of Corrections guards have
been charged with conspiring to kill two robbery witnesses for
$50,000, authorities said.
   The couple were to present their victims' index fingers as proof
the contract was completed, prosecutors said.
   Wayne Lyle Cox, 48, and Linda Rae Cox, 36, both of Navasota,
were being held Tuesday in Harris County jail in lieu of $250,000
bond each.
   The Coxes were correctional officers at the Pack 1 Unit in
Navasota. Cox had worked for the prison system for nearly six
years, while Mrs. Cox had been employed for nearly five years, said
TDC spokesman David Nunnelee.
   The case developed after a Harris County prisoner fighting
extradition to Arkansas on charges of robbing a jewelry store began
spreading word about seeking a contract killing for two store
employees, said Prosecutor Jon Munier.
   Before long, an undercover officer made contact with the Coxes,
who discussed the planned killing in recorded conversations, Munier
said.
   On March 11, Cox accepted $10,000 from the undercover officer as
a downpayment on the job, Munier said.
   The intended victims remain under guard in Arkansas, Munier said.
   ``Those people aren't the only hit teams this guy's got,''
Munier said. ``He's been robbing Zales jewelry stores in Texas and
all over, and he's got a lot of money to spend.''
