<HEAD>Moscow Rock Concerts Rescheduled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Bowie, Jennifer Rush, U-2 and other Western
rock groups will join Soviet musicians for a series of concerts to
raise money to fight drug addiction.
   The concerts, originally scheduled for this month, are to take
place in late April, the Novosti Press Agency said.
   Novosti did not give a date, but said the three six-hour
concerts will be held at the 30,000-seat Olympic Stadium in Moscow.
   The agency did not say why they were delayed, but sources close
to the organizers blamed the postponement on bureaucratic red tape.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said former
Beatles George Harrison and Paul McCartney, as well as Julian
Lennon, the son of the late Beatle John Lennon, had been invited.
It was unclear whether they would participate.
   The press agency said revenue from ticket sales will be donated
to the United Nations fund for the struggle against drug addiction
and to the Soviet toxicology research center.
   Sponsors include several Soviet organizations and trade
companies from the United States, West Germany and Hungary.
   Soviet officials denied reports of drug abuse in the country
until Mikhail S. Gorbachev's campaign for greater openness. Now,
newspaper stories often point out the problems and have disclosed
there are 50,000 diagnosed addicts and many more who may be
undiagnosed.
   Novosti said musicians from 10 North American and European
countries will peform along with several Soviet groups. Among the
foreign groups that have agreed to perform, Novosti said, are Level
42, Supertramp, U-2, Foreigner, Tangerine Dream, Bon Jovi, Jennifer
Rush and David Bowie.
   Participating Soviet groups are Aquarium, Bravo, Brigade S,
Black Coffee and others whose music ranges from heavy metal to
traditional rock 'n' roll, according to Novosti.
   Tickets will be about $16, much more expensive than for the
average Soviet concert. When Billy Joel performed in Moscow last
summer, tickets sold for a little under $8.
</TEXT>
