<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--GuardianAngels     03-15 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Guardian Angels,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guardian Angels Fined For Failing To Comply With Charity Laws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crimefighting Guardian Angels
illegally solicited $17,863 in Florida last year and will be fined
$450 for failing to comply with charity laws, officials say.
   The Division of Licensing cited the group last month for
violations in the first half of 1987. The Guardian Angels were
cited for soliciting funds without a license, hiring a private
fund-raiser without reporting it, failing to maintain records of
contributions and failing to have identification as a charitable
group while soliciting, said division spokesman Alan C. Rollins.
   Angels founder Curtis A. Sliwa, whose red-bereted army patrols
subways and neighborhoods in several cities, blamed the violations
on ignorance.
   The New York City-based Alliance of Guardian Angels Inc. now
complies with Florida laws, state spokesman Rollins said. In
reports filed last year, the group said it received $17,863 and
spent about $10,000.
   New York state records show the Angels received $117,139
nationwide last year, not including the value of free rent and
services. The group has debts of $122,086.
