<HEAD>Survivors of Post Office Massacre To Wed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDMOND, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two postal clerks who survived the Edmond
Post Office massacre that killed 14 of their co-workers plan to
marry in April.
   Debbie Smith and Steven Brehm said they will tie a yellow bow
around a gazebo post at the park where they say their vows to mark
the memory of those who were killed Aug. 20, 1986, by gunman
Patrick Sherrill.
   ``It is as if our friends will be there,'' said Ms. Smith.
   Ms. Smith and Brehm had been dating before the shooting. Brehm
has since transferred to the Lincoln, Neb., post office, and Ms.
Smith is on assignment in Oklahoma City, although she has applied
for a transfer to Lincoln.
   ``We still have nightmares,'' Ms. Smith said. ``But it's time we
get on with our lives,'' Brehm added.
   The couple escaped Sherrill's gunfire by running separately out
doors before the gunman returned and locked them. Sherrill fatally
shot himself to end the siege.
