<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-US     03-15 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-US,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Probing 29 Possible MIA Cases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam is investigating another 29
possible cases of Americans who never returned home from the
Vietnam War, a U.S. military official said Tuesday.
   The latest inquiry could represent a significant step in
resolving the fates of nearly 1,800 Americans listed as missing in
action since the United States withdrew its troops in 1973.
   ``The Vietnamese told us they are investigating 29 instances
where they have received information, material or remains,'' said
Lt. Col. Joe Harvey. ``But they said it will take at least three
weeks for them to draw any conclusions from these investigations or
to have remains to repatriate.''
   Harvey, commander of the U.S. Joint Casualty Resolution Center
based in Hawaii, returned Tuesday from four days of what he
described as ``positive and productive'' talks on accounting for
the MIAs. It was the fourth round of negotiations since retired
Gen. John W. Vessey, a presidential envoy, visited Vietnam in
August and the Vietnamese agreed to end a deadlock on the MIA issue.
   Harvey said his team provided new information to the Vietnamese.
He said it also visited the crash site of an American aircraft near
the major northern port of Haiphong, about 60 miles southeast of
Hanoi, but he gave no details.
   At least 27 U.S. aircraft were shot down when the United States
in December 1972 launched air strikes in the Hanoi-Haiphong area to
pressure the communists into signing a peace agreement.
   Harvey's team is composed of six experts from the casualty
center and the Army Central Identification Laboratory. Nguyen Can,
deputy director of the Foreign Ministry's North American affairs
department, headed the Vietnamese side at the talks.
   Vessey had asked the Vietnamese to give top priority to
resolving 70 ``discrepancy cases,'' in which the United States says
there is strong evidence that Vietnamese officials know the fates
of the missing Americans. These include cases where Americans
failed to emerge from prisoner of war camps.
   Since Vessey's talks, Vietnam has returned remains it believes
are those of Americans three times. The most recent, on March 2,
involved 17 sets of remains _ the largest turnover in two years and
the fourth largest since the war ended. The Vietnamese also turned
over reports on three other MIA cases.
   In exchange for Vietnamese cooperation on the MIA issue,
Washington has sent medical teams to Vietnam four times and
encouraged private U.S. agencies to provide assistance to
war-disabled Vietnamese. It has rejected calls for official aid
because of continued U.S. opposition to Vietnam's 9-year-old
military occupation of Cambodia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880315-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 1335EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-RodinoRetirement 1stLd-Writethru   03-15 0813</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rodino Retirement, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0492,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Longtime Civil Rights Advocate Steps Aside For Black Successor</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 3 grafs after 3rd pvs, bgng: Rodino, 78, with likely
successor; SUBS 18th graf pvs, bgng: In 1974, to CORRECT that
predecessor's defeat, sted death, gave Rodino the chairmanship</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The changing face of his home district finally
caught up with Rep. Peter Rodino, an Italian-American who spent 20
terms crusading for civil rights but who is now reluctantly giving
up his House seat to make way for a black successor.
   The New Jersey Democrat, who gained national prominence when he
chaired the impeachment hearings of former President Richard Nixon,
yielded Monday to calls from minority constituents who want one of
their own to represent them.
   Rodino, 78, one of the most senior members of the House and
chairman of its powerful Judiciary Committee, issued a statement
saying he would step aside in January.
   Texas Rep. Jack Brooks, the next ranking Democrat on the
committee the past 13 years, will be Rodino's likely successor.
   ``Chairing that committee would be an honor and a privilege
should my colleagues extend me that opportunity next year,'' said
Brooks, who currently heads the House Government Operations
Committee.
   Brooks would have to be officially named by the Democratic
Steering and Policy Committee and elected by the Democratic Caucus.
Committee members said they expected Brooks to be the next chairman.
   ``It is not without a sense of sadness that I am announcing my
decision to retire from the Congress at the end of this term,''
Rodino said.
   Although he did not mention the demands of blacks and other
minorities, who now comprise the majority in his district, Rodino
had been under increasing pressure to step aside. A host of black
leaders _ most notably Democratic presidential candidate Jesse
Jackson _ lauded his record but urged him to make way for what
would be New Jersey's first black member of Congress.
   In his statement, Rodino said, ``I believe that my part of the
journey in this great American experiment is at its end. I feel I
have served my time and a purpose.''
   Rodino arrived in Washington in 1948, a 38-year-old lawyer from
an Italian neighborhood in Newark, N.J., eager to represent the
bustling city in Congress.
   He became an institution in the intervening 40 years: fighting
for liberal legislation, controlling one of Congress' most powerful
committees and helping write into history the downfall of a
president.
   But in those same years, Newark decayed from the heart of the
Garden State into the brunt of jokes. Rodino's political base
eroded, and three black Democrats, including two Newark city
councilmen, announced plans this year to seek his 10th
Congressional District seat.
   Rodino, respected even by those calling on him to retire, had
survived earlier challenges. In 1984 and 1986, he won re-election
even though Jackson went to Newark to lead the retirement calls
himself.
   Backers, both black and white, noted Rodino served as House
floor manager for the landmark Civil Rights Act of 1966 and wrote
the 1982 Voting Rights Act. He is an honorary member of the
congressional Black Caucus and has been honored by the NAACP.
   ``Rodino is a good man,'' Jackson told the New York Times in
1986. ``That's not the issue. We can have a good man and black man
from New Jersey at the same time.''
   During his fight two years ago, Rodino hinted strongly he would
retire after another two-year term. He said said he wanted to stay
in Congress to counter the Reagan presidency.
   But, as Rodino began last year to raise campaign funds and plan
for re-election, black and white leaders in his party accused him
of breaking a promise.
   Aides said he wrote the resignation statement in his Capitol
Hill office on Monday, then left for his home. The announcement
brought immediate accolades for Rodino.
   ``I will miss his knowledge and his friendship. He sets an
extraordinarily high standard for whomever will succeed him,'' said
Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J.
   Rodino served nearly 20 years as a representative before being
thrust into the national spotlight.
   In 1974, barely a year after his predecessor's defeat in a
renomination battle gave Rodino the Judiciary Committee gavel, the
panel was charged with reviewing Nixon's role in the Watergate
affair.
   The televised proceedings won Rodino respect for his evenhanded
handling of an emerging national crisis. In an interview last year,
Rodino recalled weeping after he and a majority of committee
members voted to deliver articles of impeachment to the full House.
   Nixon resigned before the House voted.
   Rodino also served on the House Iran-Contra committee, which
investigated the Reagan administration's handling of the sale of
arms to Iran and the funneling of profits to the Nicaraguan Contra
rebels. He has been harshly critical of the Reagan administration's
handling of the arms-for-hostages debacle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
