<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-South Africa,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Urges Clemency for `Sharpville Six'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan today urged clemency for the
``Sharpeville Six'' in South Africa, saying such action would be
``welcomed by all Americans.''
   The six blacks are scheduled to be hanged Friday for being in a
mob outside a home where a township official was killed.
   In Johannesburg, South Africa, the Justice Ministry said
President P.W. Botha has refused to block the hangings, but added
that any further petitions for mercy would be given ``careful
consideration.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters, ``The
president urges clemency for the Sharpeville Six in South Africa on
compassionate and humanitarian grounds.''
   ``We implore the South African government to respond favorably
to these requests,'' Fitzwater said. ``An act of compassion such as
this by the South African government would be welcomed by all
Americans.''
   ``Our disgust for apartheid has been stated many times, and we
continue to speak out for its total elimination,'' the spokesman
said.
   He said the administration was appealing directly to South
African officials for clemency, as well as making the paublic
statement.
   He said the United States had previously appealed for clemency
in the case through public statements, support of a resolution in
the United Nations and representations at diplomatic talks in
Geneva.
   ``We are making this view known officially as well as publicly
to the South African government,'' he said.
</TEXT>
