<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Kirkpatrick-Gorbachev     03-15 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kirkpatrick-Gorbachev,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kirkpatrick Urges Talks to Reduce Soviet Conventional Forces in
Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States should give top priority to
negotiating reductions of 50 percent to 75 percent in conventional
military forces in the Soviet Union, and Eastern and Western
Europe, former U.N. Ambassador Jeane Kirkpatrick said Tuesday.
   Mrs. Kirkpatrick also said she believes the United States should
continue restrictions on trade with Moscow in an effort to win
human rights improvements inside the Soviet Union.
   ``So long as the Soviets do not permit the free flow of people
across the borders I do not believe it is appropriate for us to
permit the free flow of goods across borders,'' she said.
   At the same time, she said she is not opposed on principle to
expanding U.S.-Soviet trade ``as long as the trade is profitable to
us and does not subsidize them.''
   Mrs. Kirkpatrick commented at a hearing of the Commission on
Security and Cooperation in Europe which was organized to monitor
Soviet compliance with the human rights provisions of the Helsinki
accords.
   She said it was not ``inappropriate'' for the United States to
have signed the new Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces agreement
eliminating medium-range nuclear missiles worldwide.
   But she said she does not believe that agreements reducing
specific nuclear weapons systems are very important as long as the
Soviet Union and its Warsaw Pact allies retain superiority in
conventional forces.
   ``I think the top priority of the United States should be to
negotiate real reductions _ 50 percent to 75 percent _ in
conventional forces in Eastern Europe, the Soviet Union and Western
Europe,'' she said.
   The hearing was convened to explore the impact on the nations of
Eastern Europe of the reforms insituted in the Soviet Union by
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, general secretary of the Soviet Communist
Party.
   Mrs. Kirkpatrick called those reforms important, said they
should not be belittled and said of Gorbachev: ``I believe his
sincerity cannot be reasonably questioned.''
   ``I think in fact Gorbachev is the kind of man who would like to
dismantle the structure of oppression'' in order to revitalize the
stagnant Soviet economy and retain his nation's superpower status,
she said.
   ``He has made ... significant steps toward the release of
political prisoners and dissidents in the Soviet Union,'' she said.
   ``I think that for both internal and external reasons Gorbachev
has concluded that repression and reliance on force is
undesirable,'' she said. ``What we don't know is how far he is
willing to go.''
   Mrs. Kirkpatrick said there is relatively little U.S. policy can
do to influence the Soviets as the Gorbachev policies of glasnost
(openness) and perestroika (restructuring) run their course.
   Responding to questions, she said she does not believe that U.S.
negotiators should hold agreement on reductions in intercontinental
strategic nuclear weapons hostage to Soviet agreement to make human
rights improvements.
   ``I'm not personally in favor of using arms reduction to win
concessions in human rights,'' she said.
</TEXT>
