<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-Newspaper     03-15 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Newspaper,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Montreal Gets New English-Language Daily</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: All dollar figures U.S.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A colorful new English-language tabloid hit the
streets Tuesday in Montreal, the best-served newspaper market in
Canada with six dailies.
   The splashy Montreal Daily News was an instant success in this
bilingual city. Many newsstands sold out of the first press run of
80,000 copies.
   With minority-interest financial backing from Britain's Robert
Maxwell, owner of the London Daily Mirror, the new tabloid features
color pictures and the blue-collar standbys of sport, crime and sex.
   The lead headline was ``OUT _ No Appeal for Turk Refugees,'' a
story about the deportation of 40 Turks.
   The principal owner of the paper is Pierre Peladeau, whose
company Quebecor Inc. also produces Canada's leading
French-language daily, Le Journal de Montreal.
   Peladeau said he was prepared to invest $20 million in the
tabloid in the next five years to firmly establish it in an
English-language market previously monopolized by the serious-toned
broadsheet Montreal Gazette, circulation 196,000.
   The Daily News is the Gazette's first direct competitor since
the Montreal Star folded in 1979. Canada's second-biggest city is
also served by the French dailies La Presse, Le Devoir and Le Matin.
   The Gazette launched a new Sunday edition Feb. 28, but Daily
News publisher George MacLaren said, ``We're not publishing on
Sunday. If the advertisers want to try us, they'll try us anyway.''
   The new paper has an editorial staff of 76, many of whom sipped
champagne as the first issue ran off the presses.
   ``We're starting from scratch, and just about everybody is under
30,'' said business reporter Pierre Goad, 26.
</TEXT>
