<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NewsNielsens     03-15 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-News Nielsens,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS First in News Nielsens for Second Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS seems to have reclaimed the top spot in the
news Nielsens as the glow of the Winter Olympics wears off ABC.
   For the week ending March 11, the ``CBS Evening News'' had an
average rating of 11.1 and a 21 share, its second win in a row.
ABC's ``World News Tonight'' had a 10.2 and a 19 share. ``NBC
Nightly News'' had a 9.4 and 18 share.
   The rating is the percentage of the nation's 88.6 million
households with televisions. The share is a percentage of sets in
use.
   After a lengthy reign at the top of the news ratings last
summer, NBC is now struggling in third, although the close ratings
make the news race virtually a three-way tie.
   ``We're in the middle of a big investigation,'' said NBC analyst
Gerald Jaffe. He said the network is awaiting more information from
Nielsen on the February sweeps before deciding whether the slide is
a result of Nielsen's new people-meter sample or a real decline in
viewership.
   Jaffe pointed out that results from the November sweeps showed
NBC with a distinct disadvantage in local news lead-in. NBC
affiliates had an average rating of 11.5, which ``Nightly News''
improved on, to 11.9.
   CBS had the best advantage. Its affiliates had an average rating
of 12.9, and the network newscast improved on that to 13.1. ABC
affiliates averaged a 12.0 rating and the network broadcast was a
12.3.
   ``Network news is an island in a sea of local news,'' said
Jaffe. ``If the local news is going down, there's not much you can
do to keep the network news from going down, too.''
   If the Winter Olympics helped ABC to first in news, NBC can look
forward to potentially the same boost when it carries the Summer
Olympics.
</TEXT>
