<DOCNO> AP880315-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 1353EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-ContraAid 3rdLd-Writethru a0668 03-15 0860</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Aid, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0668,850</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House, pushing for new aid to the
Nicaraguan rebels, told congressional leaders today the Sandinista
regime appears to be preparing ``an all-out death blow'' against
the Contras, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said.
   Describing a lengthy meeting in which President Reagan discussed
the possibility of a new Contra aid package with lawmakers,
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater quoted national security adviser Colin
Powell as saying: ``The resistance program is on the verge of
collapse. It's only a matter of weeks.''
   Fitzwater said Reagan ``asked for bipartisan support to keep the
resistance from withering away and to prevent a dismantling of the
infrastructure that supports the Contras.''
   The spokesman said that in the Cabinet Room meeting, ``General
Powell outlined the buildup of Sandindista forces for an offensive
in the Bocay Valley, and it was indicated that Sandinista forces
appear to be preparing to launch an all-out death blow to the
Contras by destroying the supplies now in major Contra camps.''
   ``There was a considerable discussion of this turn of events ..
and the implication that has for the peace process,'' Fitzwater
said. But he stressed that no decisions were reached in the meeting
about how to proceed with a humanitarian aid package.
   ``I think everyone in there agreed it was a time to look forward
and to talk about how to fashion a new package, and let the fights
and arguments in the past stay there,'' the spokesman said. ``There
was no anger. ... Everyone, I think, was intense in the sense that
they think this was a time of decision for the national
government.''
   ``I think it's important to point out that everyone in that
session agreed a cease fire is what we're going after and that if
you get a cease fire, that relieves the tension for lethal aid and
for an awful lot of other kinds of aid,'' he said. ``The important
thing now is the humanitarian package that we could use to meet
their human needs.''
   Reagan, speaking to the Prime Ministers Club earlier, accused
the Sandinistas of practicing religious oppression, particularly
against Jews. He said President Daniel Ortega's government had
aligned itself with Libya, Cuba and the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, talking to reporters
following today's meeting Reagan, reiterated that he would be
willing to reconsider a $30 million humanitarian aid package that
was defeated 216-208 in the House on March 3.
   ``We told the president that we had worked very diligently,
Democrats and Republicans, to put together a package'' which was
defeated, Wright said. ``We would be glad to run it again if they
(the House Republicans) would be of a mind to vote for it.''
   Wright said it would be virtually impossible to suspend House
rules to get a vote on a new package this week, as the
administration wants.
   And one congressional supporter of renewed Contra aid, Sen.
David Boren, D-Okla., said an aid package he has been working on
was ``on hold'' for the moment while aid backers look for a way to
get agreement in the House, always the most problematic hurdle on
the Contra issue.
   Reagan, appearing before the Prime Ministers Club, a group of
approximately 150 supporters of the United Jewish Appeal, said that
among other reasons the United States should support the Contra
rebels is the oppression of Jews in Nicaragua.
   ``Few regimes today so blatantly sanction and practice official
anti-Semitism as the Sandinista communists in Nicaragua,'' Reagan
said. ``The Jewish community has been forced out almost entirely.
Managua's one synagogue has been defaced and firebombed. ... ''
   ``Nicaragua has officially aligned itself with Moammar
Gadhafi,'' he said, ``and, of course, the PLO _ an organization
that has again revealed its true colors, opposing our efforts for
peace and trumpeting its responsibility for a sickening terrorist
attack on a bus carrying Israeli men, woman and children.''
   Reagan said the Sandinistas ``have led the way in sponsoring
anti-Israel resolutions in United Nations. So I think it's time
that some in Congress who want to turn away from the reality of
left-wing anti-Semitism face the facts about the anti-Semitism of
the Sandinistas as well as their ties to the PLO and other
terrorist groups.''
   ``It is the Nicaraguan freedom fighters who are resisting this
kind of moral corruption,'' he said. ``It is the freedom fighters
who are fighting for the political, civil and human rights of Jews
and Christians in Nicaragua.''
   The rebels and the Sandinista government have agreed to sit down
and talk about their 7-year-old civil war on March 21-23 in the
town of Sapoa, Nicaragua, 90 miles south of Managua near the Costa
Rican border.
   Adolfo Calero, a political director of the umbrella opposition
group the Nicaraguan Resistance, is expected to represent the
rebels, and Defense Minister Humberto Ortega, brother of Nicaraguan
President Daniel Ortega, is to represent the leftist Sandinista
government.
   Nicaraguan Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo, who was removed as
mediator for the talks, will attend as a witness, along with Joao
Baena Soares, secretary general of the Organization of American
States.
</TEXT>
