<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Hepburn 1stLd-Writethru a0514 03-15 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Hepburn, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0514,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Planned Parenthood Honors Katharine Hepburn and Mother</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to CORRECT that Hepburn was in film of
``Spitfire,'' not the Broadway show; Note language of 5th graf</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Katharine Hepburn was starring in the 1934
film ``Spitfire,'' her mother was getting plenty of her own
attention as a ``spitfire'' for her outspoken support of birth
control for women.
   Today, the 79-year-old Miss Hepburn, with her family's
characteristic wit and keen intelligence, has taken on her mother's
cause and become one of Planned Parenthood's staunchest advocates.
   In a tribute Monday night, entitled ``Celebrating Two
Generations of Individual Courage,'' the actress and her late
mother, Katharine Houghton Hepburn, were honored by Planned
Parenthood for their efforts to gain greater reproductive rights
for women.
   ``It's a frightfully important subject,'' the actress told the
1,100 guests gathered at the Waldorf-Astoria for the black-tie
event.
   ``And I'm damn lucky to have had a mother who waked me up at an
early age.''
   Tickets for the gala were priced from $500 to $1,000, with
proceeds going to Planned Parenthood dedicated to the actress'
three priorities: keeping abortion safe and legal, preventing teen
pregnancies and preserving family planning for the poor.
   Former TV anchorman Walter Cronkite, tennis champion Martina
Navratilova, TV journalist Barbara Walters and actor Robert
Lindsay, star of the Broadway musical ``Me and My Girl,'' were
among the participants.
   As guests arrived, they encountered a small protest by the Stop
Planned Parenthood organization.
   Guests rose to their feet and applauded as Miss Hepburn,
elegantly attired in a black pantsuit, approached the podium.
   ``It's so touching to me, I can hardly begin to say what I have
to say,'' she said. But she had much to say.
   ``When a girl becomes pregnant, should she be forced by law to
have this baby? She's 13. She doesn't want it. She can't support
it. Her family doesn't want it. It would seem to me that she should
be allowed to have an abortion.''
   ``By the same token, if an older woman with several children
gets pregnant and feels that she can't support it or care for
another child, I cannot for the life of me see that anyone but this
woman has the right to decide what she's going to do,'' Miss
Hepburn said.
   ``It's certainly much harder to be a woman than it is to be a
man,'' she lamented. ``But men got here first and arranged
everything to suit themselves. And it's taking women a long time to
... try to catch up.''
   Miss Hepburn became involved with Planned Parenthood in 1981.
The group's president, Faye Wattleton, said she recruited her
because she was ``someone who really had the public's respect.''
Her participation in the organization has brought an additional
200,000 donors and supporters.
   It was only after the actress agreed to work for Planned
Parenthood that, Ms. Wattleton said, she learned
``serendipitously'' that Miss Hepburn's mother had been an
outspoken advocate of birth control at a time when it was illegal.
   Mrs. Hepburn worked alongside Planned Parenthood founder
Margaret Sanger more than 70 years ago.
   A member of the Houghton family that founded Corning Glass, she
testified before the U.S. Senate in the 1930s on the need for birth
control, particularly for poor women.
   ``Women want children but they want children they can properly
take care of,'' she testified. She died in 1951 at age 73.
</TEXT>
