<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PrimaryRdp Bjt-1stAdd   03-15 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Primary Rdp, Bjt-1st Add,650</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Consists of background material and should stand for AMs.</NOTE>
<HEAD>CHICAGO: this summer.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Thus ended the campaign in the first of the industrial states to
vote, a battle that seemed as clear-cut on the Republican side as
it was complicated for the Democrats.
   Bush campaigned like the prohibitive front-runner that he was
after his Super Tuesday rout, in which he won all 16 primary
elections and lost nly a caucus state _ Washington _ to Robertson.
He ignored Dole's repeated demands for a Lincoln-Douglas-style
debate without moderators and began tailoring his campaign to the
independent voters and potential Democratic converts likely to hold
the balance of power in the fall election campaign.
   He seemed to be gently trying to nudge Dole out of the race,
declaring, ``I'm not sure I understand what he's doing.''
   ``I've made a judgment that Illinois, whatever happens, we're
going to keep going,'' Dole said at a news conference on Monday.
But he conceded candidates sometimes fail to understand when it is
time to get out.
   ``Now if you're out there and you've been twisting in the wind
for six or eight months and you're starting to smell a little,
somebody has to cut the rope,'' he said.
   Nonetheless, his campaign was looking ahead to April 5,
releasing this to the Political Hotline:
   ``On Wisconsin, On Wisconsin, grand old Badger state,
   ``We thy loyal sons and daughters hail thee good and great.
   ``...On Wisconsin, On Wisconsin, fight on for her fame,
   ``Fight, fellows, fight fight fight
   ``We'll win this game.''
   Robertson vowed to stay in the GOP race until the convention in
New Orleans as ``a champion of conservatives.'' But he also said a
finish of less than 5 percent likely would force him to reassess
his vow.
   Bush's Illinois supporters ranged from Gov. Jim Thompson to
Edward Vrdolyak, once the Democratic kingpin of Chicago's Cook
County but now a Republican. And Bush spent $400,000 in television
advertising to boost his vote.
   Dole called Illinois a ``recovery state'' after his Super
Tuesday debacle and paid a memorable visit to the hospital where he
recovered from crippling World War II wounds 40 years ago to
underscore his point.
   But he conceded, ``We're hanging by our fingernails'' and he
staggered through the week. He laid off more than half his staff,
canceled television advertisements and was reported by aides to
have discussed quitting the campaign even before Illinois voted.
   He decided to remain a candidate and gambled on a 30-minute paid
television broadcast Saturday night _ only to fall victim to a
power failure that interrupted his statewide appeal in mid-sentence.
   The Democratic race was fittingly Byzantine in the land where
local politics is a year-round sport.
   Simon was attempting a tough campaign restart _ without funds
for advertising _ after sitting out the 21 Super Tuesday contests.
He urged his home state voters not to desert him in his hour of
need, and said he wanted to represent them at a brokered convention
this summer.
   But Dukakis responded that a brokered convention would be a
``disaster'' for the Democrats and plowed $250,000 into television
advertising in a bid to whittle away at Simon's support.
   Jackson, who won five Super Tuesday states and followed up on
Saturday with a victory in the South Carolina caucuses, said a
victory in Illinois would be a breakthrough _ his first in an
industrial battleground.
   Gore came to Illinois hoping to ride the crest of a Super
Tuesday-generated wave, but it failed to show up in the
pre-election polls. He spent an estimated $200,000 to $300,000 on
television advertising in search of a place to ``punch through'' in
his battle to compete with Dukakis.
   Gephardt, the candidate with political momentum only five weeks
ago when he won the Iowa caucuses, gave short shrift top Illinois.
Aides said he was conserving his cash and his energy for a last
stand in the Michigan caucuses on March 26.
</TEXT>
