<1ST_LINE>u w AM-TaxForms Bjt   03-15 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tax Forms, Bjt,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Given Taxing Task: Simplifying IRS Forms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students at the University of Akron are aiming
for a breakthrough that has eluded some of the best minds in
government and the professions: a tax form that can be understood
without a college education.
   ``We know it can be done and we're going to prove it,''
Professor Nicholas J. Creme, director of the Center for Taxation
Studies in the university's law school, said in an interview
Tuesday. ``We're not saying we could bring it down to a
second-grade level, but we certainly can make it simpler.
   ``If you simplify the forms, people will be a lot less hostile
toward the Internal Revenue Service,'' he said. ``And you'll raise
a lot more revenue.''
   Creme said about 20 students majoring in law, business or
education will be put to work on the project. Testifying before a
Senate Finance subcommittee Monday, some of the students and their
leaders promised Chairman David Pryor, D-Ark., that most of the
work will be done by September.
   The students got interested after seeing estimates that nine of
10 people with less than a high school education cannot understand
the instructions for the simplest tax form _ the one-page 1040EZ.
That study also determined that it takes less reading skill to get
through a typical issue of the Wall Street Journal than through a
tax form.
   The reasons for the complexity are simple, say Creme and
Professor James W. Childs, director of the university's Tax Clinic.
``The average sentence length of these (IRS) publications exceeds
25 words ... One-third of the words in these publications are
multi-syllabled words.''
   ``By reducing the number of syllables and the number of words in
a sentence we can the forms and instructions significantly more
readable,'' said Creme. ``And we want to change how the forms look
_ change the spacing so things don't look so crammed in.''
   It is not just college students or even high school dropouts who
are having trouble with tax forms. Even tax professionals shake
their heads at some instructions that were prompted by some of the
more complex provisions in the 1986 tax overhaul.
   This sentence, for example, is in the instructions for Form
8598, which up to 1 million taxpayers will have to file this year
to calculate their mortgage-interest deduction:
   ``If you received monthly statements that show either the
closing balance or the average balance for the month, you may
determine your average balance by taking the average of either the
closing balances or average monthly balances shown on your monthly
statement.''
   Creme said participants hope to develop more-readable versions
of the W-4 withholding form; W-2 year-end wages-earned statement;
1099 interest-earned form and the basic 1040, 1040A and 1040EZ
forms.
   IRS forms are developed in consultation with lawyers,
accountants and educators. In changing its forms last year to
reflect the new tax law, the IRS hired a consultant and even went
to some shopping malls for instant reaction from random taxpayers.
   IRS spokesman Steve Pyrek, who helped develop the 1040EZ several
years ago, says that form is written to an eighth-grade reading
level. That does not mean, however, that a typical student in the
eighth grade could understand it, he said.
   ``It means a grownup that understands certain concepts can
understand the form,'' Pyrek said. ``A fourth grader doesn't
understand the concept of taxation, for example, although a
40-year-old with a fourth-grade education who has been on the job
for 20 years probably does.''
   The IRS concedes that many taxpayers find taxes puzzling. The
agency's own statistics show that 46 percent of taxpayers paid
professionals to fill out their returns last year.
   Nevertheless, the IRS contends that the forms and instructions
are about as simple as they can be to reflect a complicated tax law.
   Creme, a tax lawyer for 20 years, said the IRS has nothing to
lose by making its forms more understandable. ``When people can't
figure out the right answer,'' he said, ``they will take the answer
that gives them the best break.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
