<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0684,0931</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Official Claims Another Lied About Death Threat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to correct spelling of Mecham in lead and
to rephrase 2nd graf, deleting reference to `alleged sex life';
picks up 2nd graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A witness for the prosecution at Gov. Evan
Mecham's impeachment trial said that a defense lawyer tried to
intimidate him with obscene language shortly before he testified,
according to an affidavit released today by prosecutors.
   Prosecutor William French, replying to defense accusations that
witnesses were being intimidated, released an affidavit saying that
defense attorney Fred Craft had himself berated a witness and made
accusations about the sex life of the governor's chief accuser.
   Craft accused state Department of Public Safety of ``a
consistent pattern of an abuse by the police power'' by
intimidating witnesses. ``We are afraid in this state today because
we've got a runaway police state.''
   But French contended that a defense move to dismiss an
obstruction of justice charge was a ``smokescreen'' put up because
the governor cannot disprove it.
   The impeachment allegations against Mecham, a first-term
Republican, include that he tried to thwart an investigation of an
alleged death threat by then-state prison construction chief Lee
Watkins against a former state official, Donna Carlson.
   Peggy Griffith testified last week that Watkins, a Mecham
confidant, told her that if Ms. Carlson did not keep her mouth shut
about an unreported Mecham campaign loan she might ``go on a long
boat ride'' and come to harm.
   ``It has become apparent that there is no defense'' to the
charge that Mecham tried to obstruct the probe, French said today.
   The Senate voted to take under advisement a defense motion to
either dismiss the obstruction charge or declare a mistrial. A
decision is expected Wednesday.
   The House panel overseeing the prosecution released an affidavit
from state official Antonio Corio, who said Craft made statements
about the alleged sex life of Department of Public Safety Director
Ralph Milstead.
   Milstead has testified Mecham ordered him not to cooperate with
the death threat probe, while Corio testified Friday that he had
been asked to search for listening devices in the governor's office
and found none.
   Craft claimed that Corio changed his planned testimony after
being seen with Milstead, but Corio's affidavit said, ``I contacted
DPS on my own. I have not been tampered with by DPS.''
   Corio's affidavit said Craft used obscene language on Friday in
saying he did not have time to deal with him.
   According to Corio's affidavit, Craft also said to Corio that
Milstead has sex with ``the widows of fallen officers to console
them.''
   Corio also claimed that Craft said that Milstead made DPS bureau
chiefs put on his uniform so they could have sex with him. The
affadivit did not specify the gender of the bureau chiefs alleged
involved, and it also did not indicate whether the conversation was
tape-recorded or how he remembered the quotes.
   Milstead is in Israel for an anti-terrorism seminar, but DPS
spokesman Sgt. Allan Schmidt called the alleged statements
``disgusting.'' Asked for further comment, he said, ``You can't
print it.''
   Craft indicated in arguments before the Senate that he had seen
the document, but he did not say whether he made the statements or
not.
   On Monday, a former cabinet member and Mecham confidante
testified that a key prosecution witness lied about the alleged
death threat.
   Max Hawkins, who was fired as state Department of Administration
director by acting Gov. Rose Mofford, told the Senate that
Griffith's public statements and testimony about the alleged threat
were ``substantially different'' from what she told him in November.
   ``I think Peggy really detested Lee Watkins,'' Hawkins, a
onetime Mecham campaign chairman, testified. ``I think she really
had it in for Lee Watkins,'' possibly because he had said bad
things about her friend Ms. Carlson before.
   Hawkins repeatedly told the Senate that he did not consider the
alleged threat to be a serious matter. He said the story told to
him by Mrs. Griffith was similar to what Watkins told him: ``People
are excitable out there on both sides and she (Ms. Carlson) could
end up getting hurt.''
   Hawkins said he did not remember Mrs. Griffith telling him
anything about Watkins saying Ms. Carlson could get killed or go on
a ``long boat ride.''
   Sen. Carolyn Walker, a Democrat, chided Hawkins, saying, ``You
hear a threat and you don't have the intelligence to discern a
threat?''
   The defense has accused the Department of Public Safety of
trying to intimidate Terri Fields, a defense witness who testified
she did not believe a death threat was made.
   Ms. Fields, who is Mrs. Griffith's secretary, was arrested
Friday night on a January warrant accusing her of not attending
court-ordered Alcoholics Anonymous meetings required after a
drunken driving arrest.
   The DPS has denied attempting to intimidate any witness, but the
FBI began a preliminary investigation Monday into the allegation.
   Mecham, who was impeached by the House on Feb. 5, also is
accused of concealing the $350,000 campaign loan and misusing
$80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto
dealership.
   He is the first U.S. governor to be impeached in six decades. A
two-thirds vote of the 30-member Senate is required to convict him.
   Mecham faces an April 21 criminal trial on charges of concealing
the $350,000 loan, and a May 17 recall election.
</TEXT>
