<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HinckleyBuzzards     03-15 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hinckley Buzzards,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Buzzard Spotters Spot Buzzards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HINCKLEY, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buzzard spotters got a welcome sign of
spring despite today's 20-degree temperatures when two birds
drifted into a park, officially marking their annual return to
Hinckley.
   ``It stopped snowing for a brief moment there, for 20 minutes,
and the sun came out and the birds came drifting in,'' said Ralph
Woinset, a ranger at Hinckley Reservation. ``Capt. Roger Lutz
called in the official sighting at 12:02 p.m.''
   ``They probably would have been in earlier if it hadn't been
snowing, but they have trouble negotiating the snow. By Sunday,
there should be quite a few of them in for the crowd,'' Woinset
said.
   A flock of the large, long-necked black birds supposedly returns
to its northern home at the park's Buzzard Roost each year on March
15. The annual buzzard search began in 1957 in an attempt to verify
the legend that the birds return on the same day each year.
   Lutz, a Cleveland Metroparks ranger captain, agreed that the
annual buzzard news tends to ``build on the tradition,'' but he
discounted the possibility that the buzzards stay in Hinckley
through the winter months.
   ``There's a flock of about 75 to 80 that stay in the Hinckley
area during the year. We believe they fly to Dade County, Fla.,
during the winter ... though it's difficult to verify,'' he said.
   According to local legend, buzzards were drawn to Hinckley in
1819 because of tons of decaying game killed in the Great Hinckley
Varmint Hunt.
   On Dec. 24, 1818, 475 men and boys attempted to rid the
25-square mile community of predatory animals that had been
attacking farm stock. The carcasses froze during the winter and
thawed in the spring, attracting the buzzards.
</TEXT>
