<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Infant-Award     03-15 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Infant-Award,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Awards Damages To Dead Infant, Mother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury awarded the estate of a prematurely born
boy who lived only 24 hours $75,000 for pain and suffering after he
received allegedly negligent treatment from a city ambulance crew.
   The six-member jury also awarded $350,000 to the child's mother,
Marlene Canty.
   The jury had ruled Jan. 15 that the baby was conscious enough to
experience pain and suffering, but city lawyers argued that the
finding was medically impossible and said they would appeal.
   Manhattan Supreme Court Justice Kenneth Shorter refused on Feb.
29 to overturn the verdict, the Daily News said Tuesday.
   Mrs. Canty, then 21, went into labor in her home two months
early on April 24, 1975. Her husband, Winslow, called the Emergency
Medical Service at least once, possibly three times, according to
conflicting accounts.
   The baby, still in its amniotic sac and moving one appendage,
``lay between the mother's thighs visible to her during the alleged
45-minute delay and negligent treatment ...,'' the judge wrote in
his decision.
   Mrs. Canty said the EMS technician who finally arrived told her
the baby was dead and refused to open the sac.
   ``Finally I asked her (the technician) if the baby was a boy or
a girl,'' Mrs. Canty said. ``At that point she took a small
instrument and slit open the sac. ... She lifted one leg, saw the
gender of the baby, threw the leg down and said the baby was a boy.
... She then picked up the baby, wrapped the baby in the plastic
and threw the baby'' into a cardboard box.
   Mrs. Canty and the baby were taken to Harlem Hospital, where the
infant lived for 24 hours on a respirator.
</TEXT>
