<2ND_LINE>AM-Dome-Home,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lavish Home In The Dome To Make Way For Stadium Renovation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The palatial home within the Houston Astrodome is
making way for sports fans.
   Roy Hofheinz, former mayor, county judge and prime mover behind
construction of the stadium, built the six-story apartment,
including a barber shop, game room, bowling alley, putting greens
and a shooting gallery, not to mention a superb view of the playing
field.
   Hofheinz died in 1982, and had not lived in his stadium home
since 1975. Much of it already has been converted to viewing areas
and special viewing boxes. This week the rest will be torn down,
and will become part of a new 15,000-seat area.
   In Hofheinz's master bedroom and drawing room, there are 30-foot
ceilings, gold-plated fixtures, handcarved woodwork and a bathroom
with sunken tub and sauna.
   A slanting floor in the Tipsy Tavern gives guests a feeling
being so before they take a drink. In the apartment's chapel,
changeable windows offered worshipers their choice of a cross, a
Star of David or a Buddhist symbol.
   Hofheinz lived in the apartment off and on from 1965, when the
Astrodome was built, to 1975. He died at age 70.
