<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeathRowDean     03-15 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Death Row Dean,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Only Inmate On Death Row Longer Than Darden Still Waits</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Darden Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only one man has lived longer on
Florida's death row than Willie Jasper Darden.
   Howard V. Douglas, who turns 52 on March 30, has been on death
row since Dec. 4, 1973. Darden was sentenced to death seven weeks
later and was executed Tuesday.
   Douglas was convicted of killing his ex-lover's husband after
forcing the pair to engage in a series of sex acts while he
watched, court records say.
   Former Gov. Bob Graham signed a death warrant on Douglas for
July 26, 1979, but that was stayed and subsequent legal steps
resulted in the case being sent back to Polk County for
resentencing.
   Douglas was again sentenced to death in August 1985, and the
appeal from that hearing now is with the Florida Supreme Court,
which heard oral arguments in September 1986.
   The court could affirm the death sentence or reduce it to life,
clerk Sid White said Tuesday.
   In the original trial, the jury found Douglas guilty and
recommended life, but the judge imposed the death penalty based on
a finding of no mitigating circumstances. In Florida, jury
recommendations in death cases are advisory, and the final
sentencing decision is up to the judge.
   Although Douglas has been on death row for more than 14 years,
his case could to drag on for years more.
   ``He would have the right to start the process all over again as
far as the new sentence is concerned,'' said assistant attorney
general Richard Martell. ``It's a new death sentence that has not
been reviewed by any court, so he would have a right to take a
petition to the U.S. Supreme Court.''
   Douglas was convicted of killing Jesse W. Atkins on July 17,
1973.
   Atkins' body was discovered by a hunter July 21, and five days
later the victim's wife reported the killing to authorities.
   Helen Atkins later testified she once had lived with Douglas but
returned to her husband following the birth of a baby in June 1973.
   Mrs. Atkins said she and her husband were forced to commit
various sexual acts at gunpoint before Douglas struck Atkins with
the butt of a rifle, then shot him.
   Douglas and Mrs. Atkins returned later to move and cover up the
body. She said went along with Douglas out of fear.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
