<DOCNO> AP880315-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 1445EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MarrowBrothers     03-15 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marrow Brothers,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Submits To Blood Test For Dying Brother For $1,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homeless man who refused to help his dying
brother until he was offered $1,000 finally submitted to a blood
test Tuesday to determine his suitability as a bone-marrow donor,
blood bank officials said.
   Randy Chapman, 32, who lives on the streets and earns money by
submitting to medical experiments, had initially refused to help
his brother in Indianapolis.
   ``If he dies, he dies,'' Chapman had said. ``He's about as much
a brother to me as you are.''
   But he changed his mind after an anonymous Indiana man who also
suffers from a blood disease offered him $1,000 to take the blood
test.
   Other family members had been tested but were found unsuitable.
   ``I wasn't too proud of myself when I read in the paper what I
had said. I sounded cold, but I guess all my repressed feelings
came out,'' said Chapman, who had not been in contact with his
family in 14 years.
   ``I don't wish my brother any harm. It's just that my family
only wanted me when they needed something from me. Where were they
when I needed them?,'' he said in an interview with The Miami News.
   Chapman submitted to the blood test Tuesday at the American Red
Cross Blood Bank of South Florida, said spokesman Chris Chidley.
   The test will determine if Randy is a suitable match for his
brother, Steve Chapman, 38, who is dying from leukemia.
   If he proves suitable, Randy Chapman stands to gain an
additional $2,000 for donating marrow, the source of blood cells.
   ``I'm glad he did it and I hope it all works out after all this
trouble,'' said the ill brother, Steve Chapman, who is married and
the father of two. ``I just wish he hadn't raised such a ruckus.
There was no sense in doing that. He's a little rough around the
edges, I guess.''
   Steve Chapman was released from St. Vincent's Hospital in
Indianapolis last week after chemotherapy treatment. His disease is
in remission, but he must have the marrow transplant within three
to four months, his doctor says.
   Without the transplant, he will die within two years, said Dr.
Richard Fayssoux.
   The philanthropist said he hopes his offer will not only save
Steve's life, but also help Randy turn his life around.
   ``I hope it works out well for both of them,'' he told The Miami
News.
   Randy said he hopes the money will enable him to give direction
to an aimless life.
   ``I'm planning to do something constructive with my life, rather
than destructive,'' he said. ``I'm thinking about leaving Miami.''
</TEXT>
