<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 1446EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     03-15 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethnic Violence Claims 10 More Lives in Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethnic feuding between Sinhalese and
minority Tamils killed 10 more people Tuesday, Indian authorities
said, bringing the two-day death toll to 17.
   Sinhalese attackers dragged away three Tamil bus passengers near
Tampalagama in eastern Trincomalee District and hacked them to
death, according to a representative of the Indian High Commission
in Colombo.
   An hour later in nearby Gomarankadawela, Tamil rebels shot and
dismembered seven Sinhalese, including a child, according to the
Indian-Sri Lankan joint operations command.
   The rebels reportedly belonged to the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam, who have been fighting for a separate homeland in northern
and eastern Sri Lanka.
   An Indian peacekeeping force of about 50,000 came to Sri Lanka
at the government's invitation to stem such attacks after a peace
accord was signed in July.
   The violence has persisted, however. Sri Lankan and Indian
authorities say 98 civilians have died in Trincomalee so far this
month.
   At least 12 Sinhalese villagers were killed Monday in an attack
by suspected Tamil rebels on the village of Galmetiya, according to
Sri Lankan military officials.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's
16 million people. They claim they are discriminated against by the
majority Sinhalese Buddhists, who control the government and
military.
   Militant Tamils have been fighting since 1983 for a separate
homeland. They have rejected the Indian-brokered peace accord of
July, saying it fails to protect their interests.
   India hopes to foster peace in Sri Lanka, an island just off its
southern tip, because an estimated 60 million Tamils live in
India's southern states. Many sympathize with Tamils in Sri Lanka.
</TEXT>
