<DOCNO> AP880315-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 1438EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Darden Bjt   03-15 0839</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Darden, Bjt,0861</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On Seventh Warrant, Darden's Time Runs Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JV1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STARKE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted murderer Willie Jasper Darden went
to his death Tuesday proclaiming his innocence and thanking people
around the world, from Andrei Sakharov to Jesse Jackson, who aided
his 14-year battle to escape the electric chair.
   For the widow of the man he shot between the eyes, Darden's
execution on an unprecedented seventh death warrant offered hope,
finally, for peace of mind.
   ``I think it's long overdue,'' Helen Turman Baum said minutes
after the execution about 7 a.m. at the Florida State Prison. ``He
did it to himself. I'm just thinking right now I want some peace of
mind ... it's been a long time and I'm glad it's finally over.''
   Mrs. Baum has remarried since her husband, James C. Turman, was
killed Sept. 8, 1973, after Turman walked into their Lakeland
furniture store and found his wife being robbed of $15.
   Gov. Bob Martinez also was unmoved about the international
attention Darden attracted, from death penalty opponents and people
who believed his conviction was racially tainted. Darden was black;
Turman was white.
   Among 1,600 telephone calls Monday, the majority protesting, was
one from Jackson, a candidate for the Democratic presidential
nomination. Nobel Peace Prize winner Sakharov, actress Margot
Kidder, rock star Peter Gabriel, Amnesty International and other
human rights and religious groups also all called for a halt to
Darden's execution.
   ``I think justice was served today,'' Martinez said later.
``This was not someone out of a choir. He was a career criminal.
This was a man who had a career of violent crimes.''
   It was the 18th execution in Florida and 96th in the nation
since the U.S. Supreme Court ruled in 1976 that states could again
invoke capital punishment.
   Earlier Tuesday, Wayne Robert Felde was executed in Louisiana's
electric chair for the 1978 murder of a police officer. It was the
first time two inmates were executed the same day in the United
States since Aug. 28, when executions were carried out in Florida,
Alabama and Utah.
   Darden, 54, gave a final taped interview Monday with ABC-TV,
broadcast on ``Nightline.'' He had exchanged letters with many
people and had become known as the ``sage of death row'' for the
poetry he wrote as he pressed his claim that he was unjustly
accused and convicted.
   But although he had promised in the ``Nightline'' interview to
be ``hollering `innocent, innocent' '' as he was strapped into the
electric chair, Darden instead offered, without notes, a firm,
evenly delivered, last denial.
   ``I was not guilty for the charge for which I was arrested, and
this morning I tell you I am not guilty of the charge for which I
am about to be executed,'' Darden said to 30 witnesses in the death
chamber.
   ``I say to my friends and supporters around the world: I love
each and every one of you. Your love and support has been a great
comfort to me, and my struggle for justice and freedom.
   ``I go this morning with a clear conscience. I bear no guilt.
I'm at peace with myself, with the world, with each of you. God
bless you.''
   Darden winked and nodded at one of his attorneys just before the
hood was put over his head, and was declared dead at 7:12 a.m.
after 2,000 volts of electricity flowed through his body for two
minutes. Two puffs of smoke rose from his right leg where one of
the electrodes was attached.
   On Monday, the U.S. Supreme Court, the 11th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals, a federal judge and the state Supreme Court rejected
Darden's appeals on his seventh warrant. No inmate on Florida's
death row had ever survived more than three warrants on the same
crime.
   Before dawn Tuesday, 40 people gathered in a pasture across from
the prison. The protesters maintained silence until the execution
took place, then began singing ``We Shall Overcome.''
   Court records say that after shooting Turman, Darden ordered his
wife to perform oral sex on him while Turman lay dying a few feet
away.
   A neighbor, Philip Arnold, also identified Darden during the
trial. Arnold, then 16, entered the store after apparently hearing
the shooting and the woman's cries. He was shot three times but
survived.
   Death penalty opponents, led by Amnesty International, have said
Darden had an alibi proving his innocence. They claim statements
from a minister and a woman show Darden could not have committed
the murder.
   In Sweden, about a dozen people demonstrated Monday outside the
U.S. Embassy in Stockholm. The Florida Catholic Conference and
bishops in Florida had urged a halt to the execution.
   Darden was born in Snow Hill, N.C., the second of four children.
His conviction record dated to 1964 and included attempted rape.
   Only Howard V. Douglas had been on death row longer _ by seven
weeks. Douglas was convicted of the July 1973 shooting death of his
former lover's husband. His case is currently on appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
