<DOCNO> AP880315-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 1438EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-OnToMichigan Bjt   03-15 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-On To Michigan, Bjt,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>After Illinois, Democratic Candidates Focus On Michigan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Gephardt, hoping to regain the
momentum he established in long-ago Iowa, waited for the Democratic
presidential field in Michigan, site of free-for-all caucuses
uncluttered by any favorite-son bias.
   The stakes in the March 26 caucuses were high and the campaign
was already in gear as Illinois voted on Tuesday.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis wrapped himself in
influential endorsements and sought to establish himself as the
Democratic front-runner.
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. sought a big-state victory outside his
native South. And Jesse Jackson looked for delegates in a state
that shorted him in 1984.
   Illinois, the first contest post-Super Tuesday, was destined to
leave no deep imprint on the Democratic race, given its two-way
favorite son loyalties to Jackson and Paul Simon. So Michigan looms
as the next big contest, with 138 delegates at stake.
   Gephardt skipped over Illinois and headed straight for Michigan,
a state that would seem tailor-made for his tough-on-trade,
save-the-farms message with its $15 billion agriculture industry
and import-triggered auto industry layoffs.
   Gephardt is hoping the message saves the messenger.
   ``If we don't do well here, obviously we're not going to be able
to continue in this race,'' he told Michigan supporters last week.
   Gephardt was the first to hit the airwaves with a commercial
featuring his tough talk on trade sanctions, his family farm
legislation and an endorsement from elderly champion Rep. Claude
Pepper of Florida. ``From the farms, the factories, the
neighborhoods, comes the yearning for change, and now our cause
finally has a voice,'' the ad says.
   The United Auto Workers support that Gephardt cornered in Iowa
is missing here.
   Unlike 1984, when the union endorsed Walter Mondale more than a
year before the balloting, labor leadership has taken a vow of
neutrality. The word to the rank-and-file has been ``Support the
candidate of your choice.'' The 650,000 Michigan members appear to
have taken that word to heart: their support is fractured.
   Former United Auto Workers president Douglas Fraser, still
popular with the rank-and-file, has endorsed Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis, various union locals have donated telephones to
Jackson's phone bank, and other union leaders have asked for
management favors to arrange short-notice plant tours for Gephardt.
   Even Sen. Albert Gore Jr. plays to the labor audience here,
touting scorecards issued by the national AFL-CIO's political
action committee.
   ``I have been a friend of organized labor ... in 12 years in the
House and Senate,'' he said Monday night in Detroit.
   In 1984, the Michigan system left Jackson's delegate winnings
far short of his 16 percent popular vote. Detroit Mayor Coleman
Young actively opposed him and mobilized the city's black vote for
Mondale.
   This time, the Jackson campaign ambushed Young by quietly
winning over the ministers, unionists and party activists that form
the backbone of the Young machine. Young favors Dukakis in this
race, but the mayor is unable to promise the turnout Mondale
enjoyed.
   The Jackson campaign plans no television, instead concentrating
on ethnic radio and making sure the core constituency of black
Democrats knows where to go to vote, said Michigan campaign chief
Joel Ferguson. He said Jackson is also getting a good reception
from white voters in Michigan's campus communities.
   The Gore campaign's goals seem to be twofold: prove a Southerner
can do well in the Rust Belt and siphon away enough votes to push
Gephardt below the 15 percent threshold for winning delegates.
   ``For a modest investment we can take enough votes to cut
Gephardt out of the race,'' one Gore supporter said privately.
   Illinois Sen. Paul Simon had one of the first Michigan campaign
organizations in place, but his future was uncertain.
</TEXT>
