<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 1449EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-OverseasInsurance     03-15 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Overseas Insurance,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Would Insure Businesses in Disturbed Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal agency proposed to Congress on
Tuesday that it be allowed to offer insurance to U.S. businesses to
help them stay in countries threatened with political turmoil, such
as the Philippines and Haiti.
   But the proposal by the Overseas Private Investment Corp.
prompted Rep. Don Bonker, D-Wash., to say: ``Wouldn't that be like
offering health insurance to someone who's terminally ill?''
   ``Or like fire insurance on a house that's burning,'' agreed
Craig A. Nalen, president of OPIC, which wants to sell the
insurance against political risks.
   Nalen was quick to add that such policies would only be offered
in consultation with the State Department.
   ``We would not go forward if Molotov cocktails were coming
through the windows of the plant,'' he told the House Foreign
Affairs subcommittee on economic policy, which Bonker chairs.
   Nalen explained that an insurance policy would be offered in
order to prevent a company leaving a country.
   ``That could be devastating to a country that's in
difficulties,'' he said.
   Bonker offered the Philippines as an example and Nalen suggested
Haiti as another.
   Bonker said the idea needs further exploration.
   In testimony prepared for the subcommittee, Nalen emphasized
that the purpose of the insurance would be to keep the country
concerned economically stable and would be offered only in rare
circumstances.
   ``It is very unlikely that private insurers would be interested
in underwriting the kinds of exposures OPIC would be considering
under this authority,'' he said.
   The new authority would permit the agency to offer insurance to
new or existing companies.
   Nalen said members of his staff also have been discussing
agreements for insurance of U.S. firms operating in the territory
of two communist governments: Poland and Hungary.
   Bonker reminded him of the U.S. law that prevents economic
favors to countries that limit emigration of their citizens.
   OPIC's job is to insure U.S. investors in other countries
against political risks, including war, domestic violence,
confiscation and the freezing of their assets. It also makes loans
for investment.
   Nalen told the subcommittee that in the last three years it had
promoted $8.7 billion worth of investment in 61 countries and
turned a profit of $300 million.
</TEXT>
