<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Chambers     03-15 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chambers,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyers In Chambers Case Sum Up Wednesday, Prosecution To Suggest
A Motive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecutor in Robert Chambers' murder trial
plans to suggest during closing arguments a motive that might have
led him to deliberately kill Jennifer Levin in Central Park, a
source said Tuesday.
   Assistant District Attorney Linda Fairstein said at the
beginning of the 11-week trial that she would prove Chambers
intended to kill Miss Levin, 18, and that it was not an accident
during rough sex as he claimed.
   She told the jurors that the prosecution is not required to
prove motive and that the real reasons for the killing might remain
forever locked in the defendant's head.
   Other lawyers, prosecutors and defense attorneys alike, agree
generally that juries like to hear a motive when they are being
asked to convict someone on a charge of intentional murder.
   Chambers, 21, is charged with second-degree murder in the
strangulation death of Miss Levin on Aug. 26, 1986. Chambers, a
former drug abuser and Boston University dropout who has been
indicted on burglary charges in another case, admits he killed Miss
Levin but says it was an accident after she attacked him sexually
and hurt him.
   The summations by both sides are expected to take most or all of
Wednesday. State Supreme Court Justice Howard Bell will likely give
the jurors final instructions Thursday before they begin
deliberations.
   Ms. Fairstein said in her opening statement that Chambers'
assertion that the killing was an accident was ``ludicrous.''
   A source said Ms. Fairstein, to emphasize the beating Chambers
allegedly gave Miss Levin before he killed her, might display a
large color photograph of the teen-ager before she died next to a
gruesome morgue picture showing red welts and bruises on her body.
   The judge has said he will instruct the jury to consider every
category of homicide, including two charges that carry no mandatory
minimum sentence.
   Bell said that besides the two types of second-degree murder
which with Chambers is charged _ intentional and ``depraved
indifference'' to life _ he will tell the jury to consider
first-and second-degree manslaughter, and criminally negligent
homicide.
   During Tuesday morning's court session the jurors watched
Chambers' vidotaped admission for a second time so the lawyers
would not have to interupt their summations to replay it.
   The replaying of the tape had an emotional effect on Stephen and
Ellin Levin, the victim's divorced parents. When Ms. Levin started
crying, her ex-husband hugged her and eventually escorted her out
of the courtroom. They had no comment as they left.
</TEXT>
