<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 1452EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Hangings     03-15 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Hangings,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pressure Mounts On Pretoria To Spare The Sharpeville Six</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer planned an appeal and
the government agreed Tuesday to hear more calls for clemency for
the ``Sharpeville Six,'' a group of blacks sentenced to hang in two
days.
   West Germany and Britain joined the growing international call
for mercy for the five men and one woman, who were convicted of
complicity in the 1984 lynching of a black township official.
   ``I am not saying that a sign of mercy will solve the problems
of South Africa but it might be a little signal that human feelings
have not died out altogether,'' West German President Richard von
Weizsaecker told a news coference in Harare, Zimbabwe, where he was
on a state visit.
   President P.W. Botha has rejected all clemency bids for the six,
the goverment said Tuesday. But he agreed to meet Thursday with two
members of the anti-apartheid Progressive Federal Party who oppose
the executions, the South African Press Association reported.
   Also, the Justice Ministry said Tuesday that further petitions
for mercy would be given ``careful consideration.''
   Prakash Diar, attorney for the six, said he would file an appeal
in the Rand Supreme Court on Wednesday to seek a stay of execution.
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, meanwhile, said she
asked Britain's ambassador to Pretoria to meet with Botha on
Tuesday in another bid for clemency.
   The condemned are Theresa Ramashamola, 26; Mojalefa Sefatsa, 32;
Reid Mokoena, 24; Oupa Diniso, 32; Duma Khumalo, 28; and Francis
Mokgesi, 30.
   They were convicted in the September 1984 killing of black
township councilor Jacob Dlamini in Sharpeville, about 40 miles
south of Johannesburg.
   No evidence was produced that the six were among those who
hacked and burned Dlamini to death. They were convicted under the
doctrine of ``common purpose,'' which holds they were responsible
for the killing by being part of the mob that gathered outside
Dlamini's home with the intent to kill him.
   One of the Progressive Federal Party members that Botha planned
to meet on Thursday was Helen Suzman, a member of Parliament who
called the executions ``sheer madness'' in remarks to the body on
Tuesday.
   Suzman said the executions would have have a devastating effect
on international opinion.
   ``What reputation do we have in the outside world anyway?''
responded Joan Hunter, a member of Parliament from Botha's National
Party.
   ``An example must be set,'' Mrs. Hunter said. ``We can't allow
these people to roam the streets and intimidate the moderate black
who is only too willing to negotiate with us.''
   Thatcher said British Ambassador Robin Renwick was given
instructions ``to express my hope that President Botha will see
fit, even at this late stage, to exercise the perogative of mercy.''
   Von Weizsaecker told reporters that the executions would
contribute to the violence and tension in South Africa, where the
system of apartheid gives control of the country to the white
minority.
   Amnesty International, the London-based human rights
organization, also urged Botha to spare the six. The organization
expressed shock that 164 people, only nine of them white, were
hanged in South Africa last year.
   Dlamini's killing came during riots that sparked a two-year
outbreak of nationwide anti-apartheid unrest that left more than
2,000 blacks dead.
   Black activists frequently targeted black township councilors,
considering them collaborators with the white-led government. The
Sharpeville riots were provoked by the local council's decision to
raise rents.
</TEXT>
