<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Hostage-Clerk     03-15 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostage-Clerk,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Iran Hostage Seeks Clerk Of Courts Seat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William E. Belk, one of the Americans
held hostage in Iran, will seek the Republican nomination as
Lexington County clerk of courts in the June 14 primary.
   Belk, 52, who declared his ambitions on Monday, has been working
part-time as a communications officer for the State Department and
is keeping busy with a company he helped found, Counts Rescue
Equipment Co. in Ballentine.
   Belk was working in the U.S. Embassy in Tehran on Nov. 4, 1979,
when Iranians seized the embassy and took more than 60 Americans
hostage. Fifty-two of them were held 444 days and released on the
day of President Reagan's first inauguration in January 1981.
   Belk's wife died in September 1986, and he since then has worked
in the Sudan, Cyprus and West Germany for the State Department. The
past two months, he has been in Baghdad, Iraq.
   He said it now is time for him to settle down.
   ``I think the Lord is trying to tell me something. Every time I
leave one of these countries, somebody blows them up. So I will try
to find my niche in the United States, hopefully in Lexington
County government,'' Belk said.
</TEXT>
