<2ND_LINE>AM-Gore,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Looks Beyond Illinois to Michigan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Primary Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Albert Gore Jr. launched his campaign for
Michigan's Democratic caucuses Tuesday by trumpeting the
endorsement of legislative leaders and depicting the race for the
presidential nomination as a decision ``whether or not the
Democratic Party is viable in national elections from here on out.''
   Gore, contending he stands a better chance than his rivals of
attracting independent voters, was looking beyond Tuesday's
Illinois primary _ to Michigan's statewide caucuses on March 26.
   In a news conference near the state Capitol, Gore was endorsed
by the speaker of the Michigan House, Gary M. Owen, the Democratic
leader in the state Senate, Art Miller, and other state legislators.
   ``This is a battle for the future of the Democratic Party, a
battle that will determine whether or not the Democratic Party is
viable in national elections from here on out,'' Gore said.
   He was addressing his familiar appeal for support from ``working
men and women'' to the state's heavily unionized work force,
describing himself upon arrival in Michigan Monday night as a
``friend of organized labor.''
   Gore said he would use existing trade laws to bring down unfair
barriers to trade overseas. However, drawing a distinction with
rival Richard Gephardt's retaliatory policies, Gore pointed to the
Reagan administration as bearing most of the blame for the nation's
large trade deficit.
   ``Now we must acknowledge that 80 percent of the problem is with
our own policies and the policies of the Reagan administration,''
Gore said.
   He pointed to his own 88 percent approval rating by the AFL-CIO
over his career in Congress and said that was particularly
noteworthy since he comes from Tennessee, a state without the
Northern states' tradition of organized labor.
   ``It is a record that's been built up in the political fires and
forces of a right-to-work state,'' Gore said.
   Gore said he backed the rights of states to have such laws
banning compulsory union membership.
   ``I believe in the right to organize,'' he said, but ``what
decisions states make, that's for them to determine.''
   Gore said he hoped to ``substantially exceed expectations'' in
Michigan but refused to predict a victory and said no state was
make-or-break for him. ``We're starting at a point where other
campaigns are ahead,'' he said of Michigan.
   Gore planned to fly to Kansas to campaign Wednesday and Thursday
toward that state's Democratic caucuses March 19. Aides said they
were considering having Gore go Friday to Puerto Rico, where
delegates are selected March 28.
   Larry Harrington, a Gore strategist, described the race in
Puerto Rico as between Gore and Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   Gore also met privately with Michigan fund-raisers and said his
fund raising has improved greatly since his victories in the South
last week.
   ``It was the difference between night and day before and after
Super Tuesday,'' he said.
</TEXT>
