<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Switch     03-15 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Switch,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Whites to Live in Black Township for Four Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200 black and white
Christians will live and worship together this week in an unusual
attempt to break down the psychological and social barriers created
by apartheid.
   Most of the participants are whites coming from across South
Africa to stay Wednesday night through Sunday in Mamelodi, the main
black township outside Pretoria. About 35 blacks from Mamelodi will
stay in white homes in the capital.
   The encounter, culminating with a community barbecue and and a
church service, will be the largest interracial get-together of its
type in South Africa.
   One of the principal organizers is the Rev. Nico Smith, a Dutch
Reformed minister in Mamelodi since 1982. He moved there two years
ago after becoming the first white permitted by the government to
live in a black township.
   Smith says relations between the races in South Africa are
warped by fear and estrangement.
   ``Since I'm living in the black community myself, I have become
aware of the almost total alienation which has developed between
whites and blacks,'' said Smith.
   ``Apartheid was successful. It brought about what it promised to
do. It separated people,'' he said. ``If people are forced to live
separately they become strangers ... Eventually on both sides they
have certain perceptions are totally different from the real
people. This eventually turns into fear of one another.''
   Smith and other clergymen organizing the four days of
socializing, Bible study and prayer have brought smaller groups of
whites into Mamelodi in the past. They said men and women sometimes
tremble with fear as they enter a township that two years ago was
wracked by violent anti-apartheid protests, political killings and
factional battles.
   There has been some opposition to the encounter from militant
groups in Mamelodi who say whites should be viewed as enemies. A
right-wing white group called United Christian Action sent letters
to Mamelodi's mayor and the commissioner of police asking that the
meeting be banned.
   Smith said some black hosts have expressed fears that they will
be arrested if they participate.
   Most South African blacks know how whites live because they work
at white homes and businesses. Few whites know first-hand how
blacks live because they seldom venture into the townships located
on the periphery of the cities.
   One of the delegates, Eddie Prest, said he has had blacks in his
house near Cape Town many times but has never visited a black home.
   ``The black culture is so set up that they don't invite people
to come,'' said Prest, retired director of a bible study program.
``They'll say, `Why don't you just come,' and I'll say, `I've not
been invited.'
   ``It's just a cultural problem,'' Prest said, ``and also a
logistics problem. Also, it's very hard for an African to have you
home, because of their accommodation, their facilities.''
   The number of black delegates is much lower than the whites,
said Baptist Rev. Kevin Roy, because it is harder for blacks to
take two or three days off work. The main goal, he said, is to
expose whites to the black lifestyle, encourage them to think about
positive action to change the apartheid system, and take their
knowledge back to their communities.
   ``Maybe for four days we will treat them (the white visitors) as
blacks. They will start seeing things from the way we look at
things, not the way they are used to looking at things,'' said Dan
Ramakgadi, a field worker for Koinonia, one of the organizing
church groups.
</TEXT>
