<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Greenspan     03-15 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greenspan,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fed Chairman Says Foreign Investment In US Shouldn't Be
Discouraged</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Foreign Trade Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan
told Congress on Tuesday that foreign investors make ``good
corporate citizens'' and should not be discouraged from buying more
U.S. assets.
   Despite statistics showing the United State widening its lead as
the world's largest debtor nation, Greenspan said he had ``very
little concern about the issue of direct foreign investment.''
   ``We will find that foreign investment in the United States will
be a plus,'' even at present record levels, Greenspan told the
House-Senate Joint Economic Committee.
   Greenspan also suggested that a recession is unlikely throughout
the next year. He cited recent positive economic statistics,
including an unemployment rate that fell to 5.7 percent in
February, its lowest level in almost nine years.
   He said the rate could drop further, probably somewhere between
half a percentage point and a full percentage point, before
triggering an increase in inflation.
   Greenspan said foreign investments flowing into this country now
from Japan and from Europe are a direct consequence of the large
sums of money the United States spent in those areas in the
aftermath of World War II.
   He testified as the Commerce Department reported that the U.S.
current account deficit _ the broadest measure of foreign trade _
surged to a record $160.7 billion in 1987. The figures add trade in
services and investment flows to other export and import numbers.
   Greenspan said direct investment in the United States by
foreigners was preferable to them putting their dollars _ amassed
through the trade imbalance _ into ``short term liquid holdings.''
   Greenspan was asked by Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., whether he
was troubled by the extent of the growing foreign investment in the
United States, particularly by Japanese companies. ``Japan is
buying America and leasing it back to us,'' D'Amato suggested.
   ``On the contrary, the integration of the world economies ... is
inevitable...and is a desirable trend,'' the Fed chief said.
   Greenspan said that foreign-owned businesses in the United
States had become ``good corporate citizens in the localities in
which they chose to locate.''
   He noted that in terms of direct investment _ excluding
government securities _ U.S. business holdings overseas remain
about $50 billion above holdings by foreigners in this country.
   In terms of U.S. Treasury securities, foreign investors held
16.4 percent of the total at the end of last year, Greenspan said.
   Greenspan also:
   _Urged Taiwan to do more to reduce its trade surplus and bring
its economic and monetary polices into equilibrium with the United
States and other major trading partners.
   _Said the British government took the ``correct action'' in not
seeking to stem the recent sharp rise of the pound through heavy
central-bank intervention.
   _Praised Japan for taking steps to stimulate its economy, but
said that steps with a similar goal taken by West Germany have not
been as successful.
   _Said the Fed is keeping in close contact with the White House
and the State Department on the current turmoil in Panama. The Fed
maintains an account for the government of Panama in the New York
Federal Reserve Bank, Greenspan said.
</TEXT>
