<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AtlantaArchbishop Bjt   03-15 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Atlanta Archbishop, Bjt,0675</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Black U.S. Archbishop Calls Appointment `Sign of Hope'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY17</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bishop Eugene A. Marino, named Tuesday as the
first black Roman Catholic archbishop in the United States, said
his appointment as head of the Atlanta archdiocese is ``a great
sign of hope to all our people.''
   The appointment by Pope John Paul II comes more than two years
after Marino and other black bishops wrote a pastoral letter
calling on the church to increase the number of blacks in official
positions.
   ``The church has spoken but has the church listened to itself?''
said the letter, suggesting that in the absence of a major
appointment such as a black archbishop in a big city, ``the
church's commitment to black leadership may be seen as half-hearted
and superficial.''
   The Atlanta archdiocese has only 10,000 blacks among its 156,000
Catholics. Of 52 million Catholics nationwide, 1.3 million are
black.
   Marino said he could see in his appointment ``a sign of hope to
all men and women of good will that the church recognizes its
wealth within its own ranks ...''
   ``I think that this appointment is a sign of hope to all
minorities that the church in general'' and the pope in particular
are sensitive to the needs of blacks, Marino told reporters.
   Marino, 53, is one of 12 black bishops in the United States and
has served as an auxiliary bishop in the Washington, D.C.,
archdiocese since 1974. In 1985, he was elected secretary of the
National Conference of Catholic Bishops, the first black to hold an
office in the organization. He is a member of the Society of St.
Joseph, formed in the late 1800s to work in the black community.
   Marino's selection was hailed by an advocacy group as an
outstanding appointment.
   Calling him ``quiet, but effective,'' Walter T. Hubbard, acting
executive director of the National Office of Black Catholics, said
Marino ``is a pastoral man and he is sensitive to the needs of lay
people, especially the needs of black Catholic lay people in the
country.
   ``We have optimism that the church is showing us signs of being
responsive to the call by black Catholic lay people for black men
to be elevated to positions of authority and responsibilty,''
Hubbard said in a telephone interview from Washington.
   Hubbard noted that Marino has represented the National
Conference of Catholic Bishops in congressional hearings,
testifying about the needs of the unemployed and the homeless and
for voting rights.
   Marino said his appointment did not necessarily make him the
church's spokesman on civil rights, despite Atlanta's historical
position in the civil rights movement.
   He also declined to be labeled an activist priest, saying he was
``not one to dodge issues; at the same time I am not one to go out
and look for issues for issues' sake.''
   Marino, a native of Biloxi, Miss., said he hoped to be able to
expand black membership in the Catholic church.
   ``We (black bishops) feel that this is a good time for our
sisters and brothers to come forward with their gifts to enrich the
church,'' Marino said.
   ``We have a rich tradition of spirituality in the
African-American tradition ... but it is not a rich tradition that
enriches the Catholic church, unfortunately,'' he said. ``Our
people tend to be religious, our people tend to be spiritual, but
they do not tend to be predominantly Catholic and we feel that
being Catholic is something special.''
   After meeting with some of the 200 priests in the archdiocese,
Marino led a noontime mass at the Cathedral of Christ the King
before returning to Washington.
   Marino will be formally installed May 5, to succeed Archbishop
Thomas A. Donnellan, who died last Oct. 15.
   The Atlanta archdiocese covers 69 counties in north Georgia and
has some administrative responsibility for Catholic dioceses in the
rest of Georgia and in North and South Carolina.
</TEXT>
