<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Carlucci     03-15 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carlucci,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Meets With Soviet Counterpart</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci met
with his Soviet counterpart Tuesday, hoping to prod Defense
Minister Dmitri Yazov into providing concrete evidence of a new
Soviet military doctrine.
   Carlucci, speaking to reporters en route to meeting Yazov in
Bern, said that despite publicity surrounding the Kremlin doctrine
of reasonable or defensive sufficiency, he had seen ``absolutely no
practical change.''
   ``If anything, their military continues to grow. They continue
to modernize,'' Carlucci said.
   Yazov, who also arrived in Bern on Tuesday for the opening of
the three-day session, said before he left Moscow that he hoped for
a ``frank, constructive discussion'' on arms control issues
including strategic arms, nuclear testing, chemical and
conventional weapons.
   Carlucci emphasized that he did not want the meeting, the first
business session between U.S. and Soviet defense secretaries, to
open a ``parallel channel'' to ongoing superpower arms negotiations
in Geneva.
   Yazov and Carlucci were attending a dinner by Swiss Defense
Minister Arnold Koller on Tuesday night, and were to sit down for
formal talks on Wednesday and Thursday.
   Yazov and other Soviet officials have said they are moving
toward a new doctrine, relying on defense. But Kremlin leader
Mikhail Gorbachev, Yazov, and other military and civilian
commentators have offered different versions of the doctrine,
puzzling Western analysts.
   ``I'm still not sure what it is,'' said Carlucci. ``That's a
question, by the way, I intend to ask him.''
   If Yazov wants to prove that the Kremlin is moving from an
offensive to a defensive posture, said Carlucci, he should seek ``a
slacking off in tank production, in artillery production, maybe
desisting from highly accurate follow-on systems like the SS-18''
intercontinental ballistic missile, which carries 10 nuclear
warheads.
   U.S. negotiators have raised all those issues in the Geneva
talks, but it is not clear when agreements may be reached to cut
strategic and conventional arsenals.
   Carlucci said U.S. analysts were looking for unilateral Soviet
action to define the new Kremlin doctrine.
   ``One of the most important indicators, I would think, would be
tanks. But tanks continue to pour out. So there is no indication at
the other end of the pipeline that there has been any change,''
said Carlucci.
   Yazov, in remarks reported from Moscow by the official Soviet
news agency Tass, said nothing about the doctrine.
   ``The goal'' of the session, he said, ``is to facilitate the
search for ways of resolving the most acute and immediate issues of
strategic offensive weapons and the (1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile)
treaty, reduction of the armed forces and conventional armaments in
Europe, termination of nuclear testing, and prohibition and
elimination of chemical weapons.''
</TEXT>
