<DOCNO> AP880315-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 1627EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Darden-Lakeland     03-15 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Darden-Lakeland,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Killer's Surviving Victims Angry Over Execution Delays</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Darden Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKELAND, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two people whose identification and
testimony sent Willie Jasper Darden to the electric chair expressed
relief Tuesday that their ordeal had ended but anger that it had
taken so long.
   ``I think it's long overdue,'' said Helen Turman Baum, whose
husband, Jim, was shot dead in front of her in 1973. ``I need to
get on with my life. ... He (Darden) put me through torture. No one
knows what I have suffered through his hands. ... It is torture
when you see a loved one shot down in front of your eyes.''
   A 16-year-old boy who came to her aid in the Turmans' Lakeland
furniture store was shot three times but survived.
   ``Justice has finally prevailed,'' Phillip Arnold said at the
Tampa asphalt company where he works. ``But it wasn't as swift and
efficient as it's supposed to be.''
   While death penalty opponents and Darden supporters said his
execution Tuesday meant the judicial system had failed, the
prosecutor, C. Ray McDaniel, criticized the length of the legal
battles ``and the unnecessary waste of legal and judicial manpower
that went into the case.''
   ``Those opponents of the death penalty simply hitched their
wagon to the wrong mule,'' said McDaniel, now a private attorney in
Bartow. ``I wish 10 percent of their efforts and the money spent
could have gone to the victims. ... Mrs. Turman's life was ruined
... because of this.''
   Mrs. Baum, 59, remarried four years ago.
   She was making breakfast and hurrying to take her husband, Fred
Baum, to a doctor when she was called by a friend and told that
Darden had been executed. She cried a little.
   Arnold and Mrs. Turman rejected recent statements by a Baptist
minister and a Lakeland secretary, who disputed testimony about the
attack. Their statements provided ammunition for Darden and
supporters who said he had been wrongly identified as the killer.
   ``I identified him several days later (after the crime) because
his face stood out to me. I know in my heart it was him,'' Mrs.
Baum said.
   ``There's no doubt in my mind. There never has been,'' said
Arnold.
</TEXT>
