<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-IrvingBerlin     03-15 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Irving Berlin,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Berlin 100th Birthday Tribute Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Irving Berlin tribute on the composer's 100th
birthday, May 11, will star an array of classical and popular
musicians ranging from Leonard Bernstein to Willie Nelson, from
Isaac Stern to Frank Sinatra.
   The tribute at Carnegie Hall will, at Berlin's request, benefit
the Carnegie Hall Society and the American Society of Composers,
Authors and Publishers Foundation, ASCAP's Ken Sunshine announced
Tuesday.
   Sunshine said the gala will be taped by CBS-TV and a broadcast
date will be announced later. Don Mischer will be executive
producer for the network.
   Berlin is the last surviving founding member of ASCAP, which
began at a dinner at Luchow's Restaurant on 14th Street in
Manhattan in 1914. Composers present, including Berlin, Victor
Herbert, Jerome Kern and John Philip Sousa, decided to form an
organization to protect their copywrights.
   Tickets to the concert and a ``Top Hat, White Tie and Tails''
dinner-dance afterwards are $1,000. Tickets to the concert only are
$250, $100, $75 and $50. The Carnegie Hall box office, taking its
cue from Berlin's ``Easter Parade,'' will start selling tickets on
Easter Sunday.
</TEXT>
