<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ChildCare     03-15 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Care,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bill To Be Changed To Avoid Discrimination Against Religious
Groups</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate sponsor of a $2.5 billion child
care bill said Tuesday he will change it to address complaints that
it discriminates against religious groups who provide some of the
nation's best child care.
   ``Within the next week or so we are going to resolve that
issue,'' said Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., sponsor of the Act
for Better Child Care or ABC bill. ``These concerns will be
resolved to the satisfaction of all.''
   The bill, which has 37 Senate co-sponsors, would provide grants
to nonprofit agencies to expand child care as well as money for
child care certificates to working parents with incomes below a
certain level.
   It would deny funding for ``any program or activity that has the
purpose or effect of advancing or promoting a particular religion
or religion generally.'' And it would cancel a Civil Rights Act
provision allowing religious institutions to hire employees on the
basis of religion.
   John Carr, an official with the U.S. Catholic Conference, said
his group supports the goals of the ABC bill and other child care
legislation before Congress but objects to those two provisions.
   ``We are working with the sponsors to see if the church-state
problems can be resolved,'' Carr, the conference's secretary for
social development and world peace, said in an interview. ``Much of
the child care now provided is provided in churches and by
religious groups, and we don't want to see an effort to broaden
quality child care exclude those groups. We're quite hopeful a
solution can be found.''
   The ABC bill was discussed at a hearing Tuesday before the
Senate Labor and Human Resources subcommittee on children, chaired
by Dodd.
   Lawmakers across the ideological spectrum are reaching agreement
that the nation needs more, better and expanded child care services
to address what Sen. Orrin Hatch called ``a bipartisan problem of
families.'' The major points of contention are over how much to
spend and whether states or the federal government should regulate
day care.
   Hatch, R-Utah, has proposed a somewhat different and less
expensive approach to the problem. He said the ABC bill's price tag
is prohibitive while its licensing requirements and religious
provisions seem to discourage home-based care and participation by
religious institutions.
   Dodd said the bill's sponsors are ``strong supporters of home
care. We just want to see minimum standards'' for day care workers,
homes and centers. He said the religious problem would be worked
out.
   The only witness against the bill was William Bentley Ball, a
Harrisburg, Pa., lawyer representing the Association of Christian
Schools International, an organization of evangelical Christian
educational institutions including 1,000 preschools. Ball said the
schools on principle would not take federal money, but said parents
otherwise eligible for aid should not be penalized for sending
their children there.
   Conservative activist Phyllis Schlafly, who opposes any federal
encouragement of day care, led a protest outside the building where
Dodd was holding his hearing.
   In the February edition of her monthly newsletter, Schlafly
referred to the Dodd bill as an attempt to ``sovietize the American
family by warehousing babies in government-licensed institutions
where they would be subjected to secular, unisex custodial care by
government-trained personnel, while their mothers would be trapped
full-time in the paid labor force.''
   Debra and and Michael Brooks of Gunnison, Colo., presented a
different view inside the hearing room. The couple's first child
was killed when his day care provider _ a woman with no training
and little experience _ struck him on the head. The woman, now in
prison, was ``not a stranger. I considered her a friend,'' said
Mrs. Brooks.
   Her husband said the experience shocked him into realizing that
his government was not monitoring or regulating child care. ``I had
no idea of the things that could go wrong,'' he told Dodd. ``I
trusted in a system that simply didn't exist.''
</TEXT>
