<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FeldeExecution     03-15 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Felde Execution,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Felde Executed In Louisiana</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Darden Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANGOLA, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wayne Felde, who claimed post-Vietnam War
stress drove him to murder a rookie policeman, died in Louisiana's
electric chair Tuesday after delivering a cryptic two-sentence
message to those who watched him die.
   ``You can kill the messenger but you can't kill the message,''
he said slowly and matter of factly, giving three reporters
separated from him by a glass window time to write down each word.
``Sooner or later, you have to acknowledge it for what it means,
not for what you want it to mean.''
   The 38-year-old killer was then led by four guards a few steps
from the microphone to the big oak electric chair. Four alternating
jolts of 2,400 volts and 500 volts of electricity were administered
over one minute. Doctors pronounced him deat at 12:14 a.m.
   Felde died for killing Officer Glen Tompkins in 1978, as Felde
was being driven to jail in Shreveport. Felde had been picked up on
a drunkeness charge and apparently had not been throroughly
searched. He pulled a gun from his clothes and shot three times
through the front seat.
   Three Shreveport officers joined the few pro death penalty
demonstrators who come to the remote prison each time the state
schedules an execution.
   ``Justice is being done tonight,'' said Sgt. Glenn Ramsey. ``I
hate it. It took 10 years.''
   Cpl. Joe Feconda, who drove Tompkins' widow home from the
hospital after the shooting, said he is still haunted by the
memory. A third officer declined to be identified.
   Felde was captured the night of Tompkins' murder when a lawman's
shotgun blast brought him down. Scars from the blast could be seen
on the lower right side of his chest as his body was examined in
the electric chair.
   Warden Hilton Butler told reporters shortly before the execution
that Felde did not desire or expect a last-minute stay of execution.
   At his 1980 trial, Felde asked the jury that convicted him to
recommend the death penalty, ``or other deaths will result.'' But
he later helped in appeals that delayed his execution for eight
years.
   Felde had enlisted in the Army at age 18 and was sent to war in
1967. The experience, he claimed, left him unable to tell right
from wrong.
   Felde's lawyers had hoped Gov. Buddy Roemer _ who took office
about 12 hours before the electrocution _ would grant Felde a stay
and a new Pardon Board hearing. But Roemer, who had said last week
he had no plans to delay Felde's death, decided against stopping
the execution after meeting late Monday with Bill Quigley, a lawyer
for Felde.
</TEXT>
