<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     03-15 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brite and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELLEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you've been wondering why the U.S.
space program has fizzled or why Johnny can't multiply anymore,
Phil Paeltz has an answer: the demise of the slide rule.
   The headmaster of the Governor French Academy is organizing a
National Slide Rule Museum in this southwestern Illinois city as a
shrine to the device, made virtually extinct by the onslaught of
the pocket calculator in the early 1970s.
   ``The thing that frightens me to death is that we seemed to have
gotten along a whole lot better with these than we are getting
along with the computer,'' said Paeltz.
   ``It was the slide rule that put together `E equals mc squared'
and it was the slide rule that put together the beginning of the
space program. Much of what we talk about as America's pre-eminent
technical position was all computed on slide rules.''
   Paeltz yearns for a return to pre-calculator days and thinks
many schools put too much emphasis on machines.
   ``A slide rule is slower, but I wonder if it doesn't have some
very beneficial things. When there is something physical as well as
mental involved in a process I think people remember things
better,'' Paeltz said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There was only one thing the Bi-State
Development Agency could give Edna Schroeder to commemorate her
retirement.
   The 73-year-old woman, who took public transportation to her
downtown job for 55 years without missing a day or arriving late
for work, received a lifetime bus pass in honor of her retirement
last month.
   Schroeder, who worked the whole time for Norcliff Thayer Inc.,
the maker of Tums, said she used to ride the street car before the
bus came along. She said she never owned a car.
   ``We at Bi-State take great pride in the fact that all that time
you used the bus,'' said Raymond Jurkowski, Bi-State's deputy
director.
   Schroeder said she would use the pass presented to her Monday to
``ride the bus to places I've never ridden to before.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KEARNS, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bennion Elementary School Principal Ken
Higgins has paid ``deerly'' for doubting his students' reading
capabilities.
   The principal spent Monday's lunch periods locked in a Utah
Division of Wildlife deer cage for losing a bet that students could
not do 500,000 pages in outside reading. They ended up last week
more than doubling that goal.
   After students hit an original target of 250,000 pages quickly,
Higgins raised the goal to 500,000 and offered a pizza party for
the class that came up with the best penalty for Higgins.
Eventually, he boosted the target to 1 million pages, a mark the
students hit last week.
   ``What was really neat was everyone was into the project,'' he
said.
   ``I was really nervous,'' he said about spending 90 minutes in
the cage, ``but it worked out well. And the important thing was it
got the kids reading.'' He spent the time chatting with students
and reading to the younger students.
   Higgins isn't done yet, however. One of the winning class
suggestions was a ride in a hot air balloon. High winds Monday
grounded the plans, but the tire company that owns the balloon
agreed to return when Higgins can take the trip.
   The principal acknowledges a fear of heights, but has vowed to
complete the agreement. ``I couldn't live with myself if I didn't
do what I said I would do,'' he said.
</TEXT>
