<2ND_LINE>AM-Youth Awards,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Outstanding Teens Get Awards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Education Secretary William Bennett
congratulated the 50 winners of an annual national award for
outstanding teen-agers Tuesday and declared that ``there's no
shortage of character in our young people.''
   Ten of the 50 recipients of the Sea Breeze Awards, a public
service project of Clairol Inc., were honored at a luncheon in the
Senate Caucus Room, where each received a $500 grant and a framed
citation.
   The winners received the awards for acting ``with courage,
heroism, integrity, compassion or in a spirit of public service to
make their world a better place.''
   The 10 recipients honored at the lunch were Rochelle Badger, 18,
Valmeyer, Ill.; Steven Bonacorsi, 18, Salem, N.H.; Darla Byrd, 17,
Rutledge, Tenn.; Sean T. Fox, 18, Winlock, Wash.; Jennifer Gates,
16, North Palm Beach, Fla.; Rosa Gonzalez, 18, Castro Valley,
Calif.; Alphonso Guest, 16, North Little Rock, Ark.; Michelle
Jones, 13, Mountain Home, Ark.; Audrey Nenoff, 18, Westwood, N.J.,
and Quoc Van-Dong, 17, Elk Mound, Wis.
   Bennett said the awards honor ``excellence in character.'' He
thanked each of the teens for ``helping us believe in the spiritual
wealth of the world.''
   ``Whatever your circumstances in life, you'll have opportunities
to show what you're made of, where your heart is,'' he said.
