<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drug-Chemicals     03-15 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug-Chemicals,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>450 Gallons Of Toxic Chemicals Found Along California Road</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAYTONVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 450 gallons of highly flammable
and toxic chemicals found in drums along a busy road probably were
the waste product of an illegal drug laboratory, authorities said
Tuesday.
   The chemicals, which included acetone and ether, were found
Monday in 10 drums about 4 miles west of this northern California
town, according to Greg Smith, coordinator of emergency services
and assistant fire chief for Mendocino County.
   The chemicals, along with another 400 gallons found on two other
occasions in the past two months, probably came from a laboratory
making methamphetamine, commonly known as speed, in the area, he
said.
   ``The problem with these people is they don't take any
consideration of waterways or school children waiting nearby,''
said Smith. He noted there was a creek 50 feet from the drums and a
school bus stop 150 yards away.
   There were no injuries, but Smith said there was concern about
the chemicals because the drums had small leaks and some of the
chemicals were crystalizing and foaming.
</TEXT>
