<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MayorCharged     03-15 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mayor Charged,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Duluth Mayor Charged With 22 Felonies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DULUTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor John Fedo has been charged with
swindling, falsifying entries in his city expense records and lying
to the state auditor about how city money was spent, but he says
it's a case of dirty politics.
   The indictment ``is not going to have an effect on City Hall,''
Fedo said at a news conference Monday, insisting that the charges
are an elaborate ploy by his political enemies.
   The indictment, including 22 felonies, was returned Thursday by
a St. Louis County grand jury and was made public after Fedo, in
office nearly nine years, was arraigned Monday.
   The indictment includes one count of theft, one count of failure
to pay over state funds, six counts of presenting false claims to a
public officer or body, 13 counts of permitting false claims
against the government, one count of obstructing the state auditor
and one count of misconduct of a public employee.
   If convicted, Fedo, 37, faces a maximum penalty of 10 years in
prison on the theft charge and up to five years in prison on most
of the other charges. He was freed on his own recognizance. A
hearing is scheduled for May 3.
   Fedo's lawyer, Douglas Sauter, said he will move for dismissal
of the charges. Fedo was ``tried once in the election and found not
guilty,'' he said.
   Fedo, a member of Minnesota's Democratic-Farmer-Labor Party, won
his first four-year term as mayor in 1979 and has been re-elected
twice.
   The theft charge concerns $13,500 given to Fedo by three
businessmen to lobby for state funds for a convention center in the
city.
   During the 1987 election campaign, Fedo said he passed the funds
to an unnamed Twin Cities businessman in 1985 in exchange for
information about other cities' convention center proposals.
   Duluth, a city of 85,000 on the western tip of Lake Superior,
was never in competition for a $200 million convention center for
which Bloomington and Minneapolis vied, according to the charges.
The Legislature awarded Duluth a total of $17.2 million for its
relatively small center.
   Prosecutors say the mayor played a limited role in lobbying for
the convention center which he later claimed to have won almost
single-handedly.
</TEXT>
