<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Disarm-Soviet     03-15 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Disarm-Soviet,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets See Deadlock At Chemical Weapons Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union said Tuesday negotations on
banning chemical weapons are stagnating, and blamed the United
States and Britain.
   Yuri Nazarkin, chief Soviet delegate to the 40-nation Conference
on Disarmament, said some Western delegations ``unfortunately make
an ever greater emphasis on the idea that allegedly there is no
need to hurry, that there is a lot more work to be done.'' His
reference was to recent statements by U.S. and British delegates.
   Tessa Solesby of Britain responded by telling the conference:
``We have to cope with a formidable number of technical
difficulties. This is why I am uneasy and my authorities are uneasy
when we are told a solution lies just around the corner.''
   U.S. envoy Max Friedersdorf agreed and urged the Soviet Union to
provide more information on the size of its chemical weapons
arsenal.
   The disarmament conference began negotiations in 1968 on a
convention to bar production, stockpiling and use of chemical arms.
   Nazarkin, in a declaration he said was aimed at helping the
exchange of information, claimed the Soviets have not transferred
chemical arms equipment or technology to other states.
   ``The Soviet delegation is concerned about a slowdown, even
stagnation'' of negotiations, but a draft convention could be
finished this year if there is a drastic change of pace, he told
reporters later.
   Nazarkin spoke of three main obstacles to an agreement: The
order of destruction of weapons over a 10-year period, inspection
provisions for commercial chemical plants, and mandatory inspection
of weapons sites on short notice if a violation is suspected.
   Nazarkin repeated the Soviet claim that Washington is blocking
progress by seeking exemptions for private industry.
</TEXT>
