<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CommunityChapel     03-15 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Community Chapel,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearing For Pastor, Elders Of Community Chapel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Tuesday made formal an order
reinstating a pastor accused by church elders of adultery stemming
from his exhortations to build ``spiritual connections'' through
dancing with other members' spouses.
   Donald Lee Barnett has admitted he sinned, but says he repented
and wants to remain as pastor of Community Chapel and Bible
Training Center, based in Burien, south of Seattle.
   The dispute spilled into court last week, and King County
Superior Court Judge Jim Bates on Tuesday signed an order he issued
verbally on Friday, which reinstated Barnett.
   A week earlier, church elders ``disfellowshipped'' Barnett,
accusing him of sexual misconduct with several women in the
congregation and saying he would not follow restrictions against
being alone with any female parishioner other than his wife.
   Church elders filed a new motion Tuesday for a more detailed
restraining order, which would prevent both sides from: firing
church employees; interfering with worship services scheduled by
either side; authorizing expenditures except through the
established system; giving keys to buildings, offices r files to
unauthorized people; destroying church documents; and hiring new
employees except through the established system. Bates set a
hearing Thursday.
   Barnett, 57, founded the 1,500-member church in 1967. He has an
unpublished telephone number, and could not be reached for comment.
   Competing services were held Sunday, and an affidavit by elder
Scott Hartley said that while Barnett attracted 240 and 195 people
to two services, the elders' services attracted 600 and 660 people.
   Church spokesman Chuck Kerr said a note from Barnett was posted
at the school chapel, reading: ``Anyone who walks in this building
will be `disfellowshipped' and staff will be fired.'' When Barnett
heard how many attended the elders' service, he rescinded the
order, according to Kerr.
   A former Boeing draftsman, Barnett guided the church from a
Bible study group to an organization that once had members in this
country, western Canada, and several other countries. Membership
locally was once about 2,500.
   Dissident members have said many problems resulted from
Barnett's preaching of ``spiritual connection,'' a relationship
between church members of opposite sexes with partners other than
their spouses. The members are encouraged to dance with regular
partners, or ``connections.''
   Some former members have said relationships that developed
between these partners have led to suicide and broken marriages.
More than a half-dozen former members have sued, some alleging
Barnett sexually assaulted them under the pretense of ministerial
counseling.
   On March 20, 1986, a woman drowned her 5-year-old daughter in a
bathtub, believing it would save the child from demons. Court
records said the woman was tormented by her 18 years of involvement
in the church. She was sent to an institution.
</TEXT>
