<1ST_LINE>u i AM-India-Strike     03-15 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Strike,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Arrested in General Strike Against Gandhi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi
shuttered businesses and took to the streets in six Indian states
Tuesday, but the general strike failed to win widespread support.
   Police arrested 7,000 people in the street clashes, which left
seven dead and 200 injured, news reports said.
   Shops and offices were closed and traffic was disrupted in
Bombay, India's business center, and Calcutta, its largest city.
   There were few signs of support, however, for the opposition-led
strike in the other 19 Indian states. It drew little apparent
backing in New Delhi, where most businesses remained open.
   The strike was called by most major opposition parties to
protest sectarian violence, rising prices and alleged corruption in
government. The parties, which include two communist groups, demand
that Parliament be dissolved and new elections held.
   In Parliament, proceedings were disrupted for more than an hour
Tuesday when opposition members raised anti-government slogans in
the upper house. Earlier, the entire opposition boycotted the first
hour of business in both houses in support of the strike.
   Gandhi's Congress Party holds more than 400 of 542 seats in the
popularly elected lower house. The rest are divided among
opposition parties which have been divided despite common demands
that Gandhi resign.
   At least five people were killed in clashes in eastern Bihar
state, according to the United News of India. The news agency also
reported that two people were killed and seven injured when a flour
mill owner opened fire at opposition party supporters attacking his
mill near the coastal city of Ernakulam in southern Kerala state.
   The agency said at least 75 people were hurt in political
violence in West Bengal state.
   State-run television said only two people died in
strike-connected violence.
   At least 1,500 people were arrested in central Madhya Pradesh
state and another 1,000 in eastern Assam state, UNI said.
   It said 14 policemen were injured near the Pakistani border in
Rajasthan state when they were pelted with stones as they tried to
remove roadblacks.
</TEXT>
