<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Students     03-15 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Students,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polish Official Denies Police Clubbed Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban on
Tuesday disputed reports that riot police clubbed students last
week to break up marches commemorating the anniversary of campus
protests 20 years ago.
   He said no general orders were issued for police to use force to
stop the March 8 student demonstrations in Warsaw and Krakow. If
force was used, it was applied only sporadically when
demonstrations turned violent, he added.
   ``I deny Western reports that police used clubs to disperse
demonstrations,'' said Urban at his weekly news conference.
``Police did not have any orders to use force without necessity,
without some aggression from the side of illegal demonstrators.''
   The demonstrations for more academic freedom coincided with the
anniversary of March 1968 student protests against censorship and
political repression that were violently broken up by police and
pro-government workers.
   The outlawed Solidarity union condemned the authorities'
reaction to the March 8 demonstrations. It issued a statement
saying that several people were hospitalized after they were beaten
by police.
   The labor group, in a statement drawn up at a meeting Sunday of
its National Executive Commission, said the police action reflected
``a growth of repressive tendencies'' on the part of communist
authorities.
   Lech Walesa, who won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1983, heads the
committee.
   ``So the situation of 20 years ago has been repeated, which
finally puts the lie to the authorities' statements about a change
of judgment of the disgraceful events of '68,'' said the statement,
which was read over the telephone Tuesday by Solidarity's national
spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz.
   At Urban's news conference, Western reporters said they had seen
riot police charging demonstrators and hitting them with clubs to
disperse a march by several hundred students after a Mass at
Warsaw's St. Anne's Church.
   Urban replied, ``You have an undoubted advantage over me ... but
it's the task of police to prevent an illegal demonstration.''
   The students were demanding restoration of academic freedoms won
during the 1980-81 Solidarity labor upheaval and legalization of
the Independent Students Union, which was outlawed under martial
law in 1982.
   The government said police detained 83 people taking part in the
student protests in Warsaw and Krakow.
   Solidarity was chartered by the government during nationwide
strikes in the fall of 1980. It was suspended in December 1981 and
subsequently outlawed by Parliament.
</TEXT>
