<HEAD>U.S. Rejects Panama's Request for Envoy's Departure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Embassy in Panama has rejected an
attempt by Panama's two-week-old government to order an American
embassy officer out of the country, the State Department said
Tuesday.
   The Panamanian government on Monday asked Terrence Kneebone,
director of the U.S. Information Service, to leave the country
within 48 hours. No explanation was given.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said the U.S. Embassy
rejected the Panamanian note because it was delivered by
representatives of a regime not recognized by the United States as
the legitimate authority in Panama.
   There was no immediate indication what Panama's next step would
be.
   In late February, President Eric Arturo Delvalle was ousted and
replaced by the education minister, Manuel Solis Palma. The United
States continues to recognize Delvalle as Panama's president.
