<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WheelchairProtest     03-15 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wheelchair Protest,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disabled Protesters Arrested After Blocking Rush Hour Traffic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-three protesters in wheelchairs and a
blind person were arrested Tuesday after blocking buses during
morning rush hour at the Department of Transportation, police said.
   The demonstrators, members of Americans Disabled for Accessible
Public Transit, were protesting the appeal by the Transportation
Department of a judge's ruling that all public transit authorities
provide services for the handicapped regardless of cost.
   The protesters had chained themselves to the entrances of the
transportation building Monday afternoon and stayed there through
the night as temperatures dipped below freezing. In the morning,
they wheeled themselves into the traffic, District of Columbia
Police Officer Walter Ferguson said.
   ``We kept warm with the thought we were sending the Department
of Transportation a message that we will take any action necessary
to obtain our civil rights,'' protester Stephanie Thomas told
hearing commissioner John Treanor after her arrest.
   Treanor released the protesters on $10 bond each, saying they
could forfeit the bond in lieu of a fine.
   The demonstrators were charged with obstructing traffic at about
9 a.m., police said.
   ``It is unfortunate disabled people have to take these actions.
But we'll continue to do so until the federal government
acknowledges our right to use public transit,'' said Clayton Jones,
a protester from Hartford, Conn.
   The Department of Transportation is appealing the Jan. 4
decision by U.S. District Judge Marvin Katz in Philadelphia which
struck down the department's regulation that transit agencies spend
3 percent of their budgets on the disabled.
   Katz called the 3 percent an ``arbitrary and capricious'' figure
that was so low it denied the handicapped ``the minimum quality of
service mandated by the Congress.''
   Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley spoke briefly with the
demonstrators Monday and offered to meet them again next week, said
Hal Paris, spokesman for the department.
   ``We haven't heard anything from them,'' Burnley said Tuesday.
   He confirmed that the department was appealing Katz' decision
but would not elaborate while the case is pending.
</TEXT>
