<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-FerreiraAldunate     03-15 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Ferreira Aldunate,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Uruguayan Opposition Leader Ferreira Aldunate Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wilson Ferreira Aldunate, head of the
National Party, the largest opposition party in Uruguay, died
Tuesday of cancer, his family said. He was 69.
   The government declared 24 hours of national mourning.
   His wife, Susana Sienra, sons Gonzalo and Juan Raul and daughter
Silvia were at his side when he died. Hundreds of mourners gathered
outside his home in the seaside suburb of Pocitos to pay respects
to the political leader, who had been ill since July.
   Ferreira Aldunate ran for president in 1971 and narrowly lost to
Juan Bordaberry of the Colorado Party.
   He went into exile in 1973 and lived abroad for 11 years after
the military seized power.
   An outspoken critic of the right-wing military regime, he was
imprisoned upon his return to Uruguay in 1984. The military
government refused to let him run for president in 1985, but
released him five days after the elections.
   Ferreira Aldunate, son of a rancher and rural doctor, studied
for the law, but then went into politics. He was a member of
Congress for 34 years and was agriculture minister from 1963-67.
   He consolidated control over the centrist National Party in the
1960s while in the Senate.
   President Raul Alfonsin of Argentina mourned the death of his
friend Ferreira Aldunate as the loss of ``a notable figure in
Uruguayan democracy and in Latin America.''
   A Mass is planned Tuesday in the metropolitan cathedral. Burial
will be Wednesday in Montevideo.
</TEXT>
