<1ST_LINE>r w AM-JudgeNixon     03-15 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Judge Nixon,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judicial Panel Says House Should Consider Impeachment of Judge
Nixon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of judges that makes policy for the
federal courts urged the House on Tuesday to consider impeaching
U.S. District Judge Walter L. Nixon of Mississippi, who is
scheduled to go to prison for perjury on March 23.
   The group, the Judicial Conference of the United States,
unanimously supported a resolution that says ``consideration of
impeachment may be warranted.''
   Nixon, 59, sentenced to five years in prison following his 1986
perjury conviction, has remained a judge but has not been hearing
cases since he was indicted in 1985. He continues to be paid his
annual salary of $89,500.
   Nixon would forfeit his salary and his eligibility for a pension
at age 65 if he is impeached by the House and removed from office
by the Senate.
   The recommendation that the House consider impeaching him was
approved by a vote of 24-0 by the judges' group. Three members
abstained, including Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, who
traditionally does not vote on such matters.
   Nixon has been a federal judge since 1968 and chief judge for
Mississippi's southern district since 1982.
   His legal problems stemmed from his business relationship with
Wiley Fairchild, a wealthy investor who sold three oil well
properties to Nixon in 1980 at bargain prices.
   Nixon, who netted more than $50,000 from the deal, testified he
bought the oil and gas rights in three wells for $9,500 in a
legitimate transaction and promised no favor to Fairchild in return.
   He was acquitted of bribery by a federal jury, but was convicted
of lying to a grand jury when he denied discussing drug charges
against Fairchild's son with the elder Fairchild and with a
Mississippi prosecutor.
   The Supreme Court on Jan. 19 denied Nixon's appeal, clearing the
way for his imprisonment.
   Nixon is the third federal judge ever to be indicted for crimes
allegedly committed while in office.
   U.S. District Judge Alcee Hastings of Florida was acquitted of
bribery in 1983 and impeachment proceedings against him are pending
in the House.
   Former federal judge Harry Claiborne of Nevada was convicted in
1984 of failing to report $106,000 on his federal income tax
returns and was sentenced to two years in prison. He was impeached
and removed from office in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880315-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 2115EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-LeanHotdogs     03-15 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lean Hotdogs,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Processors May Substitute Water For Fat, USDA Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Processors who make hotdogs, bologna and other
cooked sausages soon will be allowed to make leaner products by
substituting water for fat, so long as there is no loss of
nutritional value, the Agriculture Department said Tuesday.
   The leaner products can be labeled as ``lite,'' ``light,'' or
``lower fat'' if they contain at least a fourth less fat than
similar cooked sausage products on the market, officials said. The
labels must include a comparison that explains the term.
   For example, the label for lower-fat hotdogs might say: ``This
product contains 20 percent fat, while USDA allows 30 percent fat
in meat hotdogs.''
   Lester M. Crawford, administrator of the department's Food
Safety and Inspection Service, said the change in regulations will
be effective on April 14 and ``reflects our desire to facilitate
the marketing of lower-fat products.''
   Current federal rules for cooked sausages limit fat to 30
percent and ``added'' water to 10 percent. The new rule will limit
the combination of fat and added water to 40 percent of the product.
   The maximum fat content in the finished product will continue to
be limited to 30 percent, but the water restriction will be removed
so that processors can substitute some of the water for fat _ and
wind up with a lower-fat product, Crawford said.
   Protein content, which is indirectly controlled by the limits on
fat and added water, will remain unchanged and will be comparable
to other cooked sausages, he said.
   The rule change is being made at the request of the American
Meat Institute, a private trade association, which asked USDA to
develop a standard for light frankfurters and similar cooked
sausages. The proposed change was announced by the agency on Nov.
25, 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
