<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0727,0766</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Says Soviets Cannot Give Up Central Control</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with later Gorbachev comments, other
details</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev toured a
factory Tuesday that exports industrial robots to the Soviets and
Americans and told the workers the Soviet Union is too big to give
up all central control.
   The Yugoslav factory operates under the government's
local-management system.
   The reform-minded Soviet leader is on a five-day visit to
Yugoslavia, getting his first look at this independent Communist
country's freer economy.
   Soviet officials said Gorbachev was ``very satisfied'' with his
first two days of talks with Yugoslav leaders and seeks ways of
developing closer relations with the country Moscow once denounced
for ``revisionist'' policies.
   President Tito broke with Soviet dictator Josef Stalin in 1948,
defying the Kremlin's authority in the communist world, and
developed ties to the West. Years of plots and threats from Moscow
followed.
   Relations were mended in the 1950s, with Nikita S. Khrushchev in
charge at the Kremlin, but the last visit to Yugoslavia by a Soviet
leader was in 1980, when Leonid I. Brezhnev attended Tito's funeral.
   During a brief photo session Tuesday, Gorbachev told reporters:
``We got off to a good start.''
   The two sides exchanged copies of a new declaration
acknowledging Yugoslavia's independence from Soviet control, which
replaces similar statements issued in 1955 and 1956. A Yugoslav
spokesman said the document would not be made public until the end
of Gorbachev's visit Friday.
   Fyodor Burlatsky, a Soviet columnist traveling with Gorbachev,
said the Kremlin is preparing to adopt some practices similar to
those in Yugoslavia, among them allowing the open sale of
international newspapers and magazines.
   ``Everybody can hear many voices'' in Yugoslavia, Burlatsky said
in an interview. ``I believe there will be new decisions taken in a
short time'' to let Soviet newstands sell non-Soviet publications.
   He also praised progress Yugoslavia has made ``from bureaucracy
to self-managing socialism.''
   Public interest remained high in the visit by Gorbachev and his
wife, Raisa.
   Crowds gathered to watch the motorcade pass. When word spread
Tuesday evening that the Soviet leader would stop in a downtown
square, several thousand people turned up, but the stop turned out
not to be on his schedule.
   Earlier in the day, the Gorbachevs visited the Park of Peace to
plant a tree, a customary practice.
   To a group of children attending the ceremony, Gorbachev said
the park contains trees planted by many leaders of the non-aligned
movement, of which Tito was a founder.
   ``You take care of this park,'' he said, and carefully shoveled
every bit of dirt from a small pile set aside for the planting.
   After chatting and joking with the children, the Gorbachevs
lined up with them for photographs. He promised the children they
would receive copies.
   At the Ivo Lola Ribar factory outside Belgrade, the Gorbachevs
were shown modern machine tools and robots used by auto-assembly
plants in both the East and West.
   Gorbachev met with the factory Worker Council, which is
responsible for plant operations.
   His ``perestroika'' program, designed to modernize the Soviet
economy, proposes reducing central planning and giving managers and
workers more control over their own factories, but he told the
workers some central control will remain.
   ``We have to maintain a regulatory role at the center to
safeguard us against mistakes, particularly because the country of
the Soviet Union is so large,'' Gorbachev said.
   He brushed off a reporter's question about what useful knowledge
he might take back to the Soviet Union. Gorbachev said his schedule
was too tight for questions.
   In a dinner toast, Gorbachev said ``Eastern and Western Europe
are gradually becoming less and less suspicious of each other.''
   He criticized what he called unfounded charges in the Western
media that he is trying ``to drive a wedge'' between the United
States and its NATO allies.
   ``I have already stated and will repeat once again: We never
had, nor do we now have any such ideas,'' Gorbachev said.
   The Soviet Union is Yugoslavia's largest trading partner. It
ships raw materials in exchange for manufactured goods that
generally are of higher quality than those made at home.
   In contrast to perennial Soviet shortages of consumer goods,
Yugoslavia's shops and markets brim with domestic and imported
products. Inflation is running at about 170 percent, however, the
unemployment rate is 15 percent and Yugoslavia has a $20 billion
debt to foreign creditors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
