<1ST_LINE>u a LowTemperatureRecordsAcrossTheSouth     03-15 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Low Temperature Records Across The South</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Arctic air broke or tied low-temperature records in 38 cities
across the South on Tuesday, while snow was scattered from the
Great Lakes to the southern Appalachians and a new storm was
brewing in the West.
   More record cold was forecast for Wednesday morning and freeze
warnings were posted across Georgia, most of Mississippi and
northern Florida. A hard freeze was forecast for northern and
central Georgia, threatening damage to fruit trees.
   Tuesday's record or record-tying lows were 31 at Alexandria,
La., a tie; 33 at Apalachicola, Fla.; 23 at Auburn, Ala.; 33 at
Austin, Texas, tie; 19 at Batesville, Ark., tie; 31 at Baton Rouge,
La., tie; 24 at Birmingham, Ala.; 19 at Bristol, Tenn.; 33 at
Bryan-College Station, Texas, tie; 13 at Calico Rock, Ark.; 19 at
Conway, Ark.; 22 at El Dorado, Ark.; 15 at Fayetteville, Ark.; 48
at Fort Myers, Fla., tie; 20 at Fort Smith, Ark., tie; 23 at Greer,
S.C., tie; 32 at Houston, Texas;
   And 22 at Huntsville, Ala.; 22 at Jackson, Miss.; 21 at
Jonesboro, Ark.; 20 at Knoxville, Tenn., tie; 31 at Lake Charles,
La.; 27 at Little Rock, Ark.; 27 at Macon, Ga.; 20 at Mena, Ark.;25
at Memphis, Tenn.; 20 at Meridian, Miss.; 27 at Mobile, Ala.; 26 at
Monroe, La.; 25 at Montgomery, Ala.; 40 at New Orleans, tie; 30 at
Pensacola, Fla.; 26 at Pine Bluff, Ark.; 18 at Pinson, Ala.; 31 at
San Antonio, Texas; 31 at Savannah, Ga.,tie; 27 at Shreveport, La.;
and 25 at Texarkana, Ark.
   Snow showers fell during the afternoon across much of the
Northeast, especially near the Great Lakes and from western
Illinois across the Ohio Valley and the central and southern
Appalachians to the mid Atlantic Coast.
   Four to 6 inches of snow fell in some lakeshore counties of
northeastern Ohio, while 2 to 4 inches fell across southern West
Virginia and around an inch at Boone and West Jefferson, N.C.
   Snow also fell in parts of Michigan, where Marquette got 2
inches of snow during the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST, bringing
their total snow depth to 43 inches.
   A storm system developing in the West was centered over western
Utah, spreading snow across sections of Wyoming, Utah, Idaho and
Nevada.
   Up to 3 inches of snow was reported at Hill Air Force Base in
northern Utah during the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST, while 3 to 6
inches fell in the mountains of northern Utah.
   A winter storm watch was posted for central and southwestern
Wyoming overnight and into Wednesday.
   The storm in Utah also generated high wind in sections of the
Southwest, with gusts to 66 mph at Mammoth Lakes, and gusts to 45
mph in the Owens Valley of California and in sections of the Mojave
Valley near Las Vegas, Nev.
   Unseasonably cold weather also moved into the Pacific Northwest
during the morning, dropping temperatures near the freezing mark in
the Seattle and Portland areas.
   Astoria, Ore., tied its record low of 28 and Olympia, Wash.,
dipped to a record 24 degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 16
degrees at Ellsworth Air Force Base outside Rapid City, S.D., to 75
in the California desert at Blythe, Imperial and Thermal. The early
morning low for the day was 9 degrees below zero at Dickinson, N.D.
   For Wednesday, snow showers were forecast from much of New
England across the northern and central Appalachians to northern
Indiana and Michigan. Snow or snow showers also were forecast in
Utah, and from the northern and central Rockies to much of Kansas.
Showers were forecast in Oklahoma and northern Texas.
   Highs in the 20s or 30s were predicted from New England across
the northern and central Appalachians, the Great Lakes, the upper
Mississippi Valley and the northern and central Plains to the
northern half of the Rockies; in the 60s in Florida and Louisiana,
and in parts of western Oregon; in the 60s or 70s across most of
Texas, southern New Mexico, southern Arizona and much of
California; and in the 40s or 50s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
