<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0716</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Low Temperature Records Across The South</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to restore slugline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Arctic air broke or tied low-temperature records in 38 cities
across the South on Tuesday, while snow was scattered from the
Great Lakes to the southern Appalachians and a new storm was
brewing in the West.
   More record cold was forecast for Wednesday morning and freeze
warnings were posted across Georgia, most of Mississippi and
northern Florida. A hard freeze was forecast for northern and
central Georgia, threatening damage to fruit trees.
   Tuesday's record or record-tying lows were 31 at Alexandria,
La., a tie; 33 at Apalachicola, Fla.; 23 at Auburn, Ala.; 33 at
Austin, Texas, tie; 19 at Batesville, Ark., tie; 31 at Baton Rouge,
La., tie; 24 at Birmingham, Ala.; 19 at Bristol, Tenn.; 33 at
Bryan-College Station, Texas, tie; 13 at Calico Rock, Ark.; 19 at
Conway, Ark.; 22 at El Dorado, Ark.; 15 at Fayetteville, Ark.; 48
at Fort Myers, Fla., tie; 20 at Fort Smith, Ark., tie; 23 at Greer,
S.C., tie; 32 at Houston, Texas;
   And 22 at Huntsville, Ala.; 22 at Jackson, Miss.; 21 at
