<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru a0786 03-15 1244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0786,1,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Says He Hasn't Bridged Differences With Shamir Over Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 6 grafs after 18th graf pvs, The president, with Sen.
Lautenberg quoting Shamir as saying nothing is off the table; picks
up 19th graf pvs, Shultz set</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz said
Tuesday he was unable to bridge differences with Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir over a U.S. plan for opening Mideast peace
negotiations by May 1.
   But he called the first of three days of talks with Shamir
constructive and said ``we feel encouraged to continue our efforts
to work with Israel and others in the Middle East.''
   Shamir underscored one of the main differences. He said that in
Israel's view, the Middle East peace conference Shultz wants to
convene next month to set the stage for negotiations could not play
``any positive role.''
   President Reagan sought, meanwhile, to reassure Shamir he would
not be put under U.S. pressure to agree to any particular solution
to Israel's 40-year dispute with the Arabs.
   But Reagan stressed that ``making progress toward peace in the
Middle East not only serves mutual interests, it is urgent.''
   In a speech to the United Jewish Appeal, the president said he
would tell Shamir at the White House on Wednesday that ``peace will
not be imposed by us or anyone else.''
   Shultz met with Shamir for about three hours, first over
blueberry pancakes at the secretary's home in suburban Maryland and
then at his State Department office.
   ``We haven't found our way to bridge all of the differences,''
Shultz said afterward. ``I see quite clearly what the nature of the
differences are and what they aren't.''
   Shultz did not offer any details, but Shamir restated his
opposition to an international forum that would include the Soviet
Union and China, which do not have diplomatic relations with Israel
and usually support Arab positions.
   ``We are interested, first of all, to negotiate directly with
all the parties concerned,'' Shamir said. ``We don't see any
positive role for an international conference.''
   The prime minister described his first round with Shultz as
``very serious and thorough.'' He pledged to cooperate ``to get
peace and to enhance the prospects for peace in our area.''
   But, he added, the Arabs were not willing to negotiate with
Israel.
   Avi Pazner, a spokesman for Shamir, said the U.S. proposal for
an international conference was ``a sticking point that has to be
resolved if we are going to go ahead.''
   King Hussein of Jordan has demanded the conference. Pazner said
Hussein sees it as ``an instrument which would be used by the
enemies of Israel, both Arabs and non-Arabs, like countries that do
not have diplomatic relations with Israel, to put pressure on
Israel, to try to bring Israel to agree to solutions it would not
agree to in free negotiations.''
   Shamir offered last October to hold Israeli-Jordanian
negotiations in Washington with U.S. and Soviet ``blessing.''
Pazner said Shamir stands by the offer even though it was rejected
by the king.
   The Israeli spokesman said Shamir did not give Shultz ``an
answer'' to the overall proposal for negotiations. ``He did not say
yes, he did not say no,'' he said.
   Speaking a half-mile away, at the Old Executive Office Building
next to the White House, Reagan said he would tell Shamir that
``when it comes to Israel the United States is not a bargainer or a
broker; the United States is a friend and an ally.''
   The president offered assurances to the Jewish gathering that
``we will not leave Israel to stand alone, nor will we acquiesce in
any effort to gang up on Israel.'' He added: ``Peace will not be
imposed by us or by anyone else. It will and must come from the
genuine give-and-take of negotiations. That's what we're working to
set in motion now.''
   In a meeting with a small group of senators at the Capitol,
Shamir was quoted as saying he was not ruling out any issue or
proposal as the subject for negotiations.
   ``The prime minister said there is nothing that is off the table
in terms of negotiations,'' said Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.
   Lautenberg said Shamir was asked whether he was ruling out
trading territory for peace with Israel's Arab nations.
   ``I didn't hear anything that said territory is excluded,''
Lautenberg said.
   Lautenberg said he got the impression that Shamir would be
prepared to be ``a lot more flexible'' in direct talks with Arab
states than he is in ``this pre-negotiation period.'' But he added:
``I don't think the prime minister's obstinancy about an
international conference is any less than it was earlier.''
   He said Shamir indicated he might be able to accept ``a
ceremonial group'' of other nations at the opening of discussions.
``But once serious discussions started he wanted to talk only to
Israel's (Arab) neighbors,'' the senator said.
   Shultz set this week as a deadline for a reply from Israel and
Jordan, which would form a delegation with Palestinians for the
negotiations.
   In Amman, a senior Jordanian official told The Associated Press
that Jordan was not yet ready to give a final response to Shultz's
plan.
   ``We are consulting with other Arab leaders,'' said the
official, who demanded anonymity. Asked when he expected the
Jordanian stand to be announced, he said: ``In the next 10 days or
so.''
   On Capitol Hill, Assistant Secretary of State Richard W. Murphy
sought to reassure supporters of Israel that an international
conference would not dictate solutions to any side. ``We won't
tolerate efforts _ such as ones by the Soviets or the Syrians _ to
turn this into an authoritative, plenipotentiary forum,'' he told a
House Foreign Affairs subcommittee.
   Murphy said the administration still has questions about the
terms under which the Soviets could participate in such a forum,
and these would be discussed next week when Foreign Minister Eduard
A. Shevardnadze visits Washington for talks with Shultz.
   Pressed by several congressmen why Shultz had softened his
opposition to Soviet participation, Murphy said no Arab state would
enter peace talks without a Soviet presence. ``They're (the
Soviets) in the region, and we have to find a way to deal with
them,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, nine senators made public the text of a letter to
Shultz urging him not to subject Shamir to U .S. criticism or
pressure.
   American support should not be used ``as a lever to force
Israel's leaders to adopt a policy which they see as dangerous to
the national security of their country _ especially when such
policy entails injecting the Soviet Union into the peace process,''
the letter said.
   The letter was signed by Sens. Chic Hecht, R-Nev.; Jesse Helms,
R-N.C.; Steven Symms, R-Idaho; David Karnes, R-Neb.; William L.
Armstrong, R-Colo.; Gordon J. Humphrey, R-N.H.; Phil Gramm,
R-Texas; Larry Pressler, R-S.D.; and Christopher Bond, R-Mo.
   Shultz's plan for peace talks anticipates Israel relinquishing
at least part of the West Bank and Gaza Strip it has held since the
1967 Six-Day War in exchange for Arab recognition of the Jewish
state.
   In a tough speech Monday night to another UJA group, Shamir said
yielding territory would invite another attempt by the Arabs to
destroy Israel.
   ``These matters are questions of life and death, of our very
existence,'' he said.
   Also on Shamir's schedule Tuesday were meetings with Treasury
Secretary James A. Baker III, Republican presidential aspirant Pat
Robertson and congressional leaders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
