<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--TaxBill     03-15 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Tax Bill,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Wants IRS Statement To Taxpayers On National Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York congressman proposed on Tuesday a
bill to require the Internal Revenue Service to send taxpayers a
``credit card statement'' highlighting the cost of federal deficit
spending.
   Rep. Joe DioGuardi, R-N.Y., who is a certified public
accountant, would require the IRS to put the national balance sheet
in the format of an individual's regular monthly credit bill. The
statement would be mailed with the government's annual income tax
forms.
   ``And I am sorry to report that the bottom line is that the
average American owes Uncle Sam $18,569.10 from all the unpaid
bills we have allowed to pile up,'' he said. The national debt is
about $2.5 trillion.
   DioGuardi's sample statement for fiscal 1987 includes the
previous balance of $17,118.08. It then details the purchases
ranging from $2,769.34 per taxpayer toward Social Security to
$73.60 for criminal justice.
   It then subtracts payments _ taxes _ and adds in the debt's
finance charge of $1,358,03 per taxpayer.
   Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for DioGuardi, said the congressman
had not determined how much producing and mailing the annual
statement would add to government spending. But it would be
minimized by including it with the other tax forms, he said.
</TEXT>
