<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Angola     03-15 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Angola,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa Frees 12 Angolan Soldiers In Return For Two Bodies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK REYNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUANDA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South African military plane landed
Tuesday in Luanda and released 12 Angolan soldiers in exchange for
the bodies of two South African corporals killed in northern Angola
in 1985, Angolan officials said.
   They also said U.S. envoy Chester Crocker was expected to arrive
in this Angolan capital by Wednesday for talks with Angolan leaders
following his meetings in Geneva on a southern African peace
settlement with South African Foreign Minister Roelof F. Botha.
   The officials, who spoke on condition of not being identified,
said Tuesday's exchange took place at Luanda Airport. They said 12
Angolan soldiers were freed. The South African military said 12
captured Angolans were freed, but refused to say if they were
soldiers or civilians.
   South Africa identified the two dead soldiers as Cpls. Rowland
Liebenberg and Louis Van Breda, both 25. Angola said they were
killed in Cabinda province May 21, 1985, when Angolan troops
surprised their commando unit outside an oil depot.
   The unit leader, Maj. Wynard Du Toit, was captured. He said the
commandos were sent to blow up the depot belonging to Cabinda Gulf
Oil, a subsidiary of the U.S. oil company Chevron.
   Du Toit was exchanged last September for 133 Angolan soldiers
reportedly captured by the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola, the South African-backed rebel movement
known as UNITA.
   The Tuesday exchange appeared to be a further step in intense
diplomatic efforts to reach a settlement in Marxist Angola's
13-year conflict. UNITA, which also is supported by the United
States, is fighting to force the Cuban- and Soviet-backed
government to share power.
   The talks Monday between Crocker, assistant secretary of state
for African affairs, and Botha focused on efforts for an agreement
on withdrawal of an estimated 40,000 Cuban soldiers stationed in
Angola.
   Crocker is trying to negotiate a withdrawal of the Cubans in
return for South African withdrawal from neighboring South-West
Africa, also known as Namibia. South Africa administers Namibia
under a post-World War I mandate from the defunct League of Nations
and has rejected United Nations's resolutions demanding that the
territory be independent.
   South Africa recently acknowledged having troops in southern
Angola, but said they were in the process of withdrawing.
   However, President P.W. Botha of South Africa was quoted in the
Washington Times newspaper Monday as saying South African troops
would not leave Angola unless Cuban troops also left.
   Angola says it will send the Cubans home only when South Africa
pulls its troops out of southern Angola, America halts aid for
UNITA and an independence settlement is reached for Namibia.
   President Jose Eduardo dos Santos of Angola says 9,000 South
African soldiers are in southern Angola.
   UNITA said Tuesday in a statement distributed in Lisbon,
Portugal, that its guerrillas captured the town of Kiwaba-N'zogi in
northern Malange province, killing 12 soldiers and seizing arms.
   It said guerrillas attacked the town 42 miles north of the
provincial capital of Malange on Sunday.
   The rebels said they also captured three Angolan soldiers and
destroyed five trucks in an attack Saturday on a military convoy in
Malange province. They claimed to have killed 10 Angolan soldiers
in an attack on an army post at Elola in southwestern Huila
province, but did not say when.
   UNITA gave rebel casualties in the clashes as three killed and
eight wounded. There was no independent confirmation of the claims.
   In Brussels, Belgian professor Aubin Heyndrickx, a specialist in
toxicology, claimed that Cuban troops were using chemical weapons
in Angola.
   Heyndrickx visited southeast Angola three weeks ago at the
invitation of Jonas Savimbi, leader of UNITA, and examined eight
UNITA soldiers in a field hospital in the Mavinga area.
   He said in stories published Tuesday that examinations showed
the soldiers were victims of toxic gas and further laboratory
checks made later in Ghent confirmed that diagnosis.
</TEXT>
