<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Photographer     03-15 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Photographer,0637</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Photographer Charged With Stoning Israeli Troops</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Israel Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American photographer has been accused by
the army of throwing stones at Israeli soldiers during a violent
Palestinian protest in the occupied West Bank.
   The army on Tuesday identified the photographer as William
Biggart, and Israel radio said he had been on assignment for the
Village Voice, a weekly newspaper published in New York City.
Biggart and the newspaper denied the army allegations.
   Biggart was detained last week during a Palestinian riot in
Nablus, the West Bank's largest Arab town, the army said. A
spokesman said the photographer was wearing a traditional checkered
Arab headdress and was seen throwing stones at soldiers.
   The army filed a complaint with Nablus police, the spokesman
said, refusing to let his name be used because of military
regulations.
   Martin Gottlieb, editor of the Village Voice, said in New York
that Biggart apparently went to the West Bank to see if he could
take pictures to sell to other news organizations.
   ``He's a free-lance photographer on assignment from us to take
some very routine head-and-shoulder shots and real estate pictures
of the Knesset (the Israeli Parliament),'' Gottlieb said.
   ``He adamantly denies the charges. Our position here is one of
outrage. We think that although he wasn't specifically working for
us on the West Bank, we would have been anxious to see the photos
he took.''
   Gottlieb quoted the photographer as saying: ``It's ridiculous.
I'm 40 years old. I have three kids. I didn't come to Israel to
thrown stones.''
   ``We think he did absolutely nothing wrong and one can only
wonder why Israeli soldiers would concoct charges against this man
at a time when every effort is being made to keep the area closed
to the press,'' Gottlieb said. ``The democratic freedom of the
press seem to be under a severe attack in Israel.''
   He said the paper would lodge a protest with the Israeli
consulate in New York.
   Israel radio said soldiers confiscated Biggart's U.S. passport
and Israeli-issued press card but a senior officer ordered the
passport returned. It said Biggart described himself as a staff
photographer for the Village Voice.
   Biggart had applied twice for an Israeli Government Press Office
card, once with a beard and the second time clean-shaven, the radio
said, and quoted the photographer as saying he ``did not want to
look like a Jewish settler.''
   It said a policeman went to the American Colony Hotel in east
Jerusalem, where Biggert was staying, last Saturday and presented a
summons for a court appearance the next day but Biggart left the
country Sunday.
   A senior official at the U.S. consulate said Biggart was in
touch with a duty officer Saturday night and ``said that he was
summoned to court and that he was due to leave on Sunday. The
officer said he can't give a legal advice.''
   Gottlieb said Biggart gave this description of events:
   On March 7, he was on a street in the Balata Refugee camp when
Israeli soldiers began lobbing tear gas grenades. The soldiers
later charged into the street.
   ``Like everybody else on the street, I began to run. I slipped.
I was the only one who didn't get away.''
   After an Israeli soldier struck him on the legs and ripped the
film out of his camera, an officer took him to a military post and
accused him of throwing rocks.
   His passport was returned but the soldiers kept the press card.
He was presented with a document, written in Hebrew, by a police
officer who spoke only Arabic.
   He left Israel on Sunday after a U.S. consulate official told
him he could leave the country but might have trouble returning.
</TEXT>
