<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Biaggi-Wedtech     03-15 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0615</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Prosecution Witness Takes Stand Against Biaggi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From 1975 on, Wedtech Corp. deceived federal
agencies into believing it was a minority-controlled business that
qualified for no-bid government contracts, a former company
executive testified Tuesday at the racketeering trial of Rep. Mario
Biaggi.
   Mario Moreno, one of four ex-Wedtech officials who have pleaded
guilty to bribery and other state and federal charges, was the
first prosecution witness to testify at the trial of Biaggi and six
co-defendants.
   Biaggi, a 10-term Bronx Democrat; his eldest son; his former law
partner; and four others are charged with turning Wedtech into a
racketeering enterprise that paid millions of dollars in bribes to
win government contracts. Since the allegations became public, the
company has filed for protection under bankruptcy laws and
suspended most operations.
   Moreno, who is cooperating with the government in return for
leniency, also described Biaggi's lobbying efforts on Wedtech's
behalf in 1980 when the company was trying to win an Army contract
to build small engines.
   Prosecutors have charged that Wedtech grew from a small Bronx
machine shop into a $100 million-a-year government contractor, in
part, by falsely portraying itself as minority-controlled, in order
to qualify for a Small Business Administration program that gave
out government contracts without competitive bidding.
   Moreno said he met Wedtech co-founders John Mariotta and Fred
Neuberger in 1976 when he served as consultant for a local program
that assisted small minority-owned businesses.
   Moreno said the pair later told him that Mariotta, who is of
Hispanic descent, owned two-thirds of Wedtech, then known as
Welbilt Electronics Die Corp., and Neuberger owned the other third.
   Mariotta is one of those on trial with Biaggi. Neuberger is one
of the four ex-Wedtech officials cooperating with prosecutors after
pleading guilty to state and federal charges.
   In 1979, Moreno testified, Mariotta and Neuberger ``told me they
each owned 50 percent of the company'' and that they had a
``handshake agreement'' dating back to 1975.
   But the pair did not reveal that Mariotta no longer controlled
the company in records presented to the Small Business
Administration ``in order to comply with the ... regulations,''
Moreno said.
   The witness also said that in 1979, the company had gross
revenues of $1.5 million and about 60 employees but by the
following year ``the company was going bankrupt any minute''
because of a scarcity of funds.
   Moreno said Wedtech was in line to get more than $4 million in
loans through the federal Economic Development Administration in
January 1980, but the loan approval was bottlenecked by an
overworked EDA official in Philadelphia.
   ``We looked for assistance from several people,'' said Moreno,
adding that it came from Biaggi's former law partner and current
co-defendant, Bernard Ehrlich, who took Moreno and Mariotta to seek
the congressman.
   Biaggi turned the matter over to an aide who knew the
Philadelphia EDA official's boss and a month later Wedtech had the
loans approved, said Moreno.
   Wedtech also tried to win an Army contract through the minority
business program. The contract was for small, gasoline-powered
engines even though Wedtech had neither the experience or
facilities to build the engines.
   When the Army turned down Wedtech's first proposal as too high,
company officials again went to Biaggi and Ehrlich for help, said
Moreno.
   Biaggi enlisted the help of Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., and
the late Rep. Joseph Addabbo, a powerful Queens Democrat, who wrote
the secretary of the Army on behalf of Wedtech, which eventually
got the contract.
   Moreno was scheduled to returned to the stand Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880315-0205 </DOCNO>
