<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Iran     03-15 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Iran,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Blames Security Council, America for `War of Cities'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran lashed out at the Security Council
again Tuesday, accusing it of wasting time on an arms embargo
proposal instead of ending the deadly missile duel between Tehran
and Baghdad.
   ``The Security Council is responsible for every drop of blood of
Iranian people, innocent civilians who are the victims of inhuman
attacks,'' said Iran's U.N. envoy, Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati.
   Mahallati spoke at a news conference after delivering a protest
to Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar that accused the
council of taking no action to stop the surface-to-surface missile
attacks on the Iranian and Iraqi capitals known as the ``war of the
cities.''
   The most recent phase of the duel began in late February. After
a two day halt, it started again Monday. Iran and Iraq both claim
hundreds of civilian casualties.
   Mahallati blamed the United States for encouraging the attacks
on cities by pushing for a worldwide arms embargo against Iran.
   The embargo would punish Iran for failing to honor the council's
July 20 resolution demanding a cease-fire and withdrawal to pre-war
boundaries as the first step in a negotiated end to the 7{-year-old
Iran-Iraq war.
   Mahallati told reporters that questions about Iran's position on
the resolution are ``outdated questions.'' Instead, he said, the
council should condemn Iraq for starting the latest round in the
``war of the cities'' and take action to stop the attacks.
   He also accused Iraq of using chemical weapons and intensifying
attacks on neutral shipping in the Persian Gulf.
   Mahallati would not say precisely what Iran wants the council to
do other than condemn Iraq and stop talking about an embargo.
   Iraq blames Iran for starting the missile duel that has killed
scores of civilians since Feb. 29. Both sides describe their
attacks as retaliatory and defensive.
   The United States increased its pressure for an embargo after
Perez de Cuellar ended months of negotiations late last year
proclaiming frustration at Iran's recalcitrance.
   The Soviet Union, which wants better relations with neighboring
Iran, has not agreed to support an embargo. Last week the Soviets
called for more negotiations and a new Security Council resolution
dealing only with the attacks on cities.
   The Soviets acknowledged Monday that they had failed to win
council support for that plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
