<DOCNO> AP880315-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 2155EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0728 03-15 0822</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0728,0841</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`War Of Cities' Continues, Scores Of Civilian Casualties Reported</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs to UPDATE with Iran criticizing U.N.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran and Iraq blasted each other's cities
Tuesday with missiles, bombs and artillery in apparent attempts to
terrorize each other into submission in a new ``war of the cities.''
   Communiques from both sides, monitored in Nicosia, reported
scores of civilians killed or wounded in the third straight day of
new attacks on population centers.
   ``We are determined to turn Tehran into a hell, the like of
which the barbaric scoundrels have never seen before,'' said the
Iraqi News Agency following another barrage of missiles into Tehran.
   Persian Gulf shipping executives said Iraqi warplanes attacked a
Liberian-flag tanker, chartered by Iran, off the Iranian coast.
   They had no details on casualties or damage aboard the
249,223-ton Trade Fortitude, the second ship damaged in Iraqi raids
in the gulf since March 8.
   Iraq, which has long held the technological edge in the deadly
duel, said it fired six long-range missiles Tuesday into Tehran,
the Iranian capital, while its air force bombed seven cities in
western Iran.
   Iran said it bombarded the southern Iraqi port city of Basra and
Nashwa, 12 miles to the north, with 11 short-range missiles and
artillery fire and hit four other cities in the northeast and
southeast with air raids.
   The Iranians reported no long-range missile attacks on Baghdad,
the Iraqi capital, or any other cities.
   The absence of any missile attack on Baghdad prompted
speculation that the Iranians may have exhausted their arsenal of
long-range missiles in an exchange with the Iraqis that began Feb.
29 and ended for two days last Friday.
   So far, the Iraqis have reported shooting 86 long-range missiles
into Tehran and other Iranian cities in the last 16 days. In
contrast, Iran has claimed to have fired 31 in that period.
   In the gulf, the Kuwaiti tanker Gas Prince, one of 11 Kuwait
tankers reflagged with the Stars and Stripes to afford them U.S.
Navy protection from Iranian attack, sailed northward in the 17th
convoy operation this year.
   The convoy was the 39th since July, when the Navy began
escorting the Kuwaiti tankers.
   In Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, foreign ministers of six conservative
Gulf Arab states met to discuss the Iran-Iraq war.
   Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency said a number of civilians
were killed in missile attacks on residential areas of the capital,
but did not say how many rockets hit the city of 6 million.
   Iraq also reported civilian casualties in several cities, but
gave no figures beyond nine killed and 20 wounded in Basra.
   AP reporter Salah Nasrawi reported from Basra on Tuesday that
the city was rocked throughout the day by exploding artillery
shells and Soviet-made Katyusha rockets fired by Iranian forces
east of the city.
   Iranian Revolutionary Guards battled to within six miles of the
city a year ago in a major offensive and have held onto their
bridgehead despite Iraqi counter-attacks.
   Basra's governor, Anwar al-Hadithi, said that more than 2,900
shells and nearly 200 rockets have hit the city since Feb. 28,
killing 50 civilians and wounding around 250 others.
   ``The Katyushas are the worst,'' al-Hadithi said. ``The Iranians
use truck-mounted launchers which means they can fire and run
before our people can locate them. The shrapnel bursts from the
rockets is worse than the shells and they kill more people.''
   Basra was once Iraq's second largest city. But its pre-war
population of 1 million has dwindled to around 300,000 in the last
two years as people fled the Iranian bombardment.
   Western military analysts believe Baghdad, which began hitting
Tehran with missiles for the first time Feb. 29, wants to provoke
Iran into retaliation that will intensify pressure on the U.N.
Security Council to impose an arms embargo on Iran.
   Western diplomats believe the Iraqi strategy is ill-advised
because it has provided the Soviet Union with an excuse to stall on
swinging behind U.S. efforts to secure the embargo.
   Moscow is Iraq's main arms supplier, but has been at pains in
the last two years to improve its relations with Tehran in an
apparent effort to mediate a cease-fire in the war.
   In New York, the Soviets' U.N. ambassador, Alexander Belonogov,
acknowledged Monday that the Soviet bid for a resolution calling
for an end to the ``war of the cities'' had failed. The United
States saw the proposal as a maneuver designed to deflect attention
from the American drive for the embargo on Iran.
   And Iran's U.N. envoy lashed out at the Security Council,
accusing it of ``wasting'' time on the arms embargo proposal
instead of ending the missile duel between Tehran and Baghdad.
   ``The Security Council is responsible for every drop of blood of
Iranian people, innocent civilians who are the victims of inhuman
attacks,'' said the envoy, Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati.
</TEXT>
