<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Meese-Pipeline 1stLd-Writethru a0743 03-15 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Pipeline, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0743,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former NSC Staffer Testifies In Meese Pipeline Probe</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Adds 3 grafs with appearance by a Pentagon lawyer</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former National Security Council staff aide
Roger W. Robinson made a 2{-hour federal grand jury appearance
Tuesday in the criminal investigation of Attorney General Edwin
Meese III and a proposed $1 billion Iraqi oil pipeline.
   Robinson declined to discuss his testimony following his
appearance. He was the aide designated by then-national security
adviser Robert McFarlane in June 1985 to work on expediting the
pipeline, which was floundering for lack of an insurance package
sought by Iraq to insure it from Israeli attack.
   Robinson was assigned to get the project back on track following
a meeting by McFarlane, longtime Meese friend E. Robert Wallach and
Wallach's client Swiss oilman Bruce Rappaport, a partner in the
proposed pipeline. Meese had referred Wallach to McFarlane the
previous month.
   Working with Wallach, Robinson tried unsuccessfully to help
assemble a $400 million bank-backed insurance package acceptable to
the Overseas Private Investment Corp.
   The government agency insures foreign investments by U.S. firms
such as Bechtel Group Inc., which was going to build the project.
OPIC officials wanted guarantees that funds would be available from
some source to cover losses if the pipeline were destroyed.
   Robinson is the second NSC aide in two weeks to testify in the
probe of Meese being conducted by independent counsel James McKay.
The other was David Wigg, who took Robinson's place on the project.
   Two former aides in Meese's office, John Richardson and John
Harrison, testified last week before the grand jury to which
McKay's office is presenting evidence. Richardson was Meese's chief
of staff before leaving the Justice Department several months ago.
Harrison, now with the solicitor general's office, worked on
Meese's staff in mid-1985.
   The probe of Meese revolves around whether he may have violated
the 1977 Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, which prohibits bribes by
U.S. companies or their agents to foreign officials.
   Wallach wrote a memo to the attorney general in September 1985
saying that a portion of up to $700 million from the pipeline would
be paid to the Israeli Labor Party of then-Prime Minister Shimon
Peres. Meese says he doesn't recall reading the portion of the memo
relating to Labor Party payments.
   Robinson left the NSC on Sept. 14, 1985, and his place on the
pipeline project was taken by Wigg, who worked with Wallach on
alternative proposals. Those included pledging U.S. aid to Israel
as a guarantee for the pipeline and seeking to put Pentagon budget
money for Israel in an overseas escrow account as insurance.
   None of the insurance proposals was adopted and the pipeline
wasn't built.
   On Tuesday afternoon, John H. McNeill of the Pentagon office of
general counsel appeared before the grand jury.
   McNeill worked with Wigg on the Pentagon budget proposal,
according to sources familiar with McKay's probe, speaking on
condition of anonymity. McNeill, who declined comment on his
testimony, is the assistant general counsel for international and
intelligence matters.
   McNeill and Robinson are both witnesses in the probe rather than
subjects or targets and do not have legal counsel.
</TEXT>
