<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-PlaneCrash     03-15 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Plane Crash,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commission Blames Pilots for Fatal Plane Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of a Soviet jetliner that crashed
killing 11 passengers allowed his co-pilot to try a difficult night
landing for which he was not prepared, a government commission said
Tuesday.
   The government newspaper Izvestia published the findings of a
commission that studied the crash of an Aeroflot Tu-154B at the
Caspian Sea port of Krasnovodsk on Jan. 18.
   It said prosecutors have started criminal proceedings in the
case.
   The three-engine jet, carrying 137 passengers from Moscow to
Krasnovodsk and then on to Ashkabad was flying normally until the
approach to Krasnovodsk in the early morning hours, the report said.
   Pilot V.S. Churayev permitted co-pilot V.D. Yegorov to land the
plan, even though Yegorov was not trained sufficiently for landing
in the difficult conditions at Krasnovodsk, according to the report.
   The report did not say why the landing in Krasnovodsk was
difficult.
   It said Yegorov made mistakes in his approach that brought the
plane down too rapidly from a height of 150 feet and even though
Churayev took over the controls at the last minute, the plane
flipped over on landing and broke in two.
   It was one of three times this year that passengers were killed
in Aeroflot flight crashes reported by the Soviet media.
   On Feb. 27 a Tupolev 134 crashed at the Siberian city of Sumgut.
The media said there were casualties, but did not say how many.
   On March 8, a family musical group from Irkutsk tried to hijack
a Tupolev 154 bound for Leningrad. A stewardess, three passengers
and five of the hijackers were killed before the plane was retaken
by security officers.
</TEXT>
