<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Weld-Drugs     03-15 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weld-Drugs,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Early Federal Strategy Would Have Singled Out Biggest Drug Rings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Justice Department's criminal
division said Tuesday that an early draft of a federal prosecution
strategy against drugs would have targeted resources almost
exclusively at the world's 150 biggest narcotics rings.
   Assistant Attorney General William Weld said the approach has
been broadened after extensive discussions with U.S. attorneys so
that smaller operations will be targeted in federal drug
prosecutions.
   ``I want that dealer in Lowell, Mass., not to be sure he won't
be picked up in a federal undercover operation,'' Weld, a former
U.S. attorney in Boston, said in an interview. ``I don't want
people to be able to relax anywhere.''
   Weld said that when he first considered focusing exclusively on
the largest drug rings, ``I ran into a little bit of a buzz saw''
from some U.S. attorneys.
   Committing ``an untoward percentage of those resources to Miami,
New York, Chicago'' and the other major drug centers ``creates the
public perception of gaps in enforcement,'' said Weld. ``The bad
guys are going to play hit 'em where they ain't.''
   ``If we were going to be entirely logical we might say the only
purpose of prosecution is to disrupt the supply'' by aiming ``at
the top-most levels of supply in the world,'' Weld said. Abandoning
regions of the country would send a mixed signal that ``it's not OK
to be a member of the Medillin cartel, but it is OK to be a little
fish.''
   Of the refinements, he said: ``Frankly, I'm happier with the
compromise than I was with my own first draft.''
   The prosecution strategy is one proposed piece of the federal
drug-fighting effort now being mapped out by a number of agencies.
The proposals, now in final form, will be presented to the National
Drug Policy Board for approval and will be publicly announced by
early next month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
