<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-PLO     03-15 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-PLO,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Assembly Prepares to Meet Friday on PLO Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 159-nation General Assembly is
expected to ask the World Court to rule on whether the United
States can close the PLO's U.N. observer mission in New York, an
Arab League spokesman said Tuesday.
   League spokesman Clovis Maksoud and U.N. sources said the
assembly would convene Friday.
   The U.S. Justice Department has said it would move on or around
Monday to enforce a new anti-terrorism law calling for the closure
of the Palestine Liberation Organization's mission office.
   Maksoud said the League will ask the assembly to take a cautious
approach.
   He said it will not ask the assembly to suspend Israel from
debates on the Middle East, as the PLO has suggested, or to move to
another country. Both would be premature, he said.
   ``The provocation was reckless. We don't want to respond with
recklessness,'' Maksoud said in an interview.
   Scores of nations said during a special session earlier this
month on the PLO dispute that the independence of the United
Nations is at stake.
   The increasingly bitter confrontation has prompted some calls to
move the world body to Geneva, which Western diplomats say is
unlikely.
   ``Nobody wants to move the headquarters,'' Maksoud said.
   U.N. sources said Tuesday that preliminary studies show the cost
of moving the assembly to Geneva would be ``excessive,'' in part
because U.N. facilities there are not adequate.
   Both the United Nations and the U.S. State Department have said
closing the PLO mission would violate the 1947 treaty under which
the United States became U.N. headquarters.
   Maksoud said the Arab League will not ask the United Nations to
go to federal court to fight the Justice Department.
   He said the United Nations should not subject itself to the
jurisdiction of a domestic court.
   Instead, the League will ask the assembly to request a ruling
from the World Court in the Hague on whether the United States has
the right to close down any mission to the United Nations.
   The PLO, an official observer at the General Assembly since
1974, has said it will apppear in a U.S. court only if ``dragged
in,'' and then only to challenge the court's jurisdiction over a
U.N. matter.
</TEXT>
