<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF-Britain-Lord     03-15 0156</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF-Britain-Lord,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bookcases Help With Castle Debts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lord Hugh Rupert Courtenay sold his bookshelves
and got to keep them, too, on Tuesday, for a record-setting
$841,750.
   London's Victoria and Albert Museum bought the two antique
bookcases but agreed to let Courtenay keep them so long as they are
on show to the public in his library.
   The museum said the price was a record for a piece of English
furniture sold in Britain.
   The bookcases will stay in Courtenay's ancestral home, Powderham
Castle, Devon, which Courtenay runs for his father, the 17th Earl
of Devon.
   The bookcases were made in 1740 by John Channon of Exeter. The
museum was given the money by the National Heritage Fund, a charity
which preserves historic objects for the nation.
   Courtenay, 46, said he loses $74,000 a year on the castle and
needs more than $1.85 million to pay taxes and fund improvements in
the castle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
