<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SpacenetSatellite     03-15 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spacenet Satellite,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GTE Satellite Reaches Geosynchronous Orbit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American communications satellite launched
into a low orbit last week rocketed successfully Tuesday into a
geosynchronous orbit 22,300 miles above the Earth's equator.
   The satellite, Spacenet III, owned by GTE Corp., fired its
apogee kick motor, a small rocket engine, at 11:57 a.m. EST, some
90 hours after its launch Friday night by a French Ariane rocket.
   GTE officials said the 1,562-pound Spacenet III would initiate a
stabilizing spin Tuesday night. This will lock its antennae into
contact with Earth. Once that is accomplished and verified, the
satellite will deploy an array of solar power cells that provide
the craft with electricity.
   GTE engineers will conduct a series of tests of the craft and
the the satellite will start operations early in April.
   Spacenet III provides a communications link between points in
all 50 of the United States. Clients include The Associated Press
and the television groups of ABC, CBS, CNN and Gannett.
   The U.S. satellite and a French communications satellite were
launched together on Friday aboard an Ariane rocket from the
European Space Agency launch site in Kourou, French Guiana. GTE
Spacenet is the first American client of Arianespace, the operating
arm of the European Space Agency.
</TEXT>
