<1ST_LINE>u w AM-AIDSTesting 3rdLd-Writethru a0848 03-15 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Testing, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0848,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal AIDS Testing May Be Breaking California Law</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts lede, INSERTS new 5th graf to reflect that some
routine AIDS tests legal in California.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All blood samples taken for routine clinical
testing at 40 hospitals in 30 states now are also being tested for
AIDS, the director of Centers for Disease Control said Tuesday.
   Dr. James Mason, director of the CDC, said at a congressional
hearing that ``blinded'' blood tests are being conducted at the
hospitals in an effort to help determine the incidence of AIDS, or
acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   Rep. William E. Dannemeyer, R-Calif., a member of the House
Energy and Commerce subcommittee on health and the environment,
asked Mason if he was aware that California has a law that forbids
AIDS testing without consent.
   ``Then I sure am committing lots of crimes every day,'' said
Mason.
   An official with the California state committee on AIDS such
certain ``blinded'' tests are legal.
   Mason said the tests were under way in hospitals in both San
Francisco and Los Angeles.
   Mason said results of the testing are now being compiled and
will be released to the public in two to three weeks.
   In the ``blinded'' tests, said Mason, a portion of each routine
blood sample taken at the hospitals is separated out and then
tested for AIDS. He said the blood used for the AIDS testing
carries no identification of the patient who provided the sample,
hence the identity of the donor is ``blinded'' to the laboratory
conducting the tests.
   Debra Smith, administrative secretary to a California state
committee on AIDS, said the ``blinded'' tests are legal. She said a
statute passed in 1987 permits such tests for statistical purposes.
   Mason's statement came during hearings chaired by Rep. Henry A.
Waxman, D-Calif., into the way that the nation's AIDS research
dollars are being spent.
   Mason, along with Dr. Frank Young, commissioner of the Food and
Drug Administration, and Dr. James Wyngaarden, director of the
National Institutes of Health, all said they were experiencing
difficulty in hiring scientists and other health care professionals
because the federal salaries are below those offered in
universities or in industry.
   Wyngaarden said that the turnover among investigators is about 2
percent a year.
   ``We're losing some of our most outstanding people,'' he said,
for reasons that involved salary, laboratory facilities and other
``complex'' reasons.
   He said this is particularly true of allied health workers, such
as nurses, laboratory technicians and X-ray technicians. He said
there is a salary differential among those workers of about 25
percent.
   ``They will stay through the training period and then leave for
more money,'' said Wyngaarden.
   Dr. Tony Fauci, deputy director for AIDS research at NIH, said
top investigators frequently receive offers to move to university
or industry positions that offer a higher salary, better facilities
and more laboratory personnel.
   ``There is a rather significant difference in salaries (between
federal and private),'' he said. ``We are constantly fighting that
battle.''
   Fauci said the outpatient clinic at the NIH treated 4,500 AIDs
patients during 1987 and that more and more of them are becoming
critically ill and in need of intensive care.
   ``The staff problems will have a negative impact'' on the amount
of care available at the clinics, he said.
   Young said his agency is experiencing difficulty in recruiting
personnel trained to evaluate drugs and medical issues. He said it
typically takes about two years to train personnel, and they often
leave the FDA shortly after the training is completed in order to
receive higher pay elsewhere.
</TEXT>
