<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dole-DoorDie 1stLd-Writethru a0657 03-15 0909</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole-Do or Die, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0657,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Needs a Victory But None Is in Sight</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT new 6th graf with Dole comment bgng ``When Dole...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frustrated, angry and unwilling to admit defeat,
Bob Dole insisted there was a turning point out there, a state
where voters would say, ``Wait a minute, we don't want George
Bush.'' But Dole's campaign was hard-pressed to identify that
turnaround state.
   It wasn't likely to happen in Connecticut, one of the states
Bush calls home. And the Republican presidential polls don't look
promising for Dole in Wisconsin, New York or Pennsylvania.
   ``So that takes us another month and a half without a big
opportunity for a victory,'' said one top Dole adviser, insisting
on anonymity.
   Before the polls opened Tuesday in Illinois, Dole conceded that
big state to Bush.
   With Bush continuing to build his delegate lead, Dole was dogged
by the question of how long he could or would stay in the race.
   When Dole returned to Washington Tuesday night, he insisted,
``We're just going to hang in there. ... We're staying in, we're
staying in.''
   Was there a realistic chance of catching the vice president?
   The numbers suggested there wasn't.
   Going into the Illinois primary, Bush already had 705 of the
1,139 delegates needed for the nomination. Dole had 165.
   Bush would need only one-third of the 1,318 delegates still to
be chosen.
   Obviously, if Dole started winning two-thirds of the delegates
in upcoming contests, the vice president's huge lead would
evaporate. But there was no sign of that happening.
   The Iran-Contra affair appeared to offer a bit of hope to Dole.
   When Robert McFarlane agreed to cooperate with the special
counsel investigating the affair, it renewed the hope within the
Dole campaign that attention once again would focus on what role
Bush had in deliberations that led to the sale of arms to Iran and
diversion of funds to the Contras.
   In a speech to the Chicago Council on Foreign Relations, Dole
referred to presidential advisers ``peddling arms to the ayatollah
while others hear no evil, see no evil.''
   But he later conceded that Iran-Contra was not an issue among
Republicans, though he predicted it would be used against the
party's nominee by the Democrats.
   Dole's frustration was apparent when he was asked why he didn't
attack Bush more directly on Iran-Contra.
   ``If I hit him, I get Ronald Reagan first and then they say, oh,
oh, he's out there attacking Ronald Reagan,'' he replied.
   Nothing so frustrates and angers Dole as Bush's success in tying
himself to Reagan, a president who remains enormously popular among
Republicans.
   Dole referred to Bush commercials that show the vice president
conferring with Reagan and, in one scene, the president putting an
arm over Bush's shoulders.
   ``I don't have nearly as many pictures of Ronald Reagan as
George Bush has,'' said Dole. ``He must have a pile six feet deep.
I can't match him in photos. But I can match him in record.''
   Bush blew the Republican race open with his sweeping victory on
Super Tuesday.
   But Dole is reluctant to give the vice president credit for
accomplishing anything on his own. ``Super Tuesday was, in my view,
a referendum on Ronald Reagan and Reagan won,'' said the senator.
   He sees Bush as someone who has ``sort of had a charmed life in
politics. He's gotten quite a ways without ever doing much.''
   That view may contribute to Dole's belief that it could all
unravel for Bush if he can ``get people to stop and think.''
   The senator admitted he has considered various tactics that
might blunt the Bush momentum, including borrowing one from Ronald
Reagan _ naming his running mate. Reagan tried that in 1976 when he
challenged incumbent Republican President Ford.
   Reagan, fighting to overcome a perception that he was too
conservative, said early in the race he would name moderate
Republican Sen. Richard Schweicker of Pennsylvania as his running
mate.
   It didn't work for Reagan, but as Dole said, ``When you're
looking for ways to catch up, you think of maybe naming your
running mate.'' One of the names on Dole's list was former Gov.
Lamar Alexander of Tennessee. He said there were others, but he
didn't name them.
   On election day in Illinois, Dole campaigned in Wisconsin and
Connecticut.
   But Connecticut, with 35 delegates, is the state where Bush grew
up and where his father served as a senator. Connecticut didn't
look like a good state for Dole, said the senator's adviser.
   Polls in Wisconsin, which chooses 47 delegates in a primary on
April 5, gave Bush a big lead. Only a Dole victory in Illinois
seemed likely to turn it around.
   The biggest upcoming prize is New York, which elects 102 GOP
delegates on April 19. Bush has already been credited with 24 of
those because his backers are running unopposed in several
districts.
   A week later, Pennsylvania, with 78 delegates, votes, and the
Dole adviser described the state as ``controlled pretty tightly''
by Bush.
   Even while claiming he was going to fight on, Dole showed
glimpses of the political realist.
   He referred to candidates who don't realize when it's time to
bow out.
   He said, ``Now if you're out there and you've been twisting in
the wind for six or eight months and you're starting to smell a
little, maybe somebody has to cut the rope.''
</TEXT>
