<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DestroyerSlaying 2ndLd-Writethru a0746 03-15 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Destroyer Slaying, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0746,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USS Hancock Paymaster Killed; $120,000 Stolen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with officials now saying man
also strangled, giving victim's name, hometown; no one else
believed missing from the ship. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `A
search...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT NAVAL STATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Naval paymaster was found
beaten and strangled Tuesday aboard the destroyer USS John Hancock
and $120,000 was stolen from the ship's safe, a naval spokesman
said.
   The officer's body was found stuffed into a sea locker in
another part of the ship, said Chief Petty Officer Art Riccio. ``He
was beaten up pretty bad.'' Later, officials said the victim,
identified as for Lt. Ratish Prasad, 24, of Park Forest, Ill., also
had been strangled.
   The search for Prasad began when he failed to report to muster
at 7:15 a.m., said Riccio. Mayport Petty Officer Billy Hill said
Tuesday evening that nobody else was known to be missing from the
ship.
   A search of the disbursement office found the safe open and
$120,000 in cash and an undetermined number of blank checks
missing, Riccio said.
   Tuesday was payday for Navy personnel, who are paid the first
and 15th of each month, said Riccio. ``An audit of the ship's funds
is pending and alternate arrangements have been made to pay the
crew,'' he said.
   Navy and Jacksonville sheriff's investigators were working on
the case, he said.
   Mayport is the Hancock's home port. Access to the ship, which
was tied in the port, is strictly controlled, said Riccio. Anyone
wanting to board must pass checkpoints at the base entrance, the
pier area and the ship itself.
   Only relatives and friends of the crew who have been previously
cleared are allowed aboard the ship in port, he said. Even Navy
personnel who do not have business on the ships cannot board, he
said.
   Construction workers doing repairs can go aboard, but Riccio
said the Hancock had no repair work scheduled.
   The Navy refuses to comment on whether nuclear weapons are
aboard a vessel, but destroyers do not ususally carry such arms.
</TEXT>
