<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 2154EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ExitPolls     03-15 0692</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Exit Polls,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Home-State Loyalty Boosts Simon in Illinois</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Primary Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Paul Simon cashed in on home-state
loyalties in the Illinois Democratic presidential primary and won
support even from voters who doubt he can win the nomination or the
presidency, exit polls said Tuesday.
   Jesse Jackson, another Illinois resident, again won overwhelming
support from black voters, and increased his share of the white
vote to about 8 percent, three percentage points better than he did
in Illinois in 1984, polls said.
   ``The way I'm looking at the numbers, hometown boys do good,''
said Doug Muzzio, an ABC News poll analyst.
   Among Republicans, Vice President George Bush defeated Sen. Bob
Dole among virtually all ideological and demographic groups. Dole
kept pace with Bush only among independents who voted in the GOP
primary.
   Bush once again defeated former television evangelist Pat
Robertson even among his most likely supporters, born-again
Christians and those concerned with moral values, ABC, NBC News and
CBS News-New York Times polls said.
   Overwhelmingly, supporters of Jackson and of Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis said their candidate had the best chance to win in
November, ABC said. But only 40 percent of Simon's supporters gave
him the best chance, and 35 percent named Dukakis even though they
voted for Simon.
   ``Simon's voters don't think he has the best chance in November
but they're voting for him anyway,'' said Muzzio. ``His vote seems
to be a home-state favorite vote.''
   Similarly, NBC News found that 80 percent of Dukakis' supporters
and 60 percent of Jackson's thought their man would win the
nomination, while only 35 percent of Simon's voters thought he
would be nominated. More Simon voters _ 39 percent _ thought
Dukakis eventually would win the nomination.
   ``Simon is a true favorite-son type candidate,'' said Sheldon
Gawiser, an NBC poll analyst. ``He has a 67 percent favorable
opinion rating. They think he's doing a good job as senator.''
   Though Dukakis finished third in the voting, ABC said a
plurality of Democrats, 35 percent, thought he was the Democrat
most likely to win the general election in November. Next was
Jackson with 27 percent; Simon had 18 percent and 12 percent
selected Gov. Mario Cuomo of New York, who is not a candidate but
has refused to rule out a convention draft.
   About a quarter of the electorate was black, and Jackson won 91
percent of the black vote, 20 points better than in 1984, ABC said.
   Jackson improved his showing among whites, but less so, winning
8 percent compared to 5 percent in 1984, Muzzio said. The racial
division was so dramatic, said Gawiser, ``There are two
electorates: black and white.''
   The groups had somewhat different concerns. The CBS News-New
York Times poll found that 53 percent of blacks cited unemployment
as one of their two greatest concerns and 45 percent cited poverty.
Unemployment also led among white concerns, at 39 percent;
protecting Social Security was second, cited by 29 percent.
   In the Republican vote, the CBS-Times poll said 70 percent of
the voters had selected their candidate before Super Tuesday, when
Bush won 16 of 17 states. The polls again indicated that good will
toward President Reagan had translated into support for the vice
president.
   NBC said 27 percent of the Republican voters said they were
born-again Protestants, and 54 percent voted for Bush, to 27
percent for Dole and 17 percent for Robertson. ABC said 17 percent
were white born-again Christians; Bush got 37 percent, Dole 35,
Robertson 26 percent.
   ``Robertson is not doing well among his core constituency, and
he's not moving beyond it,'' Muzzio said.
   The CBS-Times poll said 21 percent of the Republican voters
cited traditional moral values as one of their chief concerns, and
Bush won that group with 43 percent, to 29 percent for Robertson
and 25 percent for Dole.
   ``It's a very broad Bush victory,'' said Gawiser. ``He's solid
across the board.''
   The surveys were conducted by interviewing a random sample of
voters as they left their polling places. The margin of sampling
error for the results was about 5 points.
</TEXT>
