<HEAD>Journalist Suspended For Interviewing IRA Sympathizer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A radio journalist was suspended Tuesday
for breaking broadcast laws by interviewing a sympathizer of the
Irish Republican Army, considered a ``subversive group.''
   Ireland's state-run RTE broadcasting network took Jenny McGeever
off the air by after the broadcast of her interview with Martin
McGuinness.
   McGuinness, a vice president of the IRA's political arm Sinn
Fein, commented on the return of the bodies of three IRA members
killed in Gibraltar while on an alleged bombing mission.
   Her suspension followed an Irish government request for an
investigation of the broadcast.
   The Irish Broadcasting Act prohibits interviews with or comments
from subversive groups.
   These include the IRA and its splinter group, the Irish National
Liberation Army, which are both outlawed; Sinn Fein, which is
legal, and Northern Ireland paramilitary groups.
</TEXT>
