<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 2203EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Iditarod     03-15 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iditarod,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Butcher, Buser Battle For Lead In Iditarod</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KOYUK, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aiming for a third straight victory as the
1,150-mile Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race neared its end, Susan
Butcher left this Eskimo village Tuesday with Martin Buser just two
hours behind her.
   On the trail to Koyuk, Butcher and her 11-dog team overcame a
one-hour deficit, passing Buser and building a lead of five hours
by the time she reached this village, 171 miles from the finish
line in Nome. Butcher rested and fed her weary dogs for more than
five hours, leaving at 7:43 a.m.
   Buser, of Big Lake, made up time by cutting his stay in Koyuk
short. With 12 of his 20 original dogs still in harness, he
followed Butcher out at 9:55 a.m.
   Subzero temperatures and biting winds still hindered the
leaders, and forecasters said the wind chill factor could sink to
minus 70 degrees along the trail's final miles into Nome.
   The winner is expected to cross the finish line at midmorning
Wednesday.
   Butcher, of Manley, has won the last two Iditarods, each time
proving the strength and endurance of her team in the final,
windswept miles along the barren Bering Sea coast. She set a course
record with each victory, last year burning up the trail in 11
days, 2 hours.
   Her closest rival last year was four-time Iditarod champion Rick
Swenson, who waged a neck-and-neck race with Butcher until his dogs
staged a sit-down strike just 22 miles from the finish.
   This year, Swenson, of Two Rivers, about six hours behind
Butcher at last report, leaving Koyuk at 2 p.m. in third place.
Running in fourth was Joe Garnie of Teller, who arrived in Koyuk at
11:49 a.m.
   Herbie Nayokpuk of Shishmaref was fifth. Seventy-year-old Joe
Redington of Knik, credited with organizing the race but never a
winner, was running sixth. He had captured an early-race lead and
held onto it for more than 400 miles before falling back.
   The 16th annual race started March 5 in Anchorage. The first
musher to Nome will collect $30,000 of a $150,000 purse; the next
19 finishers will split the rest. Finishers have to have at least
five dogs in harness at the end of the race in order to qualify.
   Five of the 52 teams that started the race have dropped out.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
