<DOCNO> AP880315-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 2328EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HealthCare     03-15 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Health Care,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Senate Approves Revised Universal Health Care Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By a wide margin, the Massachusetts Senate on
Tuesday approved a revised version of a universal health care bill
championed by Gov. Michael S. Dukakis to launch the state on an
experiment in ``health care for all.''
   Dukakis has touted the proposal in his Democratic presidential
campaign as a model for the nation.
   The Senate endorsed the measure 23-11, sending the bill to a
House-Senate conference committee to iron out differences with a
House version that would exempt many small businesses and shower
favors on certain hospitals.
   Sen. Patricia McGovern, the Senate Ways and Means chairwoman and
the chief architect of the Senate bill, said she was confident a
compromise could be worked out swiftly.
   There are an estimated 600,000 uninsured residents in the state,
more than half of them working people whose employers don't provide
health benefits. Among other things, the bill would provide
incentives for businesses to offer their own health insurance.
   Senate supporters fought off repeated challenges throughout the
day. In a key test, a Republican effort to strip the huge health
care bill of provisions guaranteeing health care protection to all
Massachusetts residents by 1992 was defeated by a 27-9 vote.
   Senate Minority Leader John Parker, who championed the
amendment, tried again later, offering an amendment to match the
House language and exempt all businesses with nine or fewer
employees. That amendment fell short on a vote of 17-19.
   The exemption, included in the House measure, has been
criticized as leaving the entire program open to a challenge on the
grounds that it makes the benefits mandatory for some employees and
not others.
   The universal health care proposal has been tied to a bill
renewing the state's hospital financing law, providing nearly $1
billion in revenue increases for the state's 106 acute-care
hospitals over the next four years.
   The House passed the health care bill two weeks ago, with a
maximum price tag for the state of about $1 billion over four years
to provide insurance coverage for uninsured and incentives to
business to offer the benefit to employees.
   The Senate has estimated the state's cost at about $540 million
over the same period.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
