<DOCNO> AP880315-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 2331EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Moslems     03-15 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Moslems,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquino Says She Is Ready For New Talks With Moslem Insurgents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino said
Wednesday she was prepared for new talks with Moslem insurgents as
her government sought to head off a bid by the rebels for
international Islamic support.
   Mrs. Aquino told reporters she was willing to talk with the Moro
National Liberation Front and ``all Moslem leaders of Mindanao,''
the country's second largest island and stronghold of the 5-million
member Moslem community.
   On Tuesday, Zain Jali, a religious adviser to the liberation
front, told reporters that his group would resume peace talks but
threatened to establish a government-in-exile if the Aquino
administration did not agree to negotiations by next week.
   The front, largest of three Moslem rebel groups, is expected to
seek full membership in the Organization of Islamic Conference when
ministers of the worldwide Moslem group meet next week in Amman,
Jordan.
   Filipino officials have said the move would be tantamount to
recognition of the front as a ``state within a state'' and full
membership could lead to civil war.
   The front has been waging a campaign for 16 years for self-rule,
but the rebellion has been largely limited to small-scale ambushes
and raids. The revolt peaked in the mid-1970s after claiming more
than 50,000 lives.
   Before Wednesday's Cabinet meeting, Mrs. Aquino said she had
received no formal request from the front for new talks.
Negotiations broke down last May because of differences over the
conditions and scope of self-rule.
   A former front official, Zacaria Candao, left Tuesday for Saudi
Arabia for talks with other rebel leaders. Candao, governor of
Maguindanao province, said he would seek a meeting with
Secretary-General Shariffudin Pirzada of the Islamic organization
to discourage full front membership in the organization.
   Meanwhile, a rival Moslem rebel group announced it also was
seeking full membership in the Islamic group. Officials of the Moro
Islamic Liberation Front told reporters in Mindanao that their
organization was more stable than the Moro National Liberation
Front.
   Last April, the Moro Islamic Liberation Front organized a series
of attacks across central Mindanao to protest the decision of the
government to hold talks only with the Moro National Liberation
Front.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
