<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis     03-15 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Looks Beyond Third-Place Finish in Illinois</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis tried to put the best face on a
third-place finish in the Illinois Democratic primary Tuesday
night, saying ``it's not a setback because we ran against two
favorite sons.''
   After numerous questions about whether his showing in Illinois
was a disappointment, the Massachusetts governor was making no
predictions about the next big contest, the Michigan Democratic
caucuses on March 26.
   ``I don't believe we have any front-runners, I don't think we're
going to have a front-runner until the convention,'' he said.
   Dukakis said he didn't think the Illinois results increased the
chances of a brokered convention.
   ``I've been making a number of calls around the country to key
Democrats, and there is an overwhelming sentiment that we should
get behind a nominee,'' he said.
   Illinois Sen. Paul Simon and Jesse Jackson took first and second
respectively in the Illinois primary, leaving Dukakis third in the
popular vote.
   ``It's not a setback, because we ran against two favorite sons
who started off with a lead and stayed there,'' Dukakis said. ``We
did what I can characterize was a respectable third.''
   The seven days between Super Tuesday and the Illinois primary
left Dukakis too little time to attract strong support in Illinois,
the Massachusetts governor said at a news conference at a local
television station. Dukakis spent $246,000 in media advertising in
Illinois.
   During the Illinois campaign, Dukakis had said a vote for Simon
would increase the chances of a brokered Democratic National
Convention, something he said would be a ``disaster.''
   But Tuesday night, Dukakis said he had spent the days on the
telephone with congressmen, senators and other leading Democrats,
and most told him they favored a decision by the voters, not by
convention negotiators.
   Dukakis' demeanor was in marked contrast to his gala celebration
the night of Super Tuesday, when he won the most delegates and the
most states.
   Smiling tightly, Dukakis said with apparent relief: ``Now, we
move on to Michigan, where there are no favorite sons. The field is
wide open.''
</TEXT>
