<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA revised its schedule of space shuttle
flights and cargoes Tuesday, adding a mission that will retrieve a
bus-size experimental station left in space in 1984 for what was to
have been a one-year stay.
   The orbit of the satellite, which gauged the effects of space's
hostile environment on 13 million seeds, metal coatings and
surfaces, is decaying and there were fears it would crash through
the atmosphere and burn up if it weren't recaptured in time.
   The new schedule makes no change in the date of the much-delayed
first post-Challenger flight, now set for Aug. 4. There have been
no American manned missions in space since the Challenger _ the
25th shuttle mission _ exploded on Jan. 28, 1986 and killed its
seven-member crew as it lifted off from Kennedy Space Center in
Florida.
