<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 1338EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv16   03-15 0668</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 16,0685</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Wednesday March 16</NOTE>
<HEAD>Getting the Down Payment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Once a young couple obtains the down payment for
a house, the cost of operating it may be no more than might be
needed for rent and maintenance of an apartment.
   Moreover, the benefits of homeownership are great.
   Owners become member of the elite tax-privileged class, since
mortgage interest and real estate taxes are deductions on federal
income tax returns. They build equity. And their house is a good
hedge against inflation.
   It is for such reasons, and several more, that suggestions are
now pouring into Congress on ways to help young folks get a
financial foot in the door of their own house. What they seek, in
effect, is government sponsorship.
   This wouldn't be the first time that government provided such
assistance, of course, but in recent years it has indicated a
desire to reduce, not add to, its programs. But, say proponents of
aid, there are special factors today.
   Indeed there are.
   First on the list is the down payment. Housing prices have risen
sharply in recent years, far outperforming the after-tax paychecks
of young workers. As a consequence, ownership is down.
   Between World War II and 1980 the ownership rate rose without
significant interruption, reaching 65.6 percent in 1980. But then
it began receding again, settling at 63.8 percent in 1986.
   Even more disturbing, according to the National Association of
Realtors, the rate for people under age 25 and for those in the
prime homebuying ages of 25 to 43, fell more steeply. For the
former, the rate dropped to 21.6 percent from 26.4 percent; for the
latter, the drop was to 45.4 percent from 55 percent.
   These figures have become the cue for proponents of government
assistance, and the Realtors are among the most insistent, as
witness the statement by Nestor Weigand Jr., Realtor president,
that ``it is time for the federal government to recognize that
homeownerhip is beneficial to everyone.''
   ``Everyone'' includes lumber suppliers, plumbers, carpenters,
roofers, appliance and carpet manufacturers, real estate agents,
lawyers and many other folks besides the young couples seeking a
home of their own.
   Their efforts, especially when coordinated, can mean formidable
pressure for another housing program, even in the face of
opposition from those, such as the White House, that would like
government out of private-sector matters.
   Out of this self-interest _ which isn't to deny an element of
true public concern _ some creative, though not especially new,
proposals have emerged, such as these from the Realtors:
   _A program to enable first-time homebuyers to withdraw without
penalty a certain amount from their Individual Retirement Accounts
or other tax-deferred savings to be used only for a down payment.
   _Establishment of an Individual Housing Account, the money from
which would mean eligibility for an income tax credit if used as a
down payment.
   _Creation of a National Employee Homeownership Program to allow
employers to provide down payment assistance to employees, with tax
advantages to both.
   But just as creative is a strictly private-sector plan that also
might be considered. It is simple, informal, responsible, familial
and probably beneficial not just to the individuals involved but
for all society, too.
   Proponents of this plan observe that many homeowner parents have
built up tremendous equity, in part because of the sharp rise in
prices that denies their children the opportunity for a home of
their own.
   Many of these parents are at peak earning power, simultaneous
with a reduction in their expenses. Couldn't they tap some of that
equity in order to lend a down payment to their children? Don't
they owe it to their offspring?
   A main feature of the plan, say its proponents, is its
non-bureaucratic nature. The only way Uncle Sam gets into the act
is to allow a tax deduction to the parents who borrow the money.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wed March 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
