<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv18   03-15 0826</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Today, Adv 18,0851</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, March 18 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Unusual Religious Alliance Formed On Middle East Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an explosive time about a tense issue _
Israel's dealings with Palestinians _ a highly unusual American
religious alliance has been formed to press for solutions to the
crisis.
   Moslem, Jewish and Christian leaders are included in the new
U.S. Interreligious Committee for Peace in the Middle East.
   What made possible the unlikely combination on the keenly
divisive problem was that ``it was an idea whose time had come,''
says Ronald J. Young, executive director of the organization.
   It couldn't have happened, he adds, ``unless the time was ripe
for it.''
   In any case, prominent U.S. Jews and Moslems, who have been on
opposing sides in Middle East conflict, along with top Protestant
and Roman Catholic officials, are extensively involved in the
common effort.
   About 600 religious leaders are initial backers, with other
being enlisted, to work for a ``moral climate'' that would spur
politicians to take initiatives regarded necessary for Middle
Eastern peace.
   Seeking to set forth a middle ground in the conflict, which has
particularly divided Jews and Moslems, the committee's joint
statement affirms these principles:
   _ Support of Israel's right to secure borders, and also of U.N.
resolution 242 calling for Israel's withdrawal from the now
violence-racked West Bank and Gaza taken in the 1967 war, and
security of all states in the region.
   _ The Palestinian people's right to self-determination and to
choose their own leadership.
   _ The urgency of an international conference for peace involving
all parties in the conflict, as well as members of the U.N.
security council, including the U.S. and the Soviet Union.
   ``The Reagan administration has been reluctant about taking
these positions,'' Young said in an interview. ``It has given a
higher priority to keeping the Russians out, and this has not been
helpful.''
   He also said that the U.S. administration also has not
explicitly supported the Palestinians' right to self-determination,
although such a right ``has a history that started in this
country.''
   Young said discussions about a joint approach by American
Christians, Jews and Moslems started last June, before the outbreak
of riots in Gaza and the West Bank, but events there gave the cause
increased urgency.
   They ``dramatically demonstrate that the current situation is
disastrous for the Palestinians and, in the long run, will be
disastrous for Israel as well,'' he said.
   He said local units of the new organization have formed in St.
Louis, Kansas City, Portland, Ore., and Syracuse, N. Y., and are
being planned in 11 other cities _ Atlanta, Los Angeles, San
Francisco, Seattle, Chicago, Boston, Atlanta, Philadelphia,
Pittsburgh, New York and Washington, D.C.
   He said the aim is to build up a national mood of Jews, Moslems
and Christians that would encourage political leaders to act on the
problem.
   ``In dealing with the Middle East, we are dealing not just with
the complexities of the particular situation, but with the whole
history of prejudice against Jews and also against Arabs and
Moslems,'' Young said.
   As a result, he said, ``they have a strong fear against trusting
anyone else with the welfare of their people. There also is a great
deal of insensitivity among Christians about how deep those fears
are.''
   The alliance maintains it is urgent that the U.S. make Middle
Eastern peace a priority of foreign policy.
   Among backers listed of the new effort:
   Moslem _ Dawud Assad, president of the Council of Mosques, and
Fahd M. Al-Nassar, president of the Moslem World League, both of
New York; Iman W. Deen Muhammad of Chicago, and Cherif Sedky, an
American-Arab attorney of Washington, D.C.
   Jewish _ Rabbi Alexander Schindler, president of the Union of
American Hebrew Congregations; its senior vice president, Albert
Vorspan; Rabbi Wolfe Kelman, executive of the Rabbinical Assembly;
Rabbi Eugene Lipman, present of the Central Conference of American
Rabbis, and Rabbi Arthur Schneier, president of the Freedom of
Conscience Foundation.
   Christian _ Archbishop Roger Mahony of Los Angles; the Rev.
Theodore M. Hesburgh, president emeritus of Notre Dame; Eugene
Fisher, head of the U.S. Catholic bishops' committee on
Catholic-Jewish relations; Greek Orthodox Archbishop Iakovos;
Episcopal Presiding Bishop Edmund L. Browning; the Rev. Avery Post,
president of the United Church of Christ; the Rev. John Humbert,
president of the Christian Church (Disciples of Christ) and United
Methodist Bishop George Bashore of Boston.
   Young, a quaker, formerly director of peace programs for the
American Friends Service Committe, said Jews and Moslems have
differed on Mid-East issues, but ``see effort for peace as not
contradicting their consistency.''
   He said:
   ``We are committed to challenging historic and persistent
prejudices against the Jewish people, Moslems and Arabs _
prejudices that inhibit the kind of cooperation for justice and
peace that clearly is a moral imperative of our common Abrahamic
faith.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, March 18</NOTE>
