<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Stocks-Commission     03-14 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Stocks-Commission,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: White House Creating New Group For Stock Market Proposals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House plans to create a new group
that will make final, unified Reagan administration recommendations
on how to prevent another stock market collapse, according to a
published report.
   The New York Times reported in its Tuesday editions that the
White House, whose Brady Commission task force already has made
such recommendations, is creating a new interagency committee to
develop a consolidated administration position in the next 60 to 90
days.
   The committee, which would be headed by Treasury Secretary James
A. Baker III, would include top officials of the Federal Reserve,
Securities and Exchange Commission and Commodity Futures Trading
Commission, the newspaper stated, quoting unidentified White House
aides.
   It was hoped the new committee, details of which still are being
worked out, would be able to smooth over conflicts among the
various regulatory agencies over how best to prevent another market
crash, the newspaper stated.
   Since the Brady Commission came out with its recommendations in
early January, federal regulators have been engaged in often-public
sniping over what regulatory changes should be made to prevent a
repeat of the Oct. 19 market debacle.
   SEC Chairman David S. Ruder, for example, has indicated he
believed his agency should be chief regulator of stock index
futures traded in the commodity markets, a position vehemently
opposed by the CFTC.
   Congressional aides suggested that the White House might view
such divisiveness as weakening its influence over any legislative
response to the October crash.
   The Brady Commission, headed by former New Jersey senator
Nicholas Brady, essentially recommended a coordinated, intermarket
system of ``circuit breakers'' to prevent wild price swings; higher
margin requirements on stock index futures; unified clearing and
settlement operations in the stock and futures markets; and giving
the Fed superagency authority over key issues affecting the stock
and futures markets.
   The Times said details of the interagency committee were
contained in letters sent Friday by Senate Banking Committee
Chairman William Proxmire to White House chief of staff Howard H.
Baker Jr., and the chairmen of the Fed, SEC and CFTC. In those
letters, Proxmire referred to a conversation with Baker regarding
the committee.
   Proxmire indicated he was pleased with the idea, but also stated
that 90 days might be too long for Congress to wait for the new
group's recommendations, given that the agencies involved already
had conducted their own studies of the crash and made
recommendations.
   Proxmire also stated he planned to ask the Fed, SEC and CFTC top
submit their legislative proposals in time for a March 31 hearing
on the issue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
