cash to $6.3 billion, giving it an edge over hostile competitor
Campeau Corp.
   Campeau indicated Monday it had no immediate plans to revise its
own $6.2 billion offer, but extended the bid _ which was to expire
today _ through Friday.
   In addition to sweetening its buyout offer, Macy received a
``lock-up'' option to buy Federated's Bullock's-Bullock's Wilshire
and I. Magnin retail divisions if the merger falls through.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.P. Stevens & Co. accepted a nearly $1 billion
cash buyout bid from a private investment group, spurning offers
from its own management and rival West Point-Pepperell Inc.
   In active trading Monday on the New York Stock Exchange, Stevens
stock jumped $5.37{ a share to close at $61.12{, or just under the
offer by Odyssey Partners.
   Odyssey and other private investors agreed to pay $61.50 in cash
for each of Stevens' 15.5 million shares outstanding, or around
$953.2 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AMARILLO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mesa Limited Partnership's second foray
into the gold industry fell short when the group, controlled by
oilman T. Boone Pickens, withdrew its $1.88 billion cash offer for
Homestake Mining Co.
   Mesa said Monday it retracted its offer to acquire Homestake, a
leading gold producer, in a negotiated transaction for a price of
$20 a share in cash.
   Homestake previously had rejected Mesa's offer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business inventories rose 0.4 percent in
January, less than half the increase of the previous month, as a
rebound in car sales helped to reduce a huge backlog of unsold
cars, the government has reported.
   The Commerce Department said Monday that inventories increased
by $3 billion in January, pushing the total of unsold items on
store shelves and backlots to a seasonally adjusted $705.85 billion.
   Analysts said the slowdown in the rate of increase was an
encouraging sign and indicated economic growth may not weaken in
the first part of this year as much as had been feared.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. has a stronger-than-expected case
in its $5.7 billion damage lawsuit against Eastman Kodak Co.,
placing the instant photography pioneer in its best position in
years, some analysts say.
   The damage claim filed last month in federal court has sent
Polaroid's stock soaring on Wall Street, even though Kodak has
dismissed Polaroid's claim as ``ludicrous.''
   The two companies are meeting in court this week to discuss a
trial date in the damage portion of the case. In 1985, Kodak was
found guilty of infringing on Polaroid patents when it entered the
instant camera business in 1976.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Internal documents indicate G.D. Searle &
Co. may have misled doctors and a federal regulatory agency about
safety characteristics of its Copper-7 contraceptive, according to
an attorney representing a woman who claims that the device made
her sterile.
   Wall Street reacted Monday by knocking the stock of Monsanto
Co., Searle's parent, down $3.12{ a share to $83.37{.
   According to the documents, Searle apparently hid complaints
about the Copper-7 from the U.S. Food and Drug Administration.
</TEXT>
