<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 0059EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Stevens Bjt   03-15 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stevens, Bjt,0565</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>J.P. Stevens In Another Takeover Agreement; Is Bidding Over?</BYLINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Stevens-Glance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Textile industry analysts say the bidding may
not be over for J.P. Stevens & Co., even though the company has
accepted a nearly $1 billion cash buyout offer from an investment
group.
   A group led by Odyssey Partners of New York announced Monday it
agreed to pay $61.50 in cash for each of Stevens' 15.5 million
shares outstanding, or about $953.24 million.
   The offer is subject to a majority of the shares being tendered
and the necessary financing being obtained.
   Analysts called Odyssey's bid fair, although some said they
thought the bidding could continue.
   In active trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Stevens' stock
jumped $5.37{ a share to close at $61.12{.
   Over the past few weeks, Stevens has fielded rival offers from
Atlanta-based West Point-Pepperell Inc. and a group led by its own
senior management, including Chairman Whitney Stevens, a fifth
generation member of the family that founded the company in 1813.
   The management group offered $55 a share in cash and securities
in a leveraged buyout about two weeks ago, up from its initial
offer of $43 a share. In a leveraged buyout, a company is acquired
largely with borrowed money repaid with a target company's profits
or the sales of assets.
   West Point-Pepperell, a major household fabrics maker with
brands that include Arrow, Martex and Lady Pepperell, offered to
buy Stevens for $56 a share in cash, or about $867 million. The
company confirmed Monday it had considered raising its offer to
$62.50 a share, but had not made a formal bid at the higher price.
   West Point-Pepperell refused to comment on what, if any, further
action it might take.
   ``The arbitragers think there could be more bidding,'' said
Edward Johnson, a textile analyst with Johnson Redbook, a division
of Prescott, Ball & Turben Inc. ``A deal is never done until all
the stock is signed over.''
   George O. Zimmerman, an analyst with Gruntal & Co., said a
higher offer could torpedo the deal with Odyssey. ``I think they'll
have to take the highest bid,'' he said.
   Odyssey is a private investment company. Its deals have included
the purchase of a controlling interest in Lucky Stores Inc.'s Eagle
Food Stores, located in the Midwest, and a leveraged buyout of
Research Cottrell Inc., a pollution control, engineering and
construction company.
   Odyssey said it would finance the deal with a $600 million loan
from Citibank, $570 million from the sale subordinated debt and
preferred stock and $100 million in equity investment.
   Should the deal go through, Johnson predicted, Odyssey likely
could sell parts of Stevens to pay off its debt.
   Stevens already undertook a major restructuring about five years
ago, selling off some of its finished fabrics divisions to
concentrate more on home furnishings.
   New York-based Stevens, one of the nation's biggest textile
makers with 23,000 employees, produces home fashion textiles such
as sheets, towels and carpets under the brand names Ralph Lauren,
Laura Ashley and Pierre Cardin. The company also makes automotive
products and industrial products.
   The company had an after-tax profit of $56 million on sales of
$1.6 billion in the fiscal year ended Oct. 31.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
