<DOCNO> AP880315-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 0118EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Japan-Honda Bjt   03-15 0900</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Honda, Bjt,0925</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honda Motor Lacks Punch At Home, But Analysts See Good Potential
For Growth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Its victories in overseas markets have brought
Honda Motor Co. worldwide recognition, but the company still is
waging an uphill battle to become a dominant automaker in its own
backyard.
   In sharp contrast with Honda's success abroad _ it holds about
3.5 percent of the world auto market _ the company has had trouble
penetrating the Japanese market dominated by the ``Big Two'' of
Toyota Motor Corp. and Nissan Motor Co., which together control
nearly a 50 percent share.
   In recent years, Honda's domestic sales have been growing, often
faster than the rate of Japan's overall motor-vehicle market
expansion.
   To boost growth further, the company will add new cars and
models to its product line and increase the number of Honda dealers
and salesmen each year into the 1990s, says Honda President Takashi
Kume.
   By 1991, Honda expects its domestic network to grow about 25
percent from now to 3,000 dealers and more than double the number
of salesmen to 18,000.
   New products will allow Honda to sell 800,000 cars and
mini-vehicles a year at home by 1991 and 1 million by the
mid-1990s, Kume says. These projections compare with last year's
sales of 546,979 units and this year's forecast of 620,000 vehicles.
   Honda's domestic market share rose to 9.1 percent in 1987 from
7.0 percent in 1986.
   But in a market where overall demand for cars, trucks and buses,
exceeded 6 million units for the first time last year, Honda still
lags far behind Toyota and Nissan.
   Analysts say Japanese culture and Honda's own history have
contributed to its domestic struggle.
   Honda _ originally a motorcycle manufacturer _ had a late start
in the auto business, entering the four-wheeled vehicle market in
1963 some 30 years after the Big Two. Analysts say this still
haunts the company: Honda's sales network of 2,400 dealers and
8,200 salespeople is dwarfed, for example, by Toyota's 4,000
dealers and 41,000 salespeople.
   Takamori Matsuda, vice president of Prudential-Bache Securities
(Japan) Ltd., says Japan's ``unspoken dealer loyalty'' is a major
obstacle to Honda's expansion in the domestic market.
   ``Unlike the U.S. market, where car retailers are mostly
independent (from manufacturers) and often switch makers or brands
they handle, there is virtually no betrayal on the part of dealers
in this country,'' Matsuda said.
   Japanese automakers generally maintain high capital
participation in their dealers and thus enjoy more control over
them. That condition makes a switch, say, from Toyota to Honda,
virtually impossible, Matsuda said.
   Tetsuo Sakiya, author of the book ``Honda Motor: the Men, the
Management, the Machines'' and professor of international relations
at Musashino Womens College in Tokyo, contends Honda could have
closed the gap with the Big Two if company founder Shoichiro Honda
and his senior officials in the late 1960s had more foresight.
   Honda early on had decided to rely on an air-cooled engine and
missed out on the first full-fledged wave of Japanese motorization
in the late 1960s and the early 1970s because it did not have the
``right product,'' a car with a quieter and cleaner water-cooled
engine, Sakiya said.
   ``If Honda hadn't chosen an air-cooled engine, its standing
would've been a lot better against Toyota and Nissan today,''
Sakiya said.
   Honda introduced its 1300 model, a sedan powered by an
air-cooled engine, in 1969 but replaced it two years later with a
lightweight car, the Honda Life, with a much-acclaimed water-cooled
CVCC engine.
   A more conspicuous cause of Honda's weakness at home, and in
overseas markets to some extent, has been its lack of a full
product line and diversity in the styling and size of its cars,
according to analysts. Not until October 1985 did Honda, a thriving
maker of economical subcompacts, decide to pursue affluent
consumers with the Legend, a 2.7 liter-engine luxury car.
   Because of its relatively limited lineup of models in the over 2
liter engine class, Honda will not benefit as much as the Big Two
from the boom in the market for bigger, more powerful and more
expensive cars, analysts say.
   To expand its lineup further, Honda also recently re-entered the
minicar market and is scheduled to launch Japanese sales of a
version of the Accord series assembled at its facilities in
Marysville, Ohio. It is also widely rumored to be planning to
introduce a sports car powered by a six-cylinder or eight-cylinder
engine next year.
   Honda also is believed to be planning a line of luxury models by
the 1990s featuring a flagship sedan with a V-8 or V-12 engine.
   Matsuda says to compete domestically Honda also must deal with
Japanese upbringing that fosters more conformity and harmony among
individuals, compared with the U.S. system that stresses
individuality.
   ``It's easier to sell to Americans who aren't afraid of making
their own decisions and accepting the unknown, compared with
Japanese consumers who are often oversensitive to impressions they
make on others through the purchase of a product,'' Matsuda said.
``The upshot of this (Japanese) attitude is that people are driving
cars, often white, from the same familiar makers.''
   But analysts think Honda's potential for sustained growth at
home is strong. They concur that Honda is pulling ahead to emerge
as the definite winner in a three-way battle for the slot of
Japan's third biggest automaker with Mitsubishi Motors Corp. and
Mazda Motor Co.
</TEXT>
