<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 0126EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Polaroid Bjt   03-15 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polaroid, Bjt,0679</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Has Jumped Since $5.7 Billion Damage Request In Kodak Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buoyed by prospects of a billion-dollar court
settlement in a 12-year-old patent infringement case and by
takeover speculation, Polaroid Corp.'s stock has soared on Wall
Street in recent weeks.
   The instant photography pioneer is seeking $5.7 billion in
damages from Eastman Kodak Co., which was found guilty in 1985 of
violating seven of 150 Polaroid patents when it entered the instant
camera business in 1976.
   After reviewing papers filed in U.S. District Court here last
month, analysts increased their estimates for a possible settlement
to above $1 billion from their initial $300 million to $500 million
range.
   ``After reading the documents, a number of people said that
Polaroid's case is stronger than we had expected,'' said Eugene
Glazer, an analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   The companies are to meet Friday with Judge Rya Zobel and may
discuss setting a trial date on the damages issue.
   Analysts said the possibility of a large award has attracted
investors and also invited speculation that a corporate raider
might bid for the company in hopes of realizing a windfall on a big
settlement.
   Polaroid, based in Cambridge, was trading in the low $20s a
share until the damage request was disclosed Feb. 19. Since then
Polaroid has climbed, topping $36 a share at one point. Polaroid
rose 25 cents to $34 a share Monday in New York Stock Exchange
trading.
   Purchasing patterns have been in small blocks, however, and no
individual buyer has notified the Securities and Exchange
Commission that it holds as much as 5 percent of the stock.
   Polaroid won't comment on stock activity, takeover rumors or a
settlement.
   ``We have indicated from the very beginning 12 years ago that we
were always open to an out-of-court settlement,'' spokesman Harry
Johnson said. ``Talking about such matters in the media has a
chilling effect on that possibility.''
   In court documents, Polaroid argues it is entitled to $3.2
billion in lost camera and film sales. The company is seeking $2.5
billion more for lost opportunities to develop and market new
products.
   Kodak, which was ordered out if its $200 million a year instant
camera business in January 1986, has dismissed the claim as
``ludicrous and ridiculously inflated.'' The Rochester, N.Y.-based
photo giant argues Polaroid is entitled to a reasonable royalty,
not lost profits.
   If Zobel finds Kodak guilty of willfully infringing on
Polaroid's patents, pre-tax damages can be tripled under federal
law, raising the potential maximum award to $11 billion.
   No one expects the settlement to be that large, but a $1 billion
award _ equal to about $10 a share _ would allow Polaroid to
diversify into fields such as information retrieval or conventional
photography.
   Along with the Polaroid brand name, the possibility that the
company could run better under new management is keeping takeover
interest high, analysts said.
   ``It has the characteristics of the type of company that could
be run to generate greater cash flow,'' Glazer said.
   Polaroid founder Edwin H. Land invented instant photography in
1947 and first marketed it in 1948. Polaroid held a monopoly for
almost 30 years until Kodak entered the field.
   Polaroid camera sales peaked at 7.5 million units in 1978 before
sinking to 3.4 million in 1984. Sales jumped to 4.4 million in 1986
after the company introduced the Spectra camera, with quality
closer to that of 35 millimeter prints, but fell by 16 percent last
year.
   Polaroid had entered the 1970s with high expectations due to
technology for its SX-70 camera, which produced fast, dry color
prints. But Polaroid never was able to bring the cost of film down
enough, which hurt instant photography sales.
   Analysts said Polaroid could get a boost next month with the
introduction of the Spectra 600, priced at $40 to $60, and the
Image, which promises better quality for $60 to $80.
</TEXT>
