<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     03-15 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Steadies in Narrow Range; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained against most major currencies in
early European trading today.
   Gold prices were mixed.
   Dealers said the dollar was trading quietly in a narrow range as
market participants awaited Thursday's report of the U.S.
merchandise trade deficit for January.
   The British pound, which soared 10 cents against the dollar in a
month, slipped back ahead of the presentation to Parliament this
afternoon of the Conservative government's annual spring budget.
   Dealers in Europe said they were waiting to see whether the
budget delivered expected tax cuts and led to lower interest rates.
An interest rate cut would rein in the pound.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before it begins in Europe, the
dollar rose 0.02 yen to a closing 127.25. Later in London, the
dollar was quoted at 127.10 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Monday's
prices, included: 1.6660 West German marks, up from 1.6645; 1.3760
Swiss francs, up from 1.3693; 5.6585 French francs, up from 5.6375;
1.8717 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8645; 1,232.70 Italian lire, up
from 1,227.87; 1.2570 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2577.
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.8510, compared
with $1.8575 Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $440.80 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $441.00. At mid-morning today, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$442.15.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $442.25, up from $441.50 late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.54 to close at a bid $443.27.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.21 a troy
ounce, down from Monday's $6.22.
</TEXT>
