<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     03-15 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Rise In Japan; Dollar Nearly Unchanged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rebounded today, while the dollar
remained nearly unchanged against the Japanese yen as traders in
Tokyo awaited figures on the U.S. trade deficit for January.
   The dollar dipped at one point to 126.80 yen, but closed at
127.25 yen, up 0.02 yen from Monday's close. Its high for the day
was 127.30 yen.
   On the previous two trading days, the dollar lost a total of
0.97 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which dropped by 110.22 points on Monday,
continued to fall during today's morning session, but rebounded and
closed the day at 25,475.67 points, up 42.16 points, or 0.16
percent, from Monday's close. Volume was estimated at 1.7 billion
shares in the first section.
   ``Trading was active, but there weren't any real factors worth
commenting on,'' said an analyst with a major brokerage. ``The
market is gradually progressing toward its precrash levels and we
are seeing a general consolidation,'' said the analyst, who spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   Traders said steels and heavy industrials led the afternoon
surge.
   An exchange dealer at a major commercial bank in Tokyo, also
speaking on condition of anonymity, said the Tokyo market ``seems
to remain relatively calm'' until the release on Thursday of U.S.
trade figures for January.
   At a meeting of the House of Councillor's Budget Committee
today, Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa predicted: ``The dollar
will appreciate against the yen in the future, rather than
stabilize.''
</TEXT>
