<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks     03-15 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Up 19.2 Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices moved higher Tuesday morning on
optimism about Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson's budget
statement for fiscal 1989, due later in the day.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 19.2
points, or 1 percent, at 1,838.7 at midday.
   Volume was a moderate 241.3 million shares at midday, up from
176.3 million shares at the same time a day earlier.
   Prices advanced gradually through the morning because of
optimism about the contents of Lawson's budget statement, dealers
said.
   In addition to tax rate cuts, investors were expecting Lawson to
outline financial targets which might provide a further boost for
the pound, dealers said. That might force the government to cut
British base lending rates in order to stabilize the currency, they
added.
   But some analysts discounted the idea because of concern that an
interest rate cut would boost inflation.
   ``The idea of a base rate cut seems to be gaining credibility in
the market,'' said Kevin Gardiner, an economist at Warburg
Securities. ``But we still don't think it's very likely.''
</TEXT>
