<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 0841EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Firestone-Pirelli Bjt   03-15 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Firestone-Pirelli, Bjt,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firestone Board Seeking Alternatives To Pirelli; Bridgestone Deal
Shaky</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firestone Tire & Rubber Co. says the Pirelli
Group's unsolicited $1.8 billion takeover offer will likely force
it to abandon a previous agreement to sell most of its tire
operations to Bridgestone Corp. of Japan.
   But Firestone said its board of directors has authorized
management to explore alternatives to the Pirelli bid that possibly
could include a new deal with Bridgestone.
   Firestone said Monday that its board met to consider Pirelli's
$58-a-share tender offer but took no action.
   The company said that in light of Pirelli's offer it was
unlikely to consummate the joint venture agreement it announced
with the Japanese tiremaker on Feb. 16. Under that agreement,
Bridgestone would pay about $1.25 billion to buy 75 percent of
Firestone's tire operations.
   Pirelli's offer is contingent on Firestone dropping its plans to
enter the joint venture with Bridgestone.
   Firestone said that in seeking alternatives to the Pirelli
offer, its advisers had begun discussions with Bridgestone. The
board indicated it would meet again this week to complete its
review of Pirelli's offer.
   The board also reiterated its stance that shareholders should
not tender their shares until it issued its recommendation.
Firestone had stated previously the board would make its
recommendation by Friday.
   Firestone stock dipped 87{ cents to $61.62{ a share in active
trading Monday on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Earlier, a federal court in Cleveland heard arguments over
Pirelli's lawsuit attempting to declare Ohio's anti-takeover law
unconstitutional.
   Pirelli is seeking a temporary restraining order to keep the
Ohio Control Share Acquisition Act from affecting its bid for
Firestone. The act requires a hostile bidder to wait up to 50 days
for shareholders to vote before he can acquire tendered shares.
   A lawsuit challenging the law was filed last week by Veere Inc.,
a holding company owned by Pirelli that is incorporated in Delaware.
   Dennis Orr, an attorney for Veere, said the law is a burden on
interstate commerce and could hurt shareholders by giving Firestone
time to defeat Pirelli's tender offer, launched a week ago.
   Firestone attorney Patrick F. McCartan countered Orr's argument
by saying, ``Control is one of the most valuable assets a
shareholder can possess. It is a collective asset and should be
(given up) in a collective manner.''
   U.S. District Judge Alice Batchelder did not issue a ruling on
the temporary restraining order Monday.
</TEXT>
