<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Prudential     03-15 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Prudential,0159</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prudential-Bache Posts $164 Million Loss In 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. lost $164
million, more than previously estimated.
   Prudential Insurance Co. of America, the securities firm's
parent, said Monday its own profit from operations, before
dividends and federal income tax, rose to $2.65 billion from $2.55
billion. Prudential did not announce a net income figure.
   Prudential, the nation's largest insurer, did not detail the
reasons for the loss at Prudential-Bache except to say it included
a charge of $47 million from the closing of an international trade
unit.
   Prudential-Bache told its employees in January it had taken an
unspecified charge related to litigation involving the alleged
attempt by the Hunt brothers of Texas to corner the silver market
in early 1980.
   The securities subsidiary also said it had taken substantial
charges hiring investment bankers and had losses in the October
stock market crash and its aftermath.
</TEXT>
