<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 0911EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SouthKorea-Tariffs     03-15 0116</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-South Korea-Tariffs,0121</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Import Tariffs To Be Cut Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea plans to sharply cut its
tariffs on imports during the next five years as part of its
efforts to boost foreign sales here, government officials said
Tuesday.
   Officials at the Ministry of Finance said a plan under study
calls for the country's average import tariffs of 16.9 percent to
be cut by half by 1993.
   Details of the plan would be completed by June, the officials
said.
   The plan, they added, is aimed at stimulating imports, thereby
cutting South Korea's growing current account surplus, which
reached $10 billion last year. The imbalance has led to complaints
from trading partners.
</TEXT>
