<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru   03-15 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inventory Growth Slows, Markets Quiet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs on fourth-quarter current account report;
picks up 3rd graf pvs, Analysts said ....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The deficit in the broadest measure of U.S. foreign trade surged
13.7 percent last year to a record $160.7 billion, the government
reported today.
   The Commerce Department said the current account deficit grew
from the previous record of $141.4 billion in 1986 even though the
deficit for the final three months of the year narrowed slightly.
   The current account covers not only the flow of merchandise
across the U.S. border but also the flow of services, primarily
investment earnings between countries.
   While the United States has run deficits in merchandise trade
for 16 of the past 17 years, the current account was in surplus as
recently as 1981 as Americans' earnings on overseas investments
were enough to offset the merchandise deficits.
   On Monday the Commerce Department reported a 0.4 percent rise in
January business inventories, less than half the December increase,
reflecting a rebound in car sales that reduced backlogs of unsold
vehicles.
   Analysts said the slower growth suggested the economy may not
weaken or lapse into recession in the first half of this year, as
had been widely feared following the stock market crash in October.
   Higher business inventories and sluggish consumer spending are
considered a negative trend because they eventually collide to
cause production cutbacks and layoffs.
   The news was ignored by Wall Street, where stocks showed no
clear trend in the quietest trading this year. The Dow Jones
industrial average gained 15.09 points to 2,050.07, in a session
influenced largely by takeover news and speculation.
   Volume on the New York Stock Exchange totaled 131.89 million
shares, the lightest since a 111.58 million-share day on Dec. 29.
   Prices barely budged in the bond market, a sensitive barometer
of interest rates and the economy. The Treasury's closely watched
30-year bond declined [ point, or about $1.25 for every $1,000 in
face amount. Its yield, which moves inversely to price, edged up to
8.51 percent from 8.50 percent late Friday.
   Traders were reluctant to buy or sell aggressively, largely
because of uncertainty about the January trade deficit numbers to
be released by the Commerce Department on Thursday.
   The markets have been fixated on the trade deficit for months
because the economy's unprecedented reliance on imports is
considered one of the most visible symbols of economic weakness and
declining competitiveness.
   But the deficit narrowed in November and December, suggesting
the protracted decline of the dollar over the past two years was
helping U.S. manufacturers reclaim foreign and domestic markets
from overseas competition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880315-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 1021EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Earns-Coleco     03-15 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Earns-Coleco,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toymaker's Losses Lead to Restructuring Plans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coleco Industries Inc., which is
expected to miss an April 1 interest payment on its debentures,
says that unless it can restructure its finances it may have to
seek bankruptcy court protection.
   The toymaker announced Monday it lost $98.8 million in the final
quarter of 1987 and $105.4 million for the whole year.
   And Chairman Arnold C. Greenberg said Coleco has a $19 million
interest payment due on debentures April 1, but will not make that
payment.
   Coleco and other major toy manufacturers were hit hard by
declining sales last year. The losses announced by Coleco Monday
follow deficits of $110.6 in fourth-quarter 1986 and $111.2 million
for all of that year.
   The toymaker reported sales of $69 million in the last quarter
of 1987, compared with $73.7 million for the same period a year
earlier. Its 1987 sales totaled $504.5 million, up slightly from
$500.7 million in 1986.
   Coleco said it planned to announce a restructuring plan by the
end of this week. However, if all parties to the restructuring do
not agree to the plan, ``the company could find itself in
reorganization,'' said Morton E. Handel, Coleco's executive vice
president for corporate development.
   The company's short-term bank debt increased from $90.7 million
in 1986 to $142.1 million in 1987. Overall, Coleco paid $59.6
million in interest during 1987, compared with $42.7 million in
1986.
   Nearly $40 million of the 1987 interest was due to the $300
million in subordinated debentures Coleco has outstanding. Handel
said the company will propose to replace those debentures with a
combination of common stock, new debentures and debentures
convertible into stock.
   If the owners of the debentures accept the proposed exchange, it
would reduce some of Coleco's interest expenses and convert some
debt into positive ownership interest in the company.
   ``The company needs to get out from underneath its significant
debt load to obtain profitibility. The company needs to take steps
to ensure its survival,'' said Gary Jacobson, an analyst with
Kidder Peabody & Co. in New York City.
   Coleco has laid off more than 300 workers and taken other steps
to cut costs.
</TEXT>
