<1ST_LINE>r f BC-AutoRecalls     03-15 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Auto Recalls,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Recalling Station Wagons, Lincoln Continentals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. is recalling about 28,000 1987 and
1988 Ford Crown Victoria and Mercury Grand Marquis station wagons
for inspection of seat belts that may have improperly installed
retractors.
   Ford also is recalling 9,300 1988-model Lincoln Continental cars
for installation of spring seats on the rear torsion springs.
   Seat belts in the station wagons' optional rear-facing auxiliary
seats will be inspected and replaced, if necessary, Ford said in a
news release Monday. The belts might fit too loosely or retract
slowly if retractors were found to be installed on the wrong side
of the seats, the statement said.
   The spring seats on the Continentals are meant to prevent the
spring from touching the rear tire if the spring breaks while in
service, it said.
   Of the 9,300 Continentals being recalled, about 5,000 will be
inspected to see whether inboard attachments of the driver's and
right front seat belt assemblies were properly secured, the
statement said. Belts not properly secured to the anchor attachment
could loosen or pull free in a collision, it said.
   Inspections and necessary modifications will be made by Ford or
Lincoln-Mercury dealers at no cost to owners, the statement said.
There were no reports of accidents or injuries involving any of the
components involved with the recalls, the company said.
</TEXT>
