<1ST_LINE>r f PM-UnitedArtists 1stLd-Writethru f0059 03-15 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-United Artists, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0059,0335</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: corrects spelling of Beth Henley in 3rd graf</NOTE>
<HEAD>United Artists Communications To Begin Producing Motion Pictures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENGLEWOOD, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Artists Communications Inc., an
entertainment conglomerate with cable television systems and the
nation's No. 1 theater chain, has announced the creation of New
York-based Corsair Pictures.
   The subsidiary firm will develop films that cost between $3
million and $10 million, an amount considered modest by Hollywood
standards.
   Stewart D. Blair, president and chief executive officer of
United Artists, announced Monday that Corsair Picture's first
production would be ``The Miss Firecracker Contest,'' a comedy
written by Pulitzer Prize-winning playwright Beth Henley. Actress
Holly Hunter, who was nominated for an Oscar for her role as a
newscast producer in ``Broadcast News,'' has been signed to star in
the film.
   Blair said the venture was a ``low-key experiment.''
   ``We think there is a window for modestly priced,
high-demographic films,'' Blair said.
   ``We're looking for class. Not art films, but not slash and gash
movies either. We're not into teen exploitation films.''
   Frank Perry, who was nominated for an Oscar as best director for
the movie ``David and Lisa'' has been named to head Corsair. Perry
had directed for Pyramid Films, also a subsidiary of United
Artists. Corsair replaces Pyramid Films.
   Blair expects to produce three or four films a year, he said.
   ``Frank (Perry) has done 17 movies and he's only been over
budget once, and that was only be two percent,'' he said.
   Most of the firm's movies will be for theater distribution,
followed by sale to pay television or the video market. Finally
they will be sold to cable, he said.
   United Artists owns 2,000 movie screens, making it the largest
chain in the country.
   ``Certainly having that number of screens gives you a leg up,''
Blair said. ``But a movie has to be released across the board to
the most screens for it to generally make sense.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
