<1ST_LINE>a f BC-KetchupSpray Adv19-20   03-15 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ketchup Spray, Adv 19-20,0709</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 19</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions March 19-20 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>New Jersey Company Makes Spray Cans For Ketchup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Imagine spraying ketchup on a hamburger or
spritzing mustard on a hotdog with an aerosol-like can.
   A Hoboken-based company wants just such containers to become
commonplace in kitchens across America.
   Enviro-Spray Systems Inc. also hopes its packaging technology,
already popular in Europe, will help transform the 8-year-old
research and development company into a profitable manufacturing
and marketing firm.
   The company, which went public last year, hopes to have lines of
sprayable ketchup, tomato sauces and mustard in U.S. stores by June.
   Mayonnaise, chocolate and apple sauce are waiting in the wings,
said company President Gordon L. Banks.
   ``It's the beginning of something very, very important,'' he
said in a recent interview.
   The patented spray process was introduced successfully in
Europe, where it is used to dispense a popular form of shave gel as
well as condiments, hand cleaners and pharmaceuticals.
   For its push into the United States, Enviro-Spray will focus on
food products, said Pat Black, assistant to the president. And for
the first time, the company will get involved in selling the
products as well as the process.
   The ketchup, mustard and tomato sauce to be marketed here is
made by the French concern CCRF under the Claude Vetillard label,
Ms. Black said.
   Essentially, the cans resemble aerosol sprayers but do not mix
other substances with the product to be dispensed. Inside the can
is a pouch with sodium bicarbonate and citric acid, which is
activated by a button on the can.
   When the can is activated, the two chemicals react inside the
pouch, creating pressure that forces the product out.
   And presto, a thin stripe of ketchup is applied to your waiting
hot dog.
   The ``GrowPak'' pouches are tamper proof and the food needs no
refrigeration, has a longer shelf life and is more convenient to
dispense, Banks said.
   Since no propellants are needed to make the cans work, no
fluorocarbons, identified as harmful to the protective ozone layer
in the atmosphere, are introduced into the environment.
   Banks said he hopes such advantages will convince consumers and
restaurants to buy GrowPak products and help make the company
profitable.
   Enviro-Spray had a net loss of $448,000 on sales of $455,000 in
the second quarter ended Dec. 31. That compared with a $1 million
loss on sales of $191,000 in the same period a year earlier.
   Ms. Black attributed the losses to the heavy start-up costs
associated with the development of the equipment that manufactures
the pouches. Banks sees the company entering the black by 1989.
   ``When people get their hands on these cans, they really love
(them,)'' he said.
   Whether they will be willing to spend two to three times more
for them _ $2.50 to $3 for a 9-ounce can, as Banks described their
cost _ is another question.
   ``I doubt people would be willing to pay that price,'' said Beth
Adams, spokeswoman for Pittsburgh, Pa.-based H.J. Heinz Co., a
leading U.S. ketchup producer. Ms. Adams said she had never heard
of the process.
   ``It just seems like a strange idea,'' she said, adding that
consumers may have a difficult time accepting a food product in a
type of container that usually dispenses hairspray, carpet cleaner
or disinfectant.
   About 30 percent to 40 percent of the ketchup market is
contained in plastic squirt bottles, a development of only the last
decade, she said.
   Enviro-Spray also sells its system to drug, cosmetic, pet and
plant care companies, Banks said.
   Last year, 10 million pouches with the system were sold in
Europe and 15 million are expected to be sold this year. Banks
hopes to sell 10 million in the United States in 1988.
   Company officials believe their business will grow as the
products in the cans catch on.
   ``The more cans of Vetillard's ketchup we sell, the more pouches
we sell to them,'' said Ms. Black.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions March 19-20</NOTE>
</DOC>
