<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Seabrook-Emergency     03-15 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Seabrook-Emergency,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FEMA Withdraws Key Objection To N.H. Evac Plans For Seabrook</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency has
withdrawn a key objection to New Hampshire's emergency evacuation
plans for the $5.3 billion Seabrook nuclear power plant.
   Seabrook opponents, citing the removal of a key critic of the
plans from a FEMA review board, charged that the agency caved in to
pressure from the Nuclear Regulatory Commission and the plant's
owners. A Seabrook spokesman today called that charge ``a
smokescreen.'' A FEMA spokesman would not comment.
   The agency said in testimony to the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission on Monday that shelters are not needed and evacuation
alone offers enough protection for people that crowd beaches near
the seacoast reactor on hot summer days.
   Last summer, the agency would not approve the plans, citing 55
deficiencies observed in a February 1986 drill. A major objection
was that there aren't enough airtight buildings to protect people
from dangerous radiation that could be released in an accident.
   Now the state has considered sheltering and determined that ``in
most cases evacuation would be a preferred option and would provide
ample time to move the beach population from the area safely,
before there would be any radioactive release,'' Seabrook spokesman
David Scanzoni said today.
   FEMA's new testimony concludes: ``The requirement for a range of
protective measures has been satisfied, even though the state of
New Hampshire has chosen not to shelter the summer beach population
except in very limited circumstances. With respect to the summer
beach population, (federal standards) have been met.''
   FEMA officials acknowledged in their testimony that they were
deferring to the NRC staff's argument that evacuation offers better
protection than sheltering.
   The NRC staff and other four other federal agencies out of eight
involved in an interagency review of the plan had been trying to
persuade FEMA to change its position, according to testimony during
hearings on the New Hampshire plans. The other four were the
Department of Energy, Department of Transportation, Environmental
Protection Agency and the Food and Drug Administration.
   Seabrook is completed but unlicensed until it can gain NRC
approval for evacuation plans for a 10-mile zone around it. An NRC
licensing board resumes hearings next month on the New Hampshire
plans.
   Massachusetts officials won't cooperate in planning for six
Massachusetts communities within the 10-mile zone. Seabrook has
submitted its own plans for Massachusetts. No hearings have been
set.
   The new FEMA testimony stopped short of endorsing the New
Hampshire plans, but it clears a major obstacle.
   Robert Backus, lawyer for the Seacoast Anti-Pollution League,
said, ``I view it as a total agency collapse.'' He noted that
Edward Thomas, a top FEMA official in its Northeast regional office
who had written the earlier criticism of Seabrook's plans, was not
involved in the new testimony.
   ``I suspect that there was a fight for the soul of the agency
here and the guys who are no longer the witnesses are not the guys
who won the fight,'' Backus said.
   ``FEMA has capitulated to those who want Seabrook licensed
regardless of the fact that minimum safety requirements cannot be
met,'' said Massachusetts Attorney General James Shannon.
   FEMA spokesman Bill McAda today declined to comment on the new
testimony and on charges that the agency succombed to pressure to
change its opinion.
   Scanzoni denied that Seabrook officials pressured FEMA.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
