<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     03-15 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0428</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market moved modestly lower today as
investors stayed on the sidelines ahead of the government's
upcoming release of trade data and the year's first ``triple
witching hour.''
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 4.15 points to
2,045.92 at noon on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 10 to 9 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 695 up, 619 down and
526 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 66,680,000 million shares.
   Analysts said the market drifted in a narrow range in the
absence of any major news.
   ``There is a mood in the street of reluctance to make
commitments'' prior to the government's release of January
merchandise trade figures on Thursday, said Lew Smith, a technical
analyst at Bear Stearns & Co. That sentiment also dominated
activity in the previous session.
   ``The last two (market) responses to the trade numbers took
place in a half hour'' of trading, said Larry Wachtel, first vice
president at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   While analysts noted that the market may be overplaying the
impact the figure is likely to have on Wall Street, this week's
trade report will come just ahead of a quarterly triple witching
hour involving a group of expiring options and futures on stock
indexes.
   The past couple of witching hours have been relatively
uneventful with the adoption of new procedures designed to spread
out the impact of last-minute maneuvering by computer program
traders.
   The transportation sector was the only arena to post a clear
trend. Airline stocks were up across the board amid reports that a
number of carriers plan to tighten restrictions on discount fares.
Allegis rose 1] to 79|, AMR rose 1] to 42], Delta was up 1] to 47|,
and NWA Inc. was up ~ to 43}.
   First RepublicBank fell { to 1\ amid reports that it will seek a
federal bailout. It is Texas' largest bank holding company.
   Traders complained that the technology sector failed to help
establish a positive trend for the day. Digital Equipment fell 2{
to 116\ and IBM was down 1| to 113~.
   Federated Department Stores fell \ to 65} as Macy and Campeau
continue to battle for control of the retail giant.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
0.21 to 149.85. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down 0.67 at 296.27.
