<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-GeneralMills     03-15 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-General Mills,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Mills Reports Sharp Third-Quarter Earnings Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Mills Inc. said its earnings jumped
25.5 percent in the third quarter of its fiscal year, prompted
largely by growth in its consumers foods division.
   Earnings in the 3 months ended Feb. 28 totaled $71.4 million, or
83 cents per share, compared with $56.9 million, or 64 cents per
share a year ago.
   Revenues increased 10 percent, to $1.44 billion from $1.31
billion in the same period last year, the company said in a
statement.
   For the first three quarters, earnings totaled $228.2 million,
or $2.60 per share, on sales of $4.33 billion, compared with $185.9
million, or $2.09 per share, on $3.84 billion in the 1986 period.
   Both periods benefited from an accounting change that resulted
in a $5.8 million gain in the third quarter and a $17.3 million
gain for the nine-month period, the company said.
   Chairman Bruce Atwater said good volume growth in consumer
foods, strong performance by key restaurant concepts and
significant productivity gains led to a 15 percent cumulative gain
in operating profits.
   Year-to-date results also benefited from the effective tax rate
declining to 40.3 percent from 48.4 percent last year, primarily
reflecting the effect of Federal Tax Reform, he said.
   Consumer Foods achieved a 2 percent increase in domestic package
food volume in the third quarter, leading to sales and operating
profit gains of 7 percent and 8 percent, respectively, Atwater said.
   Restaurant results in the third quarter showed gains in sales
and operating profits of 14 percent and 11 percent, respectively.
   ``These results reflect strong performance by Red Lobster
seafood restaurants, where efforts to increase lunch business
helped boost customer traffic over 5 percent above last year's
comparable quarter and the successful expansion of The Olive Garden
Italian restaurants,'' Atwater said.
</TEXT>
