<2ND_LINE>BC-3M Settlement,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>3M To Pay Lion's Share of $8 Million Settlement In Fatal Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing Co. has
paid $7 million of an $8 million settlement to the families of
three men who died in an industrial accident in 1984, lawyers for
the parties said today.
   The remaining $1 million of the settlement was paid by the
McDowell-Davis Co., a Milan, Ill., contracting firm 3M had hired to
clean out a large chemical holding tank at its plant in Cordova,
the lawyers said.
   The three men, McDowell-Davis owner Carl McDowell, 37, of Milan;
and his employees Daniel Walker, 27, of East Moline; and Scott
Syverson, 27, of Davenport, Iowa, were overcome by nitrogen gas
when they entered the 10,000-gallon tank on April 5, 1984,
according to both attorneys.
   The tank had held magnetic oxide, a chemical used to coat
recording tapes, and was supposed to be empty, said Mary Minella, a
Chicago attorney who represented the victims' families.
   But Chicago attorney Fred Schulz, who represented 3M in the
case, said the men had not checked for danger before entering the
tank.
   ``The workers who went in didn't do anything to check whether it
was safe or not,'' Schulz said. ``They just popped right in the
tank and unfortunately died.''
   The families received the checks on Friday, one week after the
settlement was entered into before U.S. District Court Judge
Nicholas J. Bua, Ms. Minella said.
</TEXT>
