<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Quaker-ArcticCircle     03-15 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Quaker-Arctic Circle,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quaker Wants To Sell Arctic Circle Holdings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Quaker State Corp. is trying to sell its
100 Arctic Circle restaurants in nine Western states, including
Utah, a company spokesman says.
   ``I will confirm talks are going on ... But I'm just not going
to get into it any further,'' said Benton H. Faulkner. ``It (Arctic
Circle) just didn't fit our mainstream, marketing automotive oil
and other automotive after-market products and services.''
   Faulkner said Monday that Quaker is planning to keep the
Minit-Lube chain, which was originally affiliated with Arctic
Circle Inc. Most of the Minit-Lube centers are in the western
United States.
   Gary Roberts, an Arctic Circle official at the company's Salt
Lake City headquarters, said Arctic Circle Restaurants are in Utah,
California, Idaho, Nevada, Oregon, Washington, Wyoming, Montana and
Nebraska.
   Quaker State purchased Arctic Circle and its 90-service-center
Minit-Lube chain in November 1985 from J.R. Edwards, son of Arctic
Circle founder Don Carlos Edwards, and five other partners.
   The number of Arctic Circle restaurants have remained at about
100 since 1985, said Faulkner.
   Minit-Lube outlets recently numbered 261, up from 98 at the end
of 1985, he added.
   Quaker State markets consumer automotive products and produces
lubricants, fuels and automotive lighting equipment.
</TEXT>
