<1ST_LINE>u f PM-SuddenAcceleration 1stLd-Writethru   03-15 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudden Acceleration, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0022,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NHTSA Opens Acceleration Probe of Honda Acura Legend, Austin Rover
Sterling</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: CORRECTS 9th graf, bgng: Typically Acura, to show that motor
races when shifted into drive or reverse, sted park or reverse;
also moved on general news wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 150 complaints of sudden acceleration
have prompted the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration to
open an investigation of the Honda Acura Legend and Austin Rover
Sterling.
   The agency said Monday the investigation covers 62,500 1986-1988
Acura Legends and Austin Rover Sterlings with automatic shifts. The
Austin Rover Sterling uses the same mechanical components as the
Legend.
   The new investigation brings to seven the number of sudden
acceleration probes being conducted by NHTSA. Five of the
investigations involve imported vehicles.
   American Honda, through spokesman Bob Butorac in Gardena,
Calif., declined to comment specifically on the NHTSA
investigation, saying it would be inappropriate ``because we simply
haven't heard anything yet.''
   ``We've checked every vehicle in which that incident (sudden
acceleration) was reported, (and) never found any mechanical or
electrical defect that could have caused it,'' Butorac said.
   He declined to say what could have brought on the sudden
acceleration incidents in the absence of a mechanical or electrical
cause.
   NHTSA has received 147 complaints of sudden acceleration in the
cars, resulting in 82 accidents, 11 injuries and no fatalities.
   The Center for Auto Safety, a Washington-based public-issues
group, had petitioned NHTSA to open an engineering analysis of the
alleged throttle problems.
   Typically, Acura Legend owners report their cars idle normally
in park, but race out of control when shifted into either drive or
reverse, said the center, a private organization often at odds with
the auto industry and its regulators.
   NHTSA has conducted three investigations into another Honda
model, the Accord, without ordering a recall, the center said.
   The center said it has reports of at least 120 Accord sudden
acceleration accidents resulting in three deaths.
   Honda recalled 4,500 of its 1988 Civics in November because of
speed fluctuation when the cars were idling, the center said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
