<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market held at modestly lower levels
today in dull, quiet trading.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 3.82 points to
2,046.25 at 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 9 to 8 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 746 up, 656 down and
511 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 93,580,000 million shares.
   Analysts said trading was lackluster, with institutional
investors showing little interest in the market.
   Traders have cited Thursday's release of merchandise trade
figures for January and the year's first ``triple witching hour''
as reasons for staying on the sidelines, but some analysts are
skeptical of the strategy.
   ``There is a mood in the street of reluctance to make
commitments'' prior to the two events, a sentiment that also
dampened activity in the previous session, said Lew Smith, a
technical analyst at Bear Stearns & Co.
   While activity also slowed ahead of the release of the trade
figures in the previous two months, Smith said that ``when
something becomes the thing to do, it loses its relevance.''
   The market needed only half an hour to respond to the trade
figures in recent months, said Larry Wachtel, first vice president
at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., who said investors are using
the numbers as an excuse to ``sit on their rear ends.''
   While analysts indicated the market may be overplaying the
impact the figures are likely to have on Wall Street, this week's
trade report will come just ahead of a quarterly triple witching
hour involving a group of expiring options and futures on stock
indexes.
   The past couple of witching hours have been relatively
uneventful with the adoption of new procedures designed to spread
out the impact of last-minute maneuvering by computer program
traders.
   The transportation sector was the only arena to post a clear
trend. Airline stocks were up across the board amid reports that a
number of carriers plan to tighten restrictions on discount fares.
Allegis rose 1\ to 79{, AMR rose 1[ to 42[, Delta was up 1\ to 47{,
and NWA Inc. was up ~ to 43}.
   First RepublicBank fell ] to 1]. Texas' largest bank holding
company said it might seek a federal bailout.
