<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Britain-Budget 1stLd-Writethru a0643 03-15 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0643,0640</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to update with more quotes, details.
Picks up 9th graf pvs ``Despite buoyant... '' Edits thereafter to
tighten; also moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Parliamentary Uproar Over Tax Cut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury chief Nigel Lawson announced Britain's
first budget surplus in nearly 20 years today and was shouted down
by opposition legislators in one of the unruliest annual budget
presentations in parliamentary history.
   The deputy speaker twice suspended the proceedings during
Lawson's speech, and opposition socialist Laborites chanted
``Shame, Shame'' as he announced huge tax cuts for the rich.
   Lawson said he was slashing the top tax bracket from 60 percent
to 40 percent.
   A Scottish legislator, Alec Salmond, was expelled after calling
the budget an ``obscenity,'' with tax cuts instead of extra
spending on health and welfare services. Lawson's speech was halted
while legislators voted overwhelmingly to expel Salmond.
   Lawson reduced the basic rate of tax from 27 percent to 25
percent, and cut Britain's six tax brackets to just two _ 25
percent and 40 percent. The 40 percent top tax rate _ down from a
60 percent top bracket _ will be payable on income over 19,300
pounds ($35,700) a year.
   The measures were the most sweeping changes since Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher came to power on a platform of cutting taxes,
encouraging private enterprise and curbing inflation and state
spending.
   Lawson announced last autumn the size of the $290 billion budget
for the fiscal year ending in 1989. Today, armed with the battered
leather budget box, the chancellor disclosed how the government
will raise the money.
   Lawson, declaring Conservative government has transformed the
British economy, announced a surplus of 3 billion pounds ($5.5
billion) in the budget.
   ``Tax breaks for the rich, poll tax (a new property tax) for the
poor and nothing in it for the health service _ it's an absolute
and utter obscenity,''' shouted Salmond, of the Scottish National
Party.
   His expulsion went ahead after a vote that delayed Lawson's
speech for 12 minutes. The two other Scottish nationalists in the
650-member Commons walked out in sympathy.
   As the session resumed, Laborites murmured restively as Lawson
continued to list tax cuts. The opposition broke into a new uproar,
amid shouts of ``rich man's budget.'' Conservative legislators,
opposite the Laborites from the facing green leather benches,
yelled ``Quiet'' and ``Sit Down.''
   The proceedings then were suspended a second time.
   Parliamentary officials hustled four uniformed nurses out of the
public gallery after they shouted slogans in defense of
state-funded health care. ``The National Health Service is not safe
in your hands. Thanks a lot Thatcher,'' one shouted.
   Despite buoyant revenues and economic growth, today's budget was
clouded by a split between Mrs. Thatcher and Lawson on how to
handle the soaring British pound.
   Even with eve-of-budget hesitancy in currency markets, the pound
finished at $1.85 on Monday, up 8 cents in a week, and at 3.08 West
German marks, well above the 3-mark level central to Lawson's
strategy of keeping a rein on sterling. A high pound hurts British
exports.
   Mrs. Thatcher last week ruled out such intervention as immediate
pound sales by the Bank of England and lower interest rates to
depress sterling on the grounds that the moves would fuel inflation.
   A budget focusing on tax reform rather than huge giveaways would
likely be another boost for the pound.
   The budget surplus is due partly to higher-than-anticipated
revenues from increased wages and company profits. In line with a
string of trim, low deficit budgets since Mrs. Thatcher won power
in 1979, Lawson originally predicted a $7.4 billion deficit in
1988-89, and revised that to $1.85 billion last autumn.
</TEXT>
