<2ND_LINE>AM-General Dynamics,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Dynamics Establishes Satellite-Launching Subsidiary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLAYTON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Dynamics Corp. announced Tuesday it
had established a commercial satellite-launch subsidiary in San
Diego.
   General Dynamics Commercial Launch Services Inc. will provide
worldwide marketing, business development, mission analysis and
mission management services needed for launching U.S. and foreign
satellites, said Herbert F. Rogers, General Dynamics president.
   ``We made a very strong commitment to the satellite-launching
business last summer when we decided to produce 18 Atlas@Centaurs
(launch vehicles) for the commercial marketplace,'' Rogers said.
``The establishment of General Dynamics Commercial Launch Services
further reinforces this commitment.''
   Jack Isabel, a General Dynamics spokesman, said the company's
main competitors in commercial-satellite launching would be
McDonnell Douglas Corp., Martin Marietta Corp. and Arianespace, the
commercial arm of the European Space Agency.
   He said China and Japan also had entered the market.
   Dennis R. Dunbar, formerly director of commercial launch
services at the company's space systems division, has been named
vice president and managing director of the new wholly owned
subsidary.
</TEXT>
