<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 2005EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CBOELawsuit     03-15 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CBOE Lawsuit,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investors Sue CBOE on Stock Index Options October Crash
Performance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York investment partnership has filed a
class action lawsuit against the Chicago Board Options Exchange,
alleging it was responsible for millions of dollars of losses
during the October market crash.
   The lawsuit, filed Friday in U.S. District Court in Chicago,
also names the Options Clearing Corp., which processes all
securities options trades in the nation.
   The investment partnership, M&M, sued on behalf of the more than
1,000 customers it said traded in excess of $40 million worth of a
November series of stock options on the Standard & Poor's 100 stock
index.
   The investors contend the exchange violated its rules by not
halting trade in stock index options in a more timely fashion.
   It said the exchange operated a ``fraud and deceit upon the
plaintiffs'' by failing to maintain a fair and equitable market.
   Exchange spokesman Warren Moulds said it ``won't comment on
pending litigation.''
   George Hender, executive vice president of the clearing
corporation, said he couldn't comment because he had not seen the
lawsuit.
   The lawsuit contends that on the morning of Oct. 20, the day
after the crash, M&M put in an order to buy November put options.
   A put option gives the buyer the right to sell stock index
contracts at a set price before the expiration date.
   The system in use at the exchange requires that opening trades
be rotated among the various contracts, and that free trading
begins only when the rotation is completed, the lawsuit said.
   The average length of the opening rotation is 12 to 15 minutes,
it said, but in the hectic aftermath of Black Monday, opening
rotation took 2 hours and 30 minutes.
   By the time M&M's contracts were executed, prices ``were
arbitrarily high and grossly inflated,'' the lawsuit contends.
   ``Once they placed that order, they couldn't withdraw it,'' said
attorney Leigh R. Lasky, who represents M&M. ``They were locked
in.''
   The lawsuit contends that for the investors to have broken even,
the Dow Jones Industrial Average would have had to plunge an
additional 50 percent by Nov. 20, the expiration date of the
options.
   M&M invested $23,400 and lost 90 percent of it, Lasky said
Tuesday. The class of investors, which had put up more than $40
million, probably lost close to 90 percent, too, he said.
   The lawsuit asks that the investors be reimbursed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
