<1ST_LINE>r f AM-NewComputers     03-15 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Computers,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unisys, AT&T, NCR Introduce Computers; IBM Shows Software</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unisys Corp., AT&T and NCR Corp. unveiled
computers Tuesday and IBM said it was making a version of the
popular Unix operating system available on its largest mainframes.
   The announcement by International Business Machines Corp. was
another acknowledgment of the growing popularity of Unix, a kind of
internal traffic cop for computers that was invented by American
Telephone & Telegraph Co.
   IBM's version of Unix is called AIX and is now available on
computers ranging from the top of its personal computer line all
the way up to its mainframes. Each computer also has its own
operating system.
   Unisys announced additions to its 1100 family of mainframe
computers. It said the 2200-400 family was a group of mid-range
mainframes offering a four-fold improvement in the amount of
performance for the price along with 70 percent less space, power
and cooling needs.
   The Unisys computers, including some data storage and other
extras, will range in price from $178,000 to $953,000 and will be
available between the end of this year and the second half of 1989.
   NCR introduced the System 10000, which it called a family of
mid-range, multi-user computers ranging in price from $31,000 to
$227,000. All will be available this year. The computers are
intended to have terminals hooked up to them.
   AT&T announced a new personal computer, the 6300 WorkGroup
System, that runs Microsoft Corp.'s DOS operating system. It said
the computer ranges in price from $1,400 to $2,100 and is available
now. AT&T also sells more powerful personal computers ranging in
price up to $10,400.
</TEXT>
