<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 2115EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-CableTVSwap     03-15 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Cable TV Swap,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Times Mirror, Partnership Plan Cable TV Swap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Times Mirror Co. said it has agreed with a
partnership of United Artists Communications Inc. and
Tele-Communications Inc. to swap cable televison systems in several
states.
   Neither Times Mirror nor the partnership put a value on the deal
Tuesday, but analysts estimated it would be worth about $740
million, based on an average price of $2,000 per subscriber.
   The companies had announced tentative plans for the exchange in
early October, but the details weren't worked out until now, Times
Mirror said.
   Times Mirror will turn over to the partnership cable systems
serving about 185,000 customers in the Arizona communities of
Phoenix, Tempe, Chandler, Mesa, Paradise Valley, Fountain Hills,
Nogales, Bullhead City, Casa Grande and Lake Havasu.
   In exchange, Times Mirror will receive systems with a similar
number of subscribers in Taunton and North Attleboro, Mass.;
Brookhaven, N.Y.; Decatur, Ill.; Zanesville, Ohio; Reno and Carson
City, Nev.; and South Lake Tahoe, Calif.
   Times Mirror also agreed that it will acquire the Rock Island,
Ill., cable system of Tele-Communications for an undisclosed price.
That also was part of the October tentative agreement.
   The systems being received by the partnership are in areas of
projected high growth, while the systems being received by Times
Mirror largely are in areas whose subscribership is expected to
remain relatively stable but whose cash flow exceeds the industry
average.
   Tele-Communications and United Artists, both based in Denver,
are the nation's largest and third-largest cable TV operators, with
5.5 million and 2.3 million subscribers, respectively.
   Times Mirror, based in Los Angeles, is a media conglomerate
whose flagship is the Los Angeles Times newspaper. It has about
870,000 cable subscribers.
</TEXT>
