<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     03-15 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained against most major currencies
Tuesday in reaction to weakness in the British pound. Gold prices
also rose.
   Republic National Bank of New York said gold was bid at $446 a
troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up from $441.90 an ounce late Monday.
   The British pound rose sharply during a budget announcement by
Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson, who announced Britain's
first budget surplus in nearly 20 years and a sweeping tax reform.
   Later, though, the pound fell back as investors cashed in on
paper profits and word that the Bank of England was selling
sterling to stem its rise.
   As sterling fell, the dollar benefited, said Frank Conte, vice
president for foreign exchange in the New York office of Barclays
Bank PLC.
   Gold and silver strengthened in a speculative run-up. Traders
said the peg for gold's rise was word of increased tension between
the United States and Panama.
   In late London trading, the British pound was quoted at $1.8570,
down from $1.8575 Monday. Later, in New York, the pound was quoted
at $1.8455, down from $1.8540.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before it begins in Europe, the
dollar rose 0.02 yen to a closing 127.25. Later in London, the
dollar was quoted at 127.10 yen. At the end of the trading day in
New York, the dollar rose to 127.38 yen from 126.78 late Monday.
   Other dollar rates late Tuesday in New York, compared with late
Monday, included: 1.6699 West German marks, up from 1.6629; 1.3805
Swiss francs, up from 1.3718; 1.2539 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2572; 5.6660 French francs, up from 5.6395; and 1,237.00 Italian
lire, up from 1,231.25.
   Other dollar rates late Tuesday in Europe, compared with late
Monday, included: 1.6650 West German marks, up from 1.6645; 1.3760
Swiss francs, up from 1.3693; 5.6605 French francs, up from 5.6375;
1.8705 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8645; 1,232.40 Italian lire, up
from 1,227.87; and 1.2564 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2577.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $443.50 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $441.00. In Zurich, the late bid price
was $442.50, up from $441.50 late Monday. On the Commodity Exchange
in New York, gold bullion for current delivery was bid at $446.30,
up from $441.90 late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.54 to close at a bid of
$443.27 an ounce.
   Silver was quoted in London Tuesday at a bid price of $6.25 a
troy ounce, up from Monday's $6.22. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery was bid at $6.365 an ounce, up from
$6.24 late Monday.
</TEXT>
