<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AutoSales Bjt   03-15 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0693</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Domestic Car and Truck Sales Up 6.3 Percent in Early March From
1987</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to fix numbering sequence.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Led by a generous jump in purchases of Ford Motor
Co. vehicles, sales of domestic cars and light trucks rose 6.3
percent in early March from a year ago, automakers reported Tuesday.
   Industry-leader General Motors Corp., however, did not share the
strong sales increases enjoyed by No. 2 Ford and incentive-heavy
Chrysler Corp.
   ``I'm surprised how strong sales were considering that some
consumers had moved their (March) purchases into February in
expectation of sales incentives expiring,'' said industry analyst
Ron Glantz of Montgomery Securities Inc. in San Francisco.
   Ford's combined domestic car and light truck sales were the
highest for early March since 1979, Ford said.
   Ford's domestic car sales jumped 21.4 percent to 68,859 in early
March from 50,407 a year ago. Ford held 32.5 percent of the
domestic car market, up from 27.7 percent a year ago.
   Ford's light truck sales rose 18.1 percent to 46,073 in early
March from 34,685 a year ago. Ford's share of that market improved
to 39.5 percent from 37.4 percent a year ago.
   Despite its incentives, GM's domestic car sales fell 13 percent
from early March a year ago and its light truck sales dropped 1.5
percent, GM reported.
   Glantz and other analysts blamed the end-of-February expiration
date of most of GM's incentive programs for its strong February
showing and ensuing weakness in early March.
   GM later extended the buyer lures into the spring, but only
after many consumers had hurried to take advantage of the discounts
before they ended. At the same time, Ford sweetened its incentives
in early March, helping its sales.
   The eight companies that build cars and trucks in the United
States sold 328,437 in the nine selling days from March 1-10, up
from 274,626 in eight days a year ago.
   Sales have improved in each of the seven sales period so far in
1988 compared with the first quarter of 1987, when showrooms were
empty because buyers made their pre-tax reform purchases at the end
of 1986.
   The percentage that sales fell or increased is a comparison of
average daily sales during the period, not of the straight numbers
of vehicles sold in early March this year and last year.
   Automakers sold 211,772 domestic cars in early March, up 3.5
percent from 181,820 a year ago, and 116,665 light trucks, up 11.7
percent from 92,806 a year ago.
   Despite the addition of new mid-size models, GM's domestic car
sales fell to 95,372 from 97,487 a year ago. GM's light truck sales
fell slightly to 42,489, or 4,721 a day, from 38,327, or 4,790 a
day, in early March 1987.
   GM's share of the domestic car market fell nearly 9 percentage
points in early March to 45 percent from 53.6 percent a year ago.
GM lost nearly 5 points of share in the light truck market at 36.4
percent, down from 41.3 percent ago year ago.
   Sales of Chrysler domestic cars rose 18.3 percent to 34,667 from
26,046 a year ago. Sales of Chrysler domestic light trucks jumped
24.1 percent to 25,287 from 18,108 a year ago.
   The No. 3 automaker held 16.4 percent of the domestic car
market, up from 14.3 percent a year ago, and 21.7 percent of the
light truck market, up from 19.5 percent a year ago.
   Together, the Big Three held 93.9 percent of the domestic car
market, down from 95.7 percent a year ago, and 97.6 percent of the
light truck market, down from 98.2 percent in early March 1987.
   Among the remaining companies, leader Honda Motor Co. reported a
71.9 percent jump in sales of cars built at its Marysville, Ohio,
factory. Toyota Motor Corp. domestic car sales rose 97.3 percent.
   Nissan Motor Corp. domestic car sales fell 19.7 percent from a
year ago but its domestic truck sales rose 48.5 percent. Volkswagen
of America's domestic car sales dropped 18.6 percent.
</TEXT>
