<2ND_LINE>AM-USG Proxy,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Desert Partners Mounts Proxy Fight for Directors' Seats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Desert Partners L.P. has begun a
soliciting proxies from shareholders for the election of
directorships of USG Corp., which recently spurned an unsolicited
$1.9 billion buyout offer from the investor group.
   Desert Partners, the company's largest shareholder with 9.8
percent of the stock, is fielding a rival slate for the six seats
at stake in the upcoming election. USG has 15 directors.
   Earlier this month, USG rejected Desert Partners' $42-a-share
buyout offer and said it was considering defense strategies that
might include the sale of a major block of USG stock to a third
party to block an unfriendly takeover.
   The proxy battle by Desert Partners, which is headed by Texas
oilmen Jack E. Brown and Cyril Wagner Jr., will climax May 11 at
USG's annual meeting in its headquarters city of Chicago.
   USG's stock closed at $35.87{ a share, down 25 cents in New York
Stock Exchange trading.
   Desert Partners said in its proxy statement that even if it wins
all six seats, it still would not control the building materials
company.
   ``However, a vote in favor of the election of the Desert
Partners nominees should indicate your support for the offer,'' the
proxy statement read.
   Shareholders will receive two proxy statements, one from the
company and the other from Desert Partners.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
